[Amit Varma]: Madhavan, welcome to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, thanks for having me.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:55.000
[Amit Varma]: There's so much I want to talk to you about and some of those like constitutionalism

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and the state of our republic are subjects that I have continuously explored in this episode

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
[Amit Varma]: with other guests to the point that some of my questions will actually seem a clichÃ© to my listeners.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, before we get to those heavy subjects, you know, this is the first time we've met.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
[Amit Varma]: I want to start off by getting to know you a little better.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about your life. You know, where were you born? Where did you grow up?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
[Guest]: Okay. Early life, fairly boring. So I'll just keep it very short.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
[Guest]: My dad was a mid-level bureaucrat, not an IAS.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
[Guest]: And I grew up in Delhi. A bit in, he decided to retire and go back to his hometown.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
[Guest]: So a bit of the schooling in Palghar.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:39.000
[Guest]: Then the usual thing that people of my age did in those days, if you were good in maths, you tried for engineering.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:47.000
[Guest]: So I went to an IIT, did four years of IIT, largely played bridge there, decided not to continue engineering.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:55.000
[Guest]: So default option, go and do an MBA. So I went to IMCal, did my MBA, worked for a year,

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:03.000
[Guest]: thought that I wanted to get into academics. At some time, I had missed the usual deadlines for applying to the US.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:11.000
[Guest]: And one of my professors at IMCal was calling me. So went back to IMCal, did a PhD, mainly in operations,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
[Guest]: but my secondary was finance. And in fact, I had got some good advice.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
[Guest]: This is mid-90s. There was none of these logistics companies and Uber and all this stuff.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:29.000
[Guest]: So the advice was that you might like doing quantitative methods and operations, but there are no jobs.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:36.000
[Guest]: So do something which is related to either marketing or finance, because finally you need to make a living.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:42.000
[Guest]: So that was my secondary. Finished that, landed up in Bombay because jobs are in Bombay.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
[Guest]: Got a job with a company called ICICI Securities, or it was called ISEC then, in the market side.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:59.000
[Guest]: Started in equities, equity research. At that time, ISEC was a joint venture between ICICI and JP Morgan.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:05.000
[Guest]: The joint venture broke. The JP Morgan took away the debt team largely.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: And I was looking at banking and the economy, so they moved me to the interest rate side.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.000
[Guest]: So I was doing interest rate research there. So I was in ISEC for about four and a half years.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
[Guest]: Then I moved to Bank of America in Bombay. Similar stuff, interest rates and currency.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:29.000
[Guest]: Moved to Singapore in early 2004. Was there for a year doing Southeast Asian currencies.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:38.000
[Guest]: And that was the professional part. Parallelly what happened was, in 96, which is when I joined ISEC,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:45.000
[Guest]: I met a person called Madhukar, who was flatmates with a colleague of mine.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.000
[Guest]: And Madhukar had started in ISEC. He had moved to ICICI. So we used to hang out.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
[Guest]: And Madhukar had started volunteering with Pratham and started full time.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: I used to hang out with the Pratham gang. I guess you know Pratham.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:01.000
[Unknown]: Of course, the education.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
[Guest]: One of the largest ones. They were very small then.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
[Guest]: And of course, we were in touch. We used to share a flat for a while.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Guest]: Then I was doing my banking career and Madhukar decided to move full time into the education,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
[Guest]: not-for-profit space. And he moved to Premji Foundation.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:27.000
[Guest]: And he was pushing for the, they were actually trying to get the right to education constitution amendment done.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[Guest]: When they discovered that MPs have no research support at all.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
[Guest]: Because they were trying to talk to MPs and many of them didn't know.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: So Madhukar came up with this idea of PRS and he was bouncing it off me.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.000
[Guest]: And of course, I mean, anybody, I mean, I'm an MBA, right?

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:52.000
[Guest]: So anybody asks advice on anything, I mean, I will give some random gyan.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:58.000
[Guest]: So I was doing that. Over a period of time, I got intrigued. I got interested.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:05.000
[Guest]: And I had moved to Singapore. Madhukar had moved to the U.S. to do a one-year course at the Kennedy School.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: And then he was at the World Bank. And I had done a visit to the U.S. as part of my job at Bank M.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.000
[Guest]: And I had met him. He was at Harvard then.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:20.000
[Guest]: I'd come back. Then one day I thought, OK, this sounds very interesting.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: This sounds worthwhile. I was also getting a bit, by that time, I was getting intellectually bored.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.000
[Guest]: It was otherwise the job was good. I had got enough variety.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
[Guest]: But I was doing more versions of similar things.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest]: So I had done in because I cannot complain that in those almost ten, nine and a half years, I'd actually started with equities.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:53.000
[Guest]: I'd done power sector, banking sector, then interest rates, Indian interest rates, then Indian currency markets, then moved to Singapore, three other countries.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:03.000
[Guest]: Reasonable amount. But at the end of the day, if you had woken me at 3 a.m. and asked me, OK, what is the M3 growth of Indonesia in 1973?

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
[Guest]: I probably would have told you and gone back to sleep because that's what I'm doing.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest]: I thought, OK, this seems interesting and it seems something worthwhile trying out.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:19.000
[Guest]: So I called him up from Singapore to U.S. Is the plan still on? Madhukar said, of course, yes.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:25.000
[Guest]: I said, would you like me to join you? He said, are you serious? I said, yeah. He said, OK, that'll be great.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: So soon after I left my job, I came back to India. Madhukar had finished.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.000
[Guest]: He came back to India and that's how we started off PRS.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Guest]: So that's the in a way the PRS thinking and bouncing of the idea started.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
[Guest]: I don't exactly remember when, but must be 2002 to 2003 sort of a thing.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: There were some emails which I can't find now because I used to use Hotmail then and my account is dead.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:01.000
[Guest]: So I can't get those emails. But so I don't know the dates, but it was around that time.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:13.000
[Guest]: And 2005 September is when we formally started in the sense the day the daily going into office started September 2005.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Awesome. And even I had a Hotmail account which no longer exists.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:23.000
[Amit Varma]: It's like an artifact. So I moved house recently and we were unpacking everything and we decided this time.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Bombay, you know, houses are small. So we decided we don't want clutter and we'll discard whatever we don't use.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
[Amit Varma]: But I realized that it can be difficult.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Like I found this first the Nokia first Nokia mobile phone I had with just buttons, obviously not a smartphone.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And my heart would not let me kind of let it go, you know, so these artifacts kind of stay with us.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Which year did you pass out from IIT Madras by the way?

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
[Amit Varma]: 90, 1990.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Amit Varma]: That's fascinating. That means we were actually on the campus at the same time in the sense I visited Madigra your festival.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Yes, in I think 89-90. I was in my first year of junior college then.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
[Guest]: I would have been there definitely.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so we would have kind of I remember taking part in a few things.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
[Amit Varma]: So and by the way, what was the M3 growth of Indonesia in 1973?

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
[Guest]: It's 16 years since I decided I'm not going to remember that.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
[Guest]: So I don't know.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm just kidding. So I want to go back a little bit to that sort of world that there was then.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, there's a nice video of you online where you talk about the pre-liberalization years and how it was so dominated by scarcity.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And that scarcity is a scarcity, not just of goods and services, but also in a sense of the intellectual stimulation we get.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Like in terms of the books available to us, you basically read whatever you can, right?

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:46.000
[Amit Varma]: In terms of music, you know, just putting together a mixtape of new music could be such an achievement and so on and so forth.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about the texture of your life outside of these biographical details, engineer, MBA and all.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Which, by the way, in those days to do an IIT, IIM combination meant that you were really super smart.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Amit Varma]: That's how we looked at it back then.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:01.000
[Unknown]: It was default.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Unknown]: Today it's way more common.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
[Amit Varma]: It was default.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[Amit Varma]: It's default today.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:09.000
[Amit Varma]: But I don't, you know, at that time, I remember it as, you know, like you almost used to resent those guys.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:10.000
[Amit Varma]: What do they think?

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:17.000
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about, you know, the texture of your life in the 80s growing up, what would you do in your free time?

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Like today, people don't think of me, you know, people think of me time as something that you have to make for yourself.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: Because otherwise we're looking into our smartphones and we're surrounded by things.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:27.000
[Guest]: We had a lot of boredom, right?

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest]: It was nice.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
[Guest]: I mean, now I think back, I think it was good that there was a lot of boredom.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest]: But I used to read a lot.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
[Guest]: Of course, I used to reread a lot simply because I didn't have new books.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest]: And we used to trade starting with Amar Chaitra Kathas because that's the only thing.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: In most of the kids around me, many of them did not read much.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: So on a trade, I could get only Amar Chaitra Kathas and not better books.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:58.000
[Guest]: But I think at least, I mean, you are, I guess, just you said, just said that you are in first year.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:12:59.000
[Guest]: So you're just a few years younger than me.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:00.000
[Guest]: I'm 47.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm almost 48.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Similar.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:10.000
[Guest]: So 80s and I guess till mid 90s, we all had this, in India, the only a few books available.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:12.000
[Guest]: So read.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
[Guest]: Luckily, my school, very interestingly, had a very decent library.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
[Guest]: It was a small school in Delhi, RK Puram, Ramja school.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
[Guest]: But the library was excellent.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: I don't know how that happened.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:25.000
[Guest]: I was there in 11th and 12th.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
[Guest]: They had the full Alistair Maclean.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:28.000
[Guest]: They had all the P.G.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:29.000
[Guest]: Woodhouse's.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
[Guest]: So the standard, I mean, we all had the same books, right?

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:32.000
[Guest]: We had the same books.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: And even during mugging up for my JEE, I managed to read about two novels a week.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: And it was only, it was fiction.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.000
[Guest]: I mean, I didn't read.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest]: At those days, other than textbooks, you didn't read, I mean, I didn't read nonfiction.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:54.000
[Guest]: But a lot of those and the librarian, librarians, I think, like kids who read.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Guest]: So officially the school had one library period a week when you go to get an issue.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
[Guest]: But I could walk in any time and get a new book.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Guest]: So we have seen you yesterday.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest]: So a lot of reading.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:12.000
[Guest]: I think that's actually the main predominant thing.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: And otherwise doing, I mean, errands, right?

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:25.000
[Guest]: I mean, you had to go once in 15 days to the Russian shop, stand in a queue and carry that rice, 15 kgs or 10 kgs, whatever they used to give us back home.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Amit Varma]: What's your world to MITI life?

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, I know this is a very personal question and I would not answer it, but what did you daydream of?

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.000
[Guest]: I don't even know.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't think I did much.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:39.000
[Guest]: Life was much about, I mean, I just went with the flow.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: I mean, as you could see, even in my pre-PRS days, more or less, it was like, okay, you are good at maths and sciences.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest]: I mean, which is like, I was fortunate to have whatever those genes or talents or whatever.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:59.000
[Guest]: And which meant you ended up mugging up writing some exam.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:00.000
[Guest]: So you go with the flow.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.000
[Guest]: I went to the IIT with the flow.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
[Guest]: Didn't like engineering too much.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Guest]: Ended up essentially four years bunking classes and playing bridge.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:14.000
[Guest]: And then decided, okay, and what are the default options in 1990?

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:21.000
[Guest]: At least in IIT Madras, about 60 or 70% of my class went to the US for a master's.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
[Guest]: And those days, MS meant you got scholarship, right?

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
[Guest]: Today, I believe you don't.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
[Guest]: Those days, everyone, I mean, nobody had money.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
[Guest]: So you went for a master's.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
[Guest]: The remaining went for MBA.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:37.000
[Guest]: A few guys who did not get either took up a job with the idea that they'll apply next year.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
[Guest]: I mean, okay, we weren't lucky this year.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
[Guest]: Nobody wanted to go for a job.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Guest]: So the flow was that I got into an IIM in the first attempt.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:47.000
[Guest]: I was lucky enough to do so.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Guest]: And I would actually attribute, I mean, having seen others and people who didn't get in also,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[Guest]: there is, in all these things, there is some amount of talent, there's some amount of hard work,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
[Guest]: and there is a reasonable amount of luck.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:03.000
[Guest]: So I would also attribute a bunch of it to luck.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Guest]: But I got in.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
[Guest]: So as you could see, it was like, I was just going with the flow.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
[Amit Varma]: One thing that fascinates me, and when I talk to guests of Our Vintage,

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Amit Varma]: what I enjoy exploring is how their views of the world evolved.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Because one, there is red paucity where we're all essentially reading the same books, right?

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Like the Woodhouses, and like you mentioned, the Alastair Maclean's.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Guest]: Sydney Sheldon.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Guest]: I don't even know why.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Today, I would not read a Sydney Sheldon because other things are available.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:37.000
[Guest]: But if only, you know, I still remember a vacation when I was marooned in an uncle's house.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
[Guest]: Because I had, this was after my 10th standard.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: So I was 15.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: And I had got some bad eczema and it had got infected.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest]: So we were on a vacation.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: So I was at their house when everyone else had gone off to meet some other uncle for lunch or something.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
[Guest]: And I was, I was otherwise, I didn't have a fever or anything.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
[Guest]: So I was limping around.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:00.000
[Guest]: I was at home.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: And I was at their place for five days.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
[Guest]: The only books available there.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's hilarious if I think back.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: And I read those.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: There are two sets of books.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
[Guest]: Because someone had visited and left them there.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
[Guest]: There was a set of Mills and Boones.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
[Guest]: So 15-year-old boy reading Mills and Boones.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: I never read them before.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
[Guest]: And there was Bhavan's journal.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:23.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:30.000
[Guest]: So between Mills and Boones and Bhavan's journal, I think I covered the spiritual spectra.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: So I read those.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Guest]: I mean, I could, I have read the first 20, 15 or 20 pages of James Joy Ulysses many, many times.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: Because I could never get past them.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.000
[Guest]: But that book was at home.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
[Amit Varma]: So every vacation, come back and try to read it.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, and that's also luck that if you find James Joyce at home, is it Ulysses, which is so hard to read?

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Or Dubliners, which is such a great and beautiful book.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's very weird that, like you mentioned, that if you had to choose.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, it almost seems arbitrary what books were available to us.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, My Calf has been a bestseller.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:07.000
[Guest]: Hitler's book has been a bestseller in India for decades.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Guest]: I have tried reading it. It's unreadable.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:09.000
[Guest]: It's unreadable.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I dropped it.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but why is it a bestseller?

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's some accidents of happenstance there and so on.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:21.000
[Amit Varma]: But the question I was coming at is, how does one arrive at a view of the world?

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, when I think of my teenage years and young adulthood and all of that, with so little exposure, you know.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And I was a son of a civil servant.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Amit Varma]: So for me, the state having the role that it does, that you look to it as a solution of all your problems.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
[Amit Varma]: You don't question it in any way.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:45.000
[Amit Varma]: You are, you know, naturally distrustful of markets, which, of course, weren't even really there in the 80s and so on and so forth.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And it took me a long, long time to actually get into adulthood, refine my view of the world, think deeper about things,

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Amit Varma]: have the access to books that, on all sides of the argument, which would help me kind of think these things through.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Amit Varma]: What was your view of the world during those years?

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, in the sense that at a later point in time, when, you know, 96, you started having those dialogues, you said with Madhukar.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:11.000
[Amit Varma]: And by 2005, you've set up PRS.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And these are clearly things that matter to you, that what is wrong in this country, what can one do?

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Amit Varma]: But are there threads of that before as well?

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, when do you start thinking about these things?

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And when you do, who are the writers or thinkers who really influence you?

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, I'm guessing Burke is one of them because you refer to him often in your talks.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But not too much.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
[Amit Varma]: In that context only.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.000
[Guest]: No, Burke, I mean, I have seen, I have not read much of Burke.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Guest]: I have read, like, very limited amount.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
[Guest]: I have not read any of his books, couple of these things.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
[Guest]: And I have come across them only post PRS.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:47.000
[Guest]: Right, right.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
[Guest]: So, I read a lot of newspapers.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
[Guest]: I mean, not a lot.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:53.000
[Guest]: It's interesting.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
[Guest]: My father had very weak eyes.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:05.000
[Guest]: So, one of my jobs from the time I was a kid, I think by the time I was eight or nine, was to read out the newspaper headlines to him.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:09.000
[Guest]: And if he wanted any story, he'll say, okay, read this, I'll read out the story.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.000
[Guest]: That was part of my job.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
[Guest]: Good part of that.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:18.000
[Guest]: And very funnily, he was not interested in sports at all or in business.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:22.000
[Guest]: So, we used to read the newspaper pages, stop after the editorial page.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:27.000
[Guest]: Because then the business page comes and the sports page comes.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:33.000
[Guest]: And I was interested in sports because of, I mean, I was young, I had brothers, I had an uncle who was interested.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:38.000
[Guest]: I remember the very first cricket series that I can think of.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:47.000
[Guest]: I've seen slightly before, but what I remember is the 77 series when we used to wake up at 5 a.m.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:21:00.000
[Guest]: When India went to Australia, and I still remember Gavaskar scored, I think, zeroes or single digits in the first innings, in the first three matches and a century in the second innings.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
[Guest]: And we lost the first two matches narrowly.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest]: We won the next two with a fairly large margin.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:10.000
[Guest]: The first two matches, I don't remember the sequence, one was by two wickets, one was by 16 runs.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
[Guest]: Wow.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:18.000
[Guest]: So, third and fourth, I think one was in innings and one was some 200 runs, I mean, it was fairly clear victories.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:22.000
[Guest]: And the fifth match was a close one, which we lost.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
[Guest]: And of course, it was a weekend Australia team because they had, there was a Kerry Packer.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.000
[Amit Varma]: World Series.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:29.000
[Guest]: Yeah, and it was Bob Simpson leading and Thompson was there.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:31.000
[Guest]: Lily wasn't, Thompson was there.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:33.000
[Guest]: So, that is an early memory.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
[Guest]: I was what, eight or something.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:44.000
[Guest]: So, I used to follow cricket, I used to read everything in the sports pages, including some sonnet club playing some other club or something else in Delhi.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:46.000
[Guest]: It'll come in a small thing in the newspaper.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
[Guest]: So, news was always there.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:53.000
[Guest]: Of course, when I went to Madras, the newspaper then was Hindu.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:56.000
[Guest]: And the Hindu crossword is a nice thing to do.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:58.000
[Guest]: So, we used to do that every morning.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.000
[Guest]: What else?

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:06.000
[Guest]: I actually, I mean, I can't even pinpoint, but always been fascinated, interested in politics, partly because my father was.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:10.000
[Guest]: And at home, there was a lot of discussion, though he worked for the government.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
[Guest]: He didn't like the government.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.000
[Guest]: I don't think he was a pro-market or something like that.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:23.000
[Guest]: But he was always, I think there was some, he was a rebel in some sense, though not outwardly.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
[Guest]: So, I guess some of that might have been an influence.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:28.000
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:35.000
[Guest]: So, the thing that you need the system, but always be suspicious and skeptical of the system.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:41.000
[Guest]: You need the system to work, but don't trust things to work because people will do various things.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:46.000
[Guest]: And of course, we had, I mean, I don't know how familiar you are with Delhi.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.000
[Guest]: So, we were initially in RK Puram.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:56.000
[Guest]: And then we had been rudely kicked out of RK Puram and moved to Janakpuri because he had bought a flat because he thought post-retirement he wanted one.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: And Indira Gandhi imposed the emergency and said, any government servant who has a house in Delhi has to move out of government accommodation.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:04.000
[Guest]: Wow.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:08.000
[Guest]: So, we moved to some, and that time in Janakpuri, there was nothing.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:10.000
[Guest]: So, we were thrown out.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.000
[Guest]: So, all those, I guess, like what's going on sort of a thing, right?

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
[Guest]: So, I don't know.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
[Guest]: I mean, I actually don't know what are these influences.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:22.000
[Guest]: Of course, hanging out with Madhukar, I was going to Pratham.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
[Guest]: I was seeing what these guys were doing, Madhav and gang.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:39.000
[Guest]: So, one of the things that has that influenced part of the decision was the idea that if I am getting into this space, I want to do a reasonably scale impact.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's no fun.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
[Guest]: I mean, more than anything else.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:49.000
[Guest]: And even today, I'm not belittling the smaller ones because all those matter.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:56.000
[Guest]: But if you're interested in scale impact, I can think only of two models, frankly, I mean, variations of two models.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:03.000
[Guest]: One is a low cost replicable system, which is what Pratham had started off with.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:07.000
[Guest]: They were trying to do Balwadis, which was preschools in Bombay.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:12.000
[Guest]: Then they were running in the first three years, they were running, I think, some 4000 of them.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:20.000
[Guest]: So they are like a small, even in a slum, a room or a Mandir or a Masjid or something, you need a 10 by 10 space.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.000
[Guest]: And the local kids come.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:25.000
[Guest]: And these are three or four year old kids before they go to school.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:31.000
[Guest]: The idea was that these kids have never, I mean, the parents have not gone to school, many of them.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
[Guest]: So they're not used to that concept.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:39.000
[Guest]: And when they are five or five and a half and they get to school, they can't sit in a place for four hours.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:42.000
[Guest]: They're not used to it. They're running around in the slum.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:47.000
[Guest]: So you get them habituated to at least learning something.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:56.000
[Guest]: And they trained what is called ninth class pass, essentially 10th class fail, local, typically young women.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:05.000
[Guest]: And they would be doing what people like us do in nursery school, which is singing songs, learning ABC with songs or one, two, three with songs.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:08.000
[Guest]: So you get some basic thing you're playing around, essentially.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.000
[Guest]: It's a play school plus.

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
[Guest]: Now, this was a cheap model. This was replicable.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:25.000
[Guest]: Or if I think in a different space, which I am very, I mean, even in our generation, 1990s, early 90s, the PC revolution,

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:32.000
[Guest]: I mean, I end up at phone at home and getting a, making a phone call was not easy.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:41.000
[Guest]: But when they opened it up to the markets and they said, OK, PCO, that's a scalable, replicable, sustainable model for those days.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.000
[Guest]: Of course, I mean, that has become obsolete because of better technology and cheaper technology.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:55.000
[Guest]: But it did its job. Or if I think about, let's say, access to toilets.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:05.000
[Guest]: A brilliant model. It is sustainable. They charge a nominal amount, which people can afford, and it can be set up.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.000
[Guest]: I mean, you get access to a clean loo.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:15.000
[Guest]: And I'm sure that enough poor people, I mean, not very, very poor, but somewhere in the poverty range who want a clean loo,

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Guest]: but they actually used to defecate in the open, in urban places, simply because they didn't have a choice.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:27.000
[Guest]: They were given the choice at a reasonable price. So, that's one model.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Guest]: The second thing is the state doing it because state has scale, the government has scale.

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:39.000
[Guest]: So, again, Sholam Chachalai versus, let's say, Swachh Bharat.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:45.000
[Guest]: Even education. Finally, it has to be government schools.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:53.000
[Guest]: I mean, there are what? I'm just making my guesses. There are about 2 crore kids per year in the younger age group.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:57.000
[Guest]: So, if you're saying 10 years of schooling, I'm not even saying 12.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: You're talking about something like 18 to 20 crore kids.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.000
[Guest]: It has to be the government system. Nobody else can do it.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:19.000
[Guest]: And incidentally, if you look at the budgets, the union budget plus state budgets together is, I think, about two and a half lakh crore per annum spent on school education.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:25.000
[Guest]: Just think of the two and a half lakh crore per annum.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:32.000
[Guest]: The richest philanthropists in India. I mean, that's more than the net worth.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:36.000
[Guest]: I mean, this every year. And this is our money. This is the tax money.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:41.000
[Guest]: So, if there is an impact to be done, it has to be done through these.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:45.000
[Guest]: And if you can bring in, and I'm sticking to education.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:55.000
[Guest]: If you have seen the ASER reports, year after year after year, they tell you that 50 percent of kids in class five can't read class two stuff.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:00.000
[Guest]: This was the first ASER report. This now, I mean, 50 plus minus, somewhere between 45 and 55.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:11.000
[Guest]: That number hasn't changed. If you can get that two and a half lakh crore of our money to be a bit more efficient and improve this target.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:18.000
[Guest]: Just think of the impact that makes. No individual can do that sort of impact. Individuals can do impact at the margin.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:27.000
[Guest]: But I would say the individual impact has to leverage the state scale to get the real impact.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: That would be my thinking. So, some of these things. And of course, when we looked at parliament, we said, OK, all these policies.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:41.000
[Guest]: Finally, the buck stops at parliament, not at the government. The buck stops at parliament.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:46.000
[Guest]: Because they are the people who are supposed to oversee the work of the government.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:59.000
[Guest]: Are they capable of doing it in terms of do they have the systems and processes and support systems which enables them to do it well?

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:08.000
[Guest]: If not, can we strengthen those and remove at least that bottleneck and see what happens?

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:13.000
[Guest]: That may not be a sufficient condition, but that is definitely a necessary condition.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:16.000
[Guest]: So, let's get that in. So, that was the thinking.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I have a number of broad questions which occur to me. And the first of those, of course, you mentioned is education.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And I completely agree with you that if you are going to do something at scale in that particular field, only the state can do it.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:32.000
[Amit Varma]: There's no option to that. And therefore, we have to make that as efficient as possible.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:41.000
[Amit Varma]: But orthogonally, there is also a situation where the state doesn't allow private entrepreneurs to function at all in this field.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:46.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, my position on education, and I've had episodes on this with Karthik Muralidharan and others,

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:52.000
[Amit Varma]: and my position has always been that let the state do what it is doing to get its act together on government schools.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:55.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, remove the restrictions, let private schools exist.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:00.000
[Amit Varma]: As it happens, private schools exist in a very underground, jugadu kind of way.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, various studies have shown that poor parents will often, you know, living in slums,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:10.000
[Amit Varma]: will often prefer to send their kid to like a budget private school rather than a free government school.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Kind of voting with their feet.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And there's another sort of sideways suggestion there that you do school vouchers where the government keeps spending.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:21.000
[Amit Varma]: But it's the parents who are empowered with the choice of which school their child goes to,

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:24.000
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, brings about a kind of accountability in schools.

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure you would broadly agree with these propositions.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:36.000
[Amit Varma]: But my question is that what it requires to make these things happen is really a change in the default mindset people have.

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:41.000
[Amit Varma]: That the state will do everything and anything outside that should be looked upon with suspicion.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Which was really the 70s, 80s kind of default mindset which still kind of persists today.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So, at one level, you can, you know, give rich analysis, you know, to MPs and politicians and so on.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:31:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And, again, you've been at pains to point out that very wisely you don't actually make policy suggestions per se.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:05.000
[Amit Varma]: You just give all the information and the knowledge so they can take an informed decision.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:13.000
[Amit Varma]: But do you sense that there is any change at all in this default kind of mindset of, you know, the state controlling everything?

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:18.000
[Guest]: Yes. I mean, I'll give you a concrete example. Air India got sold.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, finally.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:25.000
[Guest]: Okay. I mean, it had no reason to exist for the last 15 years at least.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
[Guest]: But finally, it got sold. Okay.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
[Guest]: I don't see any reason for today.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:36.000
[Guest]: Okay. Like, I live in Delhi. I know lots of people in Delhi who owns an MTNL mobile.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:37.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.000
[Guest]: Why does that exist? Okay.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:45.000
[Guest]: So, if you allowed only market forces, they would have shut down long back like many other mobile companies did.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:58.000
[Guest]: If you want, I mean, the only reason for having something like that is if they are good and efficient and they prevent a market monopoly or a duopoly.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
[Guest]: Okay. You want competition.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
[Guest]: Government provides one more.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:09.000
[Guest]: But sector after sector, we have seen that governments are not, that is not the strength of governments.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:11.000
[Guest]: And it's not just in India.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:14.000
[Guest]: It's the nature of government of businesses.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:20.000
[Guest]: Right. I mean, so there are some, so there are place, there is a space for government and there isn't.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:24.000
[Guest]: So even when you're talking about education, take higher education.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:25.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:32.000
[Guest]: In general, in most fields, the most preferred option is a government college.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:33.000
[Guest]: Engineering.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:36.000
[Guest]: If you want to go to law, you go to NLS Bangalore, right? Or whatever.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.000
[Guest]: I mean, you're not taking a private law school ahead of that.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:44.000
[Guest]: If a kid had a choice of every law school, the kid will go to NLS Bangalore.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:49.000
[Guest]: If the kid wanted to learn medicine and every choice will go to Ames Delhi.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:56.000
[Guest]: If you want, I mean, you'll go to DU or whatever, right? I mean, one of the DU better colleges or Bombay or whatever.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:02.000
[Guest]: So, you're not going to a private college as your first choice in most higher education.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:03.000
[Guest]: You're going to a government college.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:09.000
[Guest]: So, the government actually has done a better job than this private sector in higher education.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:13.000
[Guest]: And there have been private engineering colleges for a long time.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:19.000
[Guest]: It's not, at least, I'm not talking about the liberal arts colleges, which have sprung up more recently,

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:26.000
[Guest]: but medical and engineering started even when I went, I was taking my 12th class exams.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
[Guest]: So, the state has done well there.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:38.000
[Guest]: So, I would agree with you that there's no reason to clamp down on private sector, even in school things.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:47.000
[Guest]: You just, I mean, if you improve your quality and the kids start coming to you, you won the market game.

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:52.000
[Guest]: Why should you force somebody to come to you?

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:55.000
[Guest]: I mean, let the market decide that.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:07.000
[Guest]: But I don't see, I mean, politically, among the politicians, I actually don't see that much of suspicion of private spaces.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's good to know.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:13.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one response to buy these sort of the chosen institutes in higher education,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:17.000
[Amit Varma]: and I'm thinking out loud, you know, people will go to NLS or Ames rather than anything else,

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:22.000
[Amit Varma]: is that there are still many restrictions and many of these private engineering colleges

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:27.000
[Amit Varma]: and all these fly-by-night colleges that spring up are often kind of rather shady.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But if you look in recent years, you had like ISB, you know, coming up, which is quite excellent,

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.000
[Guest]: which is good, Ashoka for the liberal arts.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:40.000
[Guest]: Today, if a kid gets into, let's say, IIM Ahmedabad and ISB, where will that kid go?

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I think they'll go to IIM Ahmedabad because of received wisdom.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:49.000
[Amit Varma]: But actually, there are plenty of people, perhaps many of them from ISB who say that ISB is a step above.

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:54.000
[Guest]: Maybe, I'm not pulling it down, but at least IIM Ahmedabad is equal to ISB in people's perception.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:55.000
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:35:01.000
[Guest]: I mean, it's not like, okay, it is not like, let us say, in Delhi context,

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:08.000
[Guest]: getting into a DPS or a modern school versus your local Delhi government school.

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:09.000
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:11.000
[Guest]: It's not, I mean, they are roughly similar.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
[Amit Varma]: You're right by that entirely.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Here's the next broad sort of question I have that when it comes to the space of ideas,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I've kind of believed in recent years that there's no point going to the supply end of the political marketplace.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.000
[Amit Varma]: You go to the demand end of the political marketplace and change the incentives.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:34.000
[Amit Varma]: That if you just go to politicians and bureaucrats and sell them policies,

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:36.000
[Amit Varma]: which, of course, to clarify, is not what you're doing.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, it's a broader question I'm asking.

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:47.000
[Amit Varma]: But to attack the supply end and say that we'll get better decisions if we work on the politicians and bureaucrats.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And I feel that there, if change happens, it depends a little bit on luck.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
[Amit Varma]: It happens at a glacial pace, like with Air India.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:55.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm glad it's happened.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.000
[Amit Varma]: It's not just the little that has happened.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Whereas my sense is that the demand end is a problem.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Like Andrew Breitbart once said that politics is downstream of culture.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you just sort of change the culture first, like Gandhi, in fact, wanted to do.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:13.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, if you kind of change the culture first, then the incentives of politicians change completely.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And the incentives of bureaucrats even change completely because of what the politicians want.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And then real change can happen.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Is that something you've thought about?

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:28.000
[Guest]: So having worked fairly, I mean, at various levels, closely, not so closely, etc.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:33.000
[Guest]: With a wide range of politicians across every political party, both at center and states.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:34.000
[Guest]: I'm coming from that.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
[Guest]: And I've been doing this for 16 years now.

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:41.000
[Guest]: I still don't understand what are the incentives that drive them.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:42.000
[Guest]: It's a very.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, I, of course, as you know, had a markets background for eight years.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:47.000
[Guest]: So it was all 10 years.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:48.000
[Guest]: It was always OK.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.000
[Guest]: Incentives drive people's behavior.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
[Guest]: Well, I don't really think that is a complete answer.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:58.000
[Guest]: Of course, there is the drive to some extent.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:05.000
[Guest]: For example, if I if you actually characterize a politician in that thing, it is OK.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
[Guest]: What are his objectives?

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:09.000
[Guest]: I do in the next election.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:10.000
[Guest]: And what do we need for that?

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:11.000
[Guest]: I need two things.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:14.000
[Guest]: I need to get the party to give me a ticket.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.000
[Guest]: And I need after that people to vote me.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
[Guest]: And that's the only thing I'm bothered about.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:22.000
[Amit Varma]: In the middle, there's also I need to raise money for the next elections and.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
[Guest]: Yeah, money and all that.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:32.000
[Guest]: We do every Wednesday when parliament in session and every Thursday, we do sessions for MPs,

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:39.000
[Guest]: which is open to every MP and only two MPs so that there is Chetan House rules are maintained.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:44.000
[Guest]: Wednesdays, we get an expert to come and talk to them on a subject.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:49.000
[Guest]: And Thursdays, we look at bills which are coming up over the next week or the next month.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.000
[Guest]: And we discuss them in great detail.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
[Guest]: Actually, the discussion goes like, OK, look at this.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:57.000
[Guest]: There is an issue and a problem with this.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:38:02.000
[Guest]: The way this has been defined, because if you read this definition, this definition and this class together,

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.000
[Guest]: there's actually a contradiction.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:05.000
[Guest]: There's a problem.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:06.000
[Guest]: So we need to fix this.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:09.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, you'll have a law which will later land up in court.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:15.000
[Guest]: And let's at least, I'm not saying what you ought to do or what the law ought to have,

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.000
[Guest]: but the law at least should not have an ambiguity.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
[Guest]: I mean, we are all agreed on that.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:21.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
[Guest]: So that sort of a discussion happens.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:25.000
[Guest]: Clause by clause, we go through it.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:27.000
[Guest]: Wednesdays, we get in someone to come and talk.

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:35.000
[Guest]: And why would, OK, my classic example is about 10 years ago, when Abhijit Banerjee was not so famous then,

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:40.000
[Guest]: because it was before his Nobel, so people in the field knew him well.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:43.000
[Guest]: But I mean, he was not a household name in India.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
[Guest]: He was visiting Delhi.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:47.000
[Guest]: He comes to India, right.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.000
[Guest]: And we had requested him to come and do one of these.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.000
[Guest]: And he did.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:58.000
[Guest]: Why would, on a December, cold December morning, about 20 MPs take out an hour of their time,

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:02.000
[Guest]: which is a precious resource, which means they are not meeting constituents,

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:07.000
[Guest]: which means they are not signing some letters, getting admission to a hospital or a school

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:10.000
[Guest]: or something like that for somebody and meeting them and winning votes.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:18.000
[Guest]: We are spending an hour sitting in a room, listening to a professor of MIT, explaining why,

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:28.000
[Guest]: I mean, and my request to Abhijit was to say that, to explain how do we understand why some policies work

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:32.000
[Guest]: and why they don't, which is essentially what their core work is, right away.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:36.000
[Guest]: They use RCT and other methodologies, but behind that, why are they doing it?

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:37.000
[Guest]: So how do you even know?

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.000
[Guest]: Okay, we have pulled out a policy.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
[Guest]: Is this policy working or not?

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:42.000
[Guest]: People sit and listen.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
[Guest]: We have had many in the recent past.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
[Guest]: I mean, we do it every time.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:47.000
[Guest]: Why do they take that time out?

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:49.000
[Guest]: Nobody in the party cares.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:54.000
[Guest]: The boss in the party is not going to give them an extra probability of getting the ticket.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.000
[Guest]: Nobody in the constituency knows.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:00.000
[Guest]: In fact, they might say, why are you wasting your time there rather than fixing my road,

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
[Guest]: which is anyway not their job.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.000
[Guest]: So why do they do?

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:09.000
[Guest]: I think at somewhere, I mean, my own, this thing interacting one-on-ones many times,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:12.000
[Guest]: is they want to do the right thing.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.000
[Guest]: The question is, what is the right thing?

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.000
[Guest]: Of course, it's driven by your ideology.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:20.000
[Guest]: I mean, what you think is the right thing and what I think is the right thing may be different.

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:21.000
[Guest]: So we don't get into that.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:31.000
[Guest]: We explain, if you do X, Y, Z, let's say if you do X, the natural consequence of that is A,

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:37.000
[Guest]: because that's what both logic and empirical evidence and what people elsewhere have done leads to.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.000
[Guest]: If you do Y, the consequence is B.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:43.000
[Guest]: Whether A is desirable or B is desirable is a political choice.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:45.000
[Guest]: I am not in that game.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:46.000
[Guest]: That's your job.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:47.000
[Guest]: People voted for you.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:48.000
[Guest]: You are the politician.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:52.000
[Guest]: No, but I can say X leads to A and Y leads to B.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:56.000
[Guest]: You choose whether you want A or B and therefore you choose whether you should take the X or Y path.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
[Guest]: That's the way we think.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:40:59.000
[Guest]: And that works.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.000
[Guest]: And they're appreciative.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:03.000
[Guest]: And in fact, these meetings which we have is all party.

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:05.000
[Guest]: We have MPs across parties.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:09.000
[Guest]: And the discussion is very civil because there's no camera on.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:11.000
[Guest]: Nobody's going to talk about it outside.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:18.000
[Guest]: It's actually better than and much more civil than the conversation I have with longtime friends nowadays,

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:22.000
[Guest]: which now many times gets into very or anything on.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:27.000
[Guest]: I am not on social media, but anything which I believe is on social media.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, one has to, you know, re-evaluate all kinds of relationships because, you know,

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:37.000
[Amit Varma]: just the polarization of these times changes so many equations.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:44.000
[Amit Varma]: So I have a question from here that politicians, it seems to me, are forced when they succeed,

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:47.000
[Amit Varma]: forced when they succeed to inhabit two worlds.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:52.000
[Amit Varma]: The first world is a world of electoral politics, which only requires them to win elections.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And they excel at that just by the selection effect that if they've actually become a minister or an MP,

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:00.000
[Amit Varma]: obviously they've excelled at that.

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:01.000
[Amit Varma]: That's why they're there.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:02.000
[Amit Varma]: They are great at that.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's a business that demands building public opinion, managing the internal politics within the party

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:12.000
[Amit Varma]: so that you get a ticket, managing money, managing money.

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And when you get money to run for elections, there are quid pro quos involved

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:22.000
[Amit Varma]: and ROI has to be guaranteed and all that is there, which leads us to the cynical view of politics

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:28.000
[Amit Varma]: that politicians will just play this first game that I've just described and look at the next election

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:33.000
[Amit Varma]: and whatever they do is with an eye on either increasing votes or increasing money

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:37.000
[Amit Varma]: or making sure the party gives them a ticket like you correctly said.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Now there is a second game that begins.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:40.000
[Amit Varma]: This is a first game.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:41.000
[Amit Varma]: They've excelled.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:42.000
[Amit Varma]: They're there.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:44.000
[Amit Varma]: The second game is the game of governance.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is a completely different game.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And this is a game they're beginners at.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:54.000
[Amit Varma]: For a first time MP or a first time politician, this is a game they're learning from scratch

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:57.000
[Amit Varma]: while the other game they've pretty much mastered by the time they come here.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Now it strikes me that, you know, for anyone to excel at any two fields to find that conjunction,

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:10.000
[Amit Varma]: first of all, is just statistically rare and unlikely that someone who has a mindset to excel at game one,

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:16.000
[Amit Varma]: which is electoral politics, will also have the mindset to excel at game two, which is governance.

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing about our modern times increasingly is that it seems to me that

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.000
[Amit Varma]: elections are determined not by the quality of the governance you might have done,

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
[Amit Varma]: but the quality of the narratives you build.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:32.000
[Amit Varma]: So there is actually even this disconnect that they may not even feel that the second game matters at all.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:37.000
[Amit Varma]: So you've mentioned that you had Dr. Banerjee come and speak to these guys and 20 people showed up.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, there are 420 MPs in parliament.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:45.000
[Amit Varma]: But I buy your point that I mean, obviously, you interact with them more than anyone I know.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:51.000
[Amit Varma]: So you'd have a better handle on this, which is why this next question that I guess at some level,

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:57.000
[Amit Varma]: a certain presumably large percentage of them would have the desire to learn governance

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
[Amit Varma]: and the interest to figure out what's going on.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:05.000
[Amit Varma]: A large percentage of that percentage would put in the work and some percentage of that percentage

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:11.000
[Amit Varma]: would actually have the capacity and the prior learning in terms of being good readers

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and having exposure to a world of ideas to actually kind of make sense of it.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't know any of this and you know all of this.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this second game and how politicians treat it.

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
[Guest]: Actually, this is the third game also.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about the third game.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Let me complicate it for you.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:27.000
[Guest]: Yeah, please do, please do.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:30.000
[Guest]: I would actually say there are three skill sets at various levels.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
[Guest]: I'm talking about the ministers.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.000
[Guest]: So first you have to win an election.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:42.000
[Guest]: That's a particular skill, which I mean, somebody like me will have zero ability.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:48.000
[Guest]: The only time I have stood for an election was for the library secretary of my hostel of 180 people,

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.000
[Guest]: which I lost.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:53.000
[Guest]: And I knew all of them for three years and I lost.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.000
[Guest]: That's my only electoral foray.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:45:03.000
[Guest]: And I have tremendous respect for people who win an election with an electorate of 15 lakh people.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.000
[Guest]: How do you manage that?

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:07.000
[Guest]: I have tremendous respect for this.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:09.000
[Guest]: Second, they get elected.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:11.000
[Guest]: Now they are legislators.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:12.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:16.000
[Guest]: You have to understand, let us say, the insolvency and bankruptcy code.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:19.000
[Guest]: What are the nuances there?

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
[Guest]: Then you have to go and see something completely different.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
[Guest]: Let's say something on education.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:27.000
[Guest]: How do you regulate higher education?

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:28.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:31.000
[Guest]: Or as you could see in all newspapers today.

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:38.000
[Guest]: Yesterday, the Standing Committee on Finance was hearing people on cryptocurrencies.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:47.000
[Guest]: Now, I mean, frankly, despite my finance background and supposedly an engineering degree, I don't understand this whole thing yet.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:50.000
[Guest]: I haven't put in my time on it, but I don't really understand what it is.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:58.000
[Guest]: But if you want to decide how to regulate, whether to regulate, not to regulate, you have to understand what that animal is.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: So that is the second skill set.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
[Guest]: Now, let's say you become a minister.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:08.000
[Guest]: There's a completely different third skill set, which is you're a manager now.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:21.000
[Guest]: It's an administrative skill, which is very different from the intellectual ability to understand how the system works.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:34.000
[Guest]: I mean, if I take, let's say, a university example, a brilliant professor and a researcher may not be a good dean or vice chancellor.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:37.000
[Guest]: I mean, that's a different skill set.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:38.000
[Unknown]: Exactly.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:42.000
[Guest]: So you need three different skill sets.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:46.000
[Guest]: If you're a minister, if you're an MP, you need two because you don't need that.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:53.000
[Guest]: You need the administrative to the extent you are managed, but that is part of the first itself, that is managing a constituency and your winning elections.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:47:03.000
[Guest]: So it's actually a very difficult task to find capable ministers because they, if you don't, you need all three.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:05.000
[Guest]: That's the issue.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:12.000
[Guest]: Of course, we, fortunately in our system, we can bypass number one for some of them by getting them through Rajya Sabha.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:17.000
[Guest]: So you have two and three you can manage, but most of the better guys have done all three.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:24.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know the name names, but you all know there are people who have been excellent ministers who have come through the Lok Sabha route.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:27.000
[Amit Varma]: Since these are words of praise, why don't you actually take names?

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:28.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm very curious.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Or you feel others will feel offended.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.000
[Guest]: Let me not go recent times.

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:33.000
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:37.000
[Guest]: Because then it, because I don't want to get into, in this polarized world, into all sorts.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Taking sides, appearance of taking sides.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.000
[Amit Varma]: I get that.

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
[Guest]: But let me think, let me somebody like Yashwant Sinha.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:44.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.000
[Guest]: He won the election.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:47.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:54.000
[Guest]: He, I would say as a finance minister, he transformed the indirect tax system.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:55.000
[Guest]: I mean, GST was a later thing.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:01.000
[Guest]: GST of course did it, but he cut the number of tax slabs.

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:14.000
[Guest]: He is the person who actually did the initial FRBM part of which said that essentially I have, there is a lot of pressure on me as the finance minister to spend.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:21.000
[Guest]: So let the legislation tie my hands on how much I can spend because that's dangerous.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:26.000
[Guest]: Of course it was passed by Chidambaram because it didn't get passed in this time fully.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
[Guest]: I think it was passed in 2005 or was it 2003?

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:32.000
[Guest]: I don't know, but I remember the first paper when it came because I was in the interest rate market.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:33.000
[Guest]: I saw that.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:37.000
[Guest]: I said, wow, I am seeing an interest rate rally because the government cuts its borrowings.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.000
[Guest]: And I remember writing a note that time.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
[Guest]: So I remember definitely it was him.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:42.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:45.000
[Guest]: So, and he of course was running a ministry.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:49.000
[Guest]: So there's somebody like him and I'm sure there are people in the past enough.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:58.000
[Guest]: And I mean, I don't want to go to current people because then it becomes, it takes a political change, whatever you say in today's world.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:48:59.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:00.000
[Guest]: So I just want to avoid that.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
[Guest]: That's why I'm going back 20 years.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:09.000
[Guest]: And he's effectively, I mean, though he, I think he tweets, et cetera, but he's effectively retired from active politics from what I know.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Indeed.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, some people say that when he was finance minister under Chandrasekhar just before that government fell,

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:19.000
[Amit Varma]: he actually came up with a plan that he also wanted to liberalize before, you know.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:20.000
[Guest]: Perhaps.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:28.000
[Guest]: Or even the reason I did not take the name of Manmohan Singh, the finance minister is because he was Rajya Sabha, but otherwise he excelled in two and three.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:29.000
[Guest]: He excelled in two and three.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
[Guest]: We are talking today, I think.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:32.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:41.000
[Guest]: Or PRS would not have existed if 1991 liberalization hadn't happened and would have given me the confidence to actually quit a job and do things like that.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:47.000
[Guest]: And even the career trajectories we had were thanks to 91.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:53.000
[Guest]: So, I mean, I am deeply grateful to the Narsimha Rao, Manmohan Singh for transforming at least my life.

00:49:53.000 --> 00:49:54.000
[Guest]: I don't know what others.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:55.000
[Amit Varma]: No, no, absolutely.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:56.000
[Amit Varma]: So they were there.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.000
[Guest]: So, but he was Rajya Sabha.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:49:59.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:03.000
[Guest]: So he didn't get the, in the three categories, he didn't make the first one.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:07.000
[Guest]: He made second and third, which is he understands things, nuances, very complex things.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:11.000
[Guest]: And he could also run the finance ministry and later the government.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:25.000
[Guest]: And running a government, I think people in the private sector don't understand the real complexity of running the government, which is way, way more complex than the most complex conglomerate you can think of.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
[Guest]: Can you elaborate on that a bit?

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:34.000
[Guest]: Well, if I'm running a conglomerate, I don't, or running a company, I'm the CEO, I have to get a buy-in, but I can also easily sack people.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:39.000
[Guest]: I can get in new people and I am doing a limited market thing.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:53.000
[Guest]: Here, the number of different stakeholders and pressures that I have to handle and any decision, the impact it has, not just the first order, but second, third, fourth, fifth order.

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:59.000
[Guest]: How do I even comprehend that and play for that?

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:07.000
[Guest]: I mean, on anything, you don't know what are the unplanned consequences and you have to be careful about it.

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:12.000
[Guest]: Because policy has way more complications and consequences than a business decision.

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:15.000
[Guest]: Worst case in a business decision, that company will go down.

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
[Guest]: Here, you take down the country.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So, let's look at the Air India decision as an example, where it seems to me that it would really require skill number two at some level to really understand why this is a good thing to do.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:36.000
[Amit Varma]: But skill number three, mainly to get it through that massive sort of government system.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:40.000
[Guest]: The vested interests which are holding that back.

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:41.000
[Guest]: Yeah, you need to get that done.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:44.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and that can take years or never happen.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:46.000
[Guest]: Why did they not do it all these years?

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:59.000
[Guest]: I mean, because you could see right from 2014, when this prime minister came in, that at least Air India was intellectually an easy decision for.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:00.000
[Guest]: Low hanging fruit.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:04.000
[Guest]: Low hanging and I think, at least I'm guessing, of course, I don't know.

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:09.000
[Guest]: I'm guessing that ideologically, you won't have an issue with it.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:12.000
[Guest]: I mean, it would be part of the thing that he thinks should be done.

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:13.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:16.000
[Guest]: That's what I'm guessing from the other actions.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
[Guest]: I mean, obviously, I've never met him, so I have no idea.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:28.000
[Guest]: But looking at the other things he has done, I think this would fit in with his worldview, by and large, not an issue.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:35.000
[Guest]: And he's easily the most powerful prime minister in terms of ability to take decisions and get them done.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:45.000
[Guest]: Since perhaps Rajiv Gandhi, right, I mean, the first clean, clear majority and first person who has full control over his party.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:49.000
[Guest]: He took him so much time to do it.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:51.000
[Guest]: So it's not an easy thing to do.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:52.000
[Unknown]: Yeah, I mean.

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:53.000
[Unknown]: People underestimate that.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
[Guest]: People say, why didn't he do it?

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:56.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:57.000
[Guest]: There must be some reason.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:06.000
[Guest]: It's not that he's incapable, it is more likely that you don't understand the complexities he's facing.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:11.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, many listeners would listen to this and wonder, he is a prime minister.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:12.000
[Amit Varma]: He is Modiji.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:16.000
[Amit Varma]: He did demonetization overnight, which was such a disaster.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:22.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, if he gives an order, what stops it from actually being carried out?

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And I understand the answer is deeply complex, but this is a question people would have, demonetization toh kiya, isme kya hai?

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So can you kind of elaborate a little bit on the sort of this labyrinthine kind of opaque, deep state, as it were?

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
[Guest]: I actually don't know the full answers.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:41.000
[Guest]: I can only take some guesses.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:51.000
[Guest]: For example, if I were a bureaucrat and I am entitled to, let's say, economic laws or business laws, I probably get a free upgrade every time I travel that.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:53.000
[Guest]: Why would I get, why would I?

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay, as small as that.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
[Unknown]: Why would I not take that?

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:57.000
[Guest]: It hurts me.

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:00.000
[Guest]: I'm guessing, but there'll be somebody like that.

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:03.000
[Guest]: And there'll be many other things and they're also ideologically.

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:05.000
[Guest]: What happens to all those Air India employees?

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
[Guest]: It's a big question.

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:08.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:11.000
[Guest]: I mean, you know, it depends upon the way you look at it.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:17.000
[Guest]: One way to look at it is that anyway, in the top 2% or 1% of the country's population,

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:22.000
[Guest]: can this money be used to the bottom 5% rather than the top 2%?

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:23.000
[Guest]: That's a good way of putting it.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:24.000
[Guest]: One way of thinking that.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:29.000
[Guest]: But another way of thinking that is, well, can I afford to hurt these guys?

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:44.000
[Guest]: One of the benefits or fortunate parts of being in some place like a PRS is the variety of issues that I get to look at and the variety of people that I get to talk to, which is great fun,

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:50.000
[Guest]: or the way we have nicely defined our domain is anything that comes to Parliament, which means everything.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:51.000
[Guest]: Right?

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:58.000
[Guest]: So I'm not restricted to, let's say, education or health or sanitation or banking or insurance or something like that.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:05.000
[Guest]: So if you talk to any of these people, health sector, they will say India should set 6% on health.

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:08.000
[Guest]: When I talk to the education guys, they will say 6%.

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:15.000
[Guest]: You talk to the guys who are working on defence, they will say China is there, Pakistan is there, we shouldn't spend X percent.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:16.000
[Guest]: You add them up.

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:17.000
[Guest]: Okay.

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:18.000
[Guest]: You'll get a number.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
[Guest]: Tax to GDP is what?

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
[Guest]: 15, 16, 17%.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
[Guest]: Say fiscal deficit, add.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
[Guest]: Okay, no, no, we shouldn't do fiscal deficit.

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:27.000
[Guest]: It's bad.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
[Guest]: But add a generous sum.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:34.000
[Guest]: Let's say, country does a fiscal deficit of 10%, which is a risky part.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:39.000
[Guest]: Still, you are at 27%, 25, 27%, and you add these, it will be like 40%.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:47.000
[Guest]: So the example I give, and for everything, again, I think the best way to think of the world is through the eyes of cricket.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:48.000
[Guest]: Yes.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:49.000
[Guest]: Should you play Ashwin?

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:50.000
[Guest]: Yes, of course.

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:51.000
[Guest]: Who do you drop?

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:54.000
[Guest]: There are only 11 spots.

00:55:54.000 --> 00:56:02.000
[Guest]: So if you say you have to play Ashwin, it is a meaningless statement unless you say, replace X by Ashwin.

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
[Unknown]: Then I'm willing to drop Ashwin.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
[Guest]: But should I drop this?

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:07.000
[Guest]: No, you need that guy.

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:10.000
[Guest]: No, then who will we play instead of somebody, right?

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
[Guest]: So same thing.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:17.000
[Guest]: If you are saying you have to increase for health, tell me what you should reduce for.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:22.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's a non-starter because the resources are limited.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:27.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't think people get the, people think government has unlimited resources.

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:39.000
[Guest]: So same thing, if you are spending, so Air India, my contention would have been that if they had paid, they got some, whatever, a few thousand crore.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:42.000
[Guest]: But let's say they paid 10,000 crore for somebody to take Air India off their hands.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:46.000
[Guest]: It would have been worth it because Air India is bleeding 5,000 per year.

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: So instead of minus 5,000, in two years, minus 10,000, you're paying minus 10,000.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:56.000
[Amit Varma]: Third year onwards, your payback period is two years.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Which makes a good business decision.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:01.000
[Guest]: The money you don't spend is a notional profit from giving Air India.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:07.000
[Guest]: It is because that 5,000 could have been spent, let's say, in sanitation or education or health or defense or wherever else.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:10.000
[Amit Varma]: Where the government needs to spend, right?

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:15.000
[Amit Varma]: So I have a story which seems unrelated to this, but I think it's related and I'll tell you why.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:18.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a story about Leo Tolstoy and a chicken.

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, in the last years of his life, Tolstoy became militantly vegetarian.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:28.000
[Amit Varma]: You can, in fact, say that he was like one of the original virtue signalers before Twitter.

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:32.000
[Amit Varma]: But militantly vegetarian and Gandhi, in fact, was very influenced by him in certain ways.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So one day, one of Tolstoy's aunts, an old lady, because obviously he was also fairly advanced by this time.

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:40.000
[Amit Varma]: An old lady said, I'm coming home for dinner.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:41.000
[Amit Varma]: So he said, you're welcome.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So she said, I would like to eat chicken.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:46.000
[Amit Varma]: I know you don't eat animals, but I want chicken.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:49.000
[Amit Varma]: So he said, OK, no problem, you'll get your chicken.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So she lands up there and when they go to the dinner table, she finds that Tolstoy has put a live chicken on the chair.

00:57:55.000 --> 00:58:03.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And for me, this is sort of a wonderful metaphor for and I'm non-veg, by the way, so I'm not advocating for vegetarianism.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:11.000
[Amit Varma]: But this is a wonderful metaphor of how in most people's minds there is a disconnect between the chicken on the plate and the chicken on the chair.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And it's almost a necessary disconnect in some ways.

00:58:15.000 --> 00:58:16.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a scene in the unseen.

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, when it comes to government, I often say that India's biggest religion is not Hinduism.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:25.000
[Amit Varma]: It's the religion of government where we look at the government as a solution to every problem.

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And we assume there is no cost to government action.

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And what you just said, you know, is such a good way of thinking about it that we've got to understand that to everything the government does, there is a cost.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, even beyond this issue of scarce resources and choosing what we spend on, even before that, at a meta level, there is a moral cost.

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:53.000
[Amit Varma]: That government exists at the extent of a certain necessary violence to, you know, to have a state.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And we never take any of that into account.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.000
[Amit Varma]: We just say ki nahi, we should spend so much, spend that much.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And I thought I should say, you know, this Tolstoy's chicken came to mind.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So I thought I should share that.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's get back to the meta question, but to the start of our republic, right?

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Where, you know, you've spoken in the past and I've had many episodes on the constitution where we speak about how, you know, it's not just important to be a democracy in a sense of having elections and all of that.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:23.000
[Amit Varma]: But you also need to be a republic.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:31.000
[Amit Varma]: You need a constitution, which is a set of rules and that constrains the actions of governments, not people, constrains the actions of the state.

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Now, what strikes to me, what strikes me as a fundamental paradox and something that I think even Ambedkar realized and Gandhi realized is that the constitution, though it is nowhere near as liberal as I would like it to be, is much more liberal than society.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, we have essentially a bunch of elites and at that time unelected elites who impose a liberal constitution on an illiberal society.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:04.000
[Amit Varma]: So the first question, which is an abstract question, which, you know, we don't have to go into if you don't want to.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:08.000
[Amit Varma]: The first question is, can that imposition be liberal? Is there a better way of doing it?

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But the second question, and this is a danger that Ambedkar was aware of because he said that the constitution is no more than a topsoil, that everything beneath is completely different.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And their hope, of course, at that time was from the topsoil, these values could kind of penetrate below, which, of course, did not happen.

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And what we see today, in a sense, in my cynical eyes, and I tend to be more cynical than others, so you might feel differently, but in my cynical eyes, in a sense, I think politics has caught up with society.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps that experiment was always doomed to failure if you did not also, you know, impose those kind of or rather introduce those kind of values into society itself and, you know, make it a bottom up thing.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:55.000
[Guest]: What are your thoughts on this?

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:57.000
[Guest]: Fairly complex one.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:10.000
[Guest]: So I'll just start off with saying that you're asking me this question in 2021, which is 71 years since 1950 and 74 years since 1947.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:25.000
[Guest]: The very fact that you can ask me this question and you're going to put it in public and we are not having a closed door conversation, which nobody knows about, is a sign of its success.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:40.000
[Guest]: And the reason I'm saying this is, and this is something that I have read and actually, I mean, I don't even know how do you find these things, but there's this, what's the name of the book?

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:44.000
[Guest]: Ashutosh Varshney's book called, I think Battles Half Won or something like that.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:02:00.000
[Guest]: I think it's Battles Half Won. I'm not, it is Ashutosh Varshney's book where he quotes a study where they have looked at some over 200 odd regimes and seen what are the determinants of who will stay democratic and who won't.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:03.000
[Guest]: And India is the biggest, by far the biggest outlier.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:23.000
[Guest]: And another very interesting thing that study puts out is, so if you look at World War II as a cutoff point, because the world, Asia, Africa, were largely colonies of European powers till then.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:32.000
[Guest]: And World War II was a break point. India was one of the early ones to get decolonized and a bunch of people in the next 20 years, almost everyone got decolonized.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:38.000
[Guest]: How many countries out of that have stayed democratic? I'm just using, say, regular elections.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:52.000
[Guest]: We missed one by one year. But after elections, second this thing, if the elections are broadly free and fair, and if the incumbent loses, hands over power, which to our credit, Indira Gandhi did.

01:02:52.000 --> 01:03:03.000
[Guest]: I don't know whether she had a choice, but the fact is she did. She didn't call in the army. I don't know whether they would have listened to her, but she handed over power peacefully and went off.

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:11.000
[Guest]: So, I'm no admirer of her, by the way. But at least this one action was, I mean, I don't even know what happened.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:22.000
[Guest]: But how many countries have managed not to have an army police rule and a democratic, can you guess, of the set that became independent post?

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:33.000
[Guest]: So, I'm not talking about, let's say, the Western democracies like the UK or the US or, I mean, I would even call Australia and New Zealand as Western or Japan, which was never a colony.

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:37.000
[Guest]: I'm not talking about them. Guess how many countries?

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:46.000
[Guest]: The number must be really small. That would be. According to this study and the book, there are seven. India is one of them.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:59.000
[Guest]: And I remember the other six and I'll tell you. So, it is Belize, Jamaica, Mauritius, Papua New Guinea, Solomon Islands and Vanuatu.

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:07.000
[Guest]: None of which has a population of even one crore. We are 150 times larger than the second largest.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:14.000
[Guest]: I guess they are way more homogeneous if a population of a few lakh like Jamaica or something than a complex country like India.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:19.000
[Guest]: So, we have pulled off a miracle. Let's not demean that.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:31.000
[Guest]: And all our cynicism about what's happening at the same time, we should not get complacent because it's a perennial project to keep this running.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:46.000
[Guest]: I mean, democracies, you could see by its very nature, the liberal order, which says that everyone has a right to say whatever is on their minds as long as they are not causing physical violence to you

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:55.000
[Guest]: and therefore can convince other peoples of their opinion versus the other order, which says that somebody who speaks what they don't like will be shut up.

01:04:55.000 --> 01:05:03.000
[Guest]: You are under way greater threat because you are saying that those guys should also be around at all times.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:14.000
[Guest]: And you want to keep that and you want to survive. If you lose the battle for ideas once, you can't get it back.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:18.000
[Guest]: Whereas those guys, if they lose the battle in the next election, they'll win the battle again.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:26.000
[Guest]: But they won't have a next election. So, it is a perennial project and we have done a great job.

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:28.000
[Guest]: I mean, so that's what I would say.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:40.000
[Guest]: Now, coming back to your first question about, yes, of course, it was a bunch of elites who put on a liberal thing, which was way more liberal than what society did.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:46.000
[Guest]: But society has moved. I mean, we still have a lot of issues.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:55.000
[Guest]: But, you know, I would say broadly moved in that direction in which they envisioned India to be for one biggest achievement.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:06:01.000
[Guest]: We are one country. We are not balkanized into 25 countries. We still are one country.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:08.000
[Guest]: You did not require a visa to come from Bombay to Delhi. You just took a flight, I guess, and came over.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:16.000
[Guest]: All of us have, I would say, multiple identities, the way we think of ourselves.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:24.000
[Guest]: So somebody might think he's a Maharashtrian or a Kannadiga or a Malayali or a Tam, but everybody, most people in India think of themselves also as Indians.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:28.000
[Guest]: And I don't know whether that was true in 1920s and 30s.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:33.000
[Guest]: I mean, you're probably your caste first or religion first or region first or something rather than Indian.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:36.000
[Guest]: So that is a huge achievement that the country as a whole has achieved.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:40.000
[Guest]: So I'm actually that way, fairly optimistic.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:45.000
[Guest]: So when you are at every point of time.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:55.000
[Guest]: Last, I mean, I don't know, ever since I can think of as an adult, the current situation has seemed bleak.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:01.000
[Unknown]: But if 10 years later you look back, you think, well, it wasn't that bad.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:11.000
[Guest]: I think, I mean, a lot of things that are being said today are, again, with a bit of exaggeration in all sides.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:18.000
[Amit Varma]: By your counterpoint, like it plays back to that old statement about whatever you say of India, the opposite is also true.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And I remember in episode 149 of the show, I had a long, deep conversation with J.P. Narayan.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And when I referred to India as an illiberal society, he pointed out that from another point of view, it's also a deeply liberal society in the sense that if you look at our food, our culture, our languages, it's just so much assimilation coming in.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:47.000
[Amit Varma]: So I buy that point. And as far as the constitution itself is concerned, I think Rohit De's book, People's Constitution, shows about how there's so much lived reality.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:50.000
[Amit Varma]: Constitution is part of the lived reality of people as well and so on.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:08:03.000
[Amit Varma]: As far as, you know, I agree that it is almost a miraculous achievement that we remained a democracy and we should not take it for granted and assume that, you know, with the benefit of hindsight that it was inevitable.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:05.000
[Amit Varma]: It absolutely wasn't. It is incredible.

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:16.000
[Amit Varma]: But I wonder how much of it is down to sort of inertia, you know, just no one really going as far as to cause the friction that causes such rapid change and also happenstance.

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Like you mentioned Indira, like sure, she lost the election and she gave over power, but we all know that Sanjay Gandhi didn't won the elections.

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:29.000
[Amit Varma]: She called the elections because she wanted, you know, she wanted the foreign press to think better of her and she genuinely believed she would win.

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:32.000
[Amit Varma]: So it might well have been the case that had Sanjay had his way.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:33.000
[Guest]: But she handed over power when she lost.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:34.000
[Guest]: She did.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:35.000
[Guest]: But she didn't rig the elections.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:39.000
[Guest]: Sure, but we may not have had the elections. Sanjay didn't want to.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:47.000
[Guest]: See, put it this way, I think emergency was the darkest period in our post 1950 history.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:52.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, as I told you, I'm not an admirer of Indira at all.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:57.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I think even the period before that when she was PM because of her economic policies were a really dark period.

01:08:57.000 --> 01:09:10.000
[Guest]: That I have a slightly different opinion in the sense, I mean, I'm not particularly in favor of those economic policies, but they went through a formal proper process.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:18.000
[Guest]: And at the end of the day, you take right choices, you take wrong choices, but you have the constitutional sanction to take.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, they weren't authoritarian impositions, but they were disastrous in their consequences.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:31.000
[Guest]: I agree with that, but whatever they were, but the very idea of the emergency is seriously problematic.

01:09:31.000 --> 01:09:34.000
[Guest]: But she did that.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:37.000
[Guest]: Sorry, I think I interrupted you and I lost my thought.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.000
[Unknown]: No, no, you didn't interrupt me.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:46.000
[Amit Varma]: You were sort of responding to my point about Indira and you were sort of stating that she did give up power.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And there are, I guess, all these, you know, always multiple ways to look at something.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:54.000
[Guest]: Sorry, just one point, which was saying that you think it's inertia.

01:09:54.000 --> 01:09:56.000
[Guest]: Well, it's a possibility.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:58.000
[Guest]: The way my counter is simple.

01:09:58.000 --> 01:09:59.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:09:59.000 --> 01:10:01.000
[Guest]: If you see culturally, okay.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:07.000
[Guest]: Assuming India is a common culture, which I actually, I don't think historically it was, it was too different.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:18.000
[Guest]: But probably our Punjab and the Pakistani Punjab have way more common culture than our Punjab and say Tamil Nadu.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:24.000
[Guest]: Okay. But Pakistan had army coup in 1955 or 50.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:25.000
[Guest]: We didn't.

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:26.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:10:26.000 --> 01:10:28.000
[Guest]: But so if it's the inertia.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:29.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:32.000
[Guest]: And what and the loss of democracy.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:41.000
[Guest]: I'm just looking at culturally India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, and I would contend even Sri Lanka to some extent are not very different.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:43.000
[Guest]: I mean, at least all of us like cricket.

01:10:43.000 --> 01:10:51.000
[Guest]: So, we had a different path politically in the democratic this thing than the others.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:56.000
[Guest]: So, that's why I'm actually saying that it's an incredible achievement already.

01:10:56.000 --> 01:11:02.000
[Guest]: But the question is 75 years, are we going to do 75 years more of that or not?

01:11:02.000 --> 01:11:03.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:09.000
[Guest]: Because it, and remember, I mean, when did, okay, US, what's the start of US?

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:12.000
[Guest]: I would say 1790 or something.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:15.000
[Guest]: Not 1776 was the declaration of independence.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:19.000
[Guest]: I think early 17, what, 82 or something is when the Brits were defeated.

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:23.000
[Guest]: The constitution was written in 1789, 1790.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:28.000
[Guest]: At 70 years, which is our age now, they were fighting a civil war.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:29.000
[Guest]: We are not.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Well, who knows after the delimitation exercise, but.

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:40.000
[Guest]: No, it's not a proper civil war with two armies fighting each other, people dying on the battlefield.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:44.000
[Guest]: I mean, that's a different level happening there.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:47.000
[Guest]: They went through that before they forced the nation.

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:50.000
[Guest]: We have managed to do it without doing that.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:51.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:52.000
[Guest]: That's itself an achievement.

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:54.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a great achievement.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:11:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And whatever people think of this regime, and I am, of course, an outspoken opponent.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:07.000
[Amit Varma]: But the point is they won elections fair and square, you know, and they kind of mastered that game one, as it were, which is.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:10.000
[Guest]: They have done elections and policies.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:12.000
[Guest]: You can always argue various ways.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:21.000
[Guest]: And there are, I mean, even the severest critics of them on the policy front will say things like insolvency, bankruptcy code is a great reform.

01:12:21.000 --> 01:12:23.000
[Guest]: And that's true of every government.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:32.000
[Guest]: Every government, if you have an ideology, which I deliberately don't because I need, I mean, professionally, I should not have one.

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:38.000
[Guest]: But if you have an ideology with every government, you'll find a mix of things where you like some and you don't like.

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:43.000
[Guest]: Because the governments are also managing multiple stakeholders and multiple ideology.

01:12:43.000 --> 01:12:51.000
[Guest]: And they're not going to do exactly what you want them to do because they are managing lots of contradictions.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:13:00.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of the sad signs of our discourse is that it's become so tribal in the sense that if you are with one party, you will think that 100% of the things they do are correct.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:08.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you're against a party, you'll think 100% of the things they do are wrong, which is crazy, which cannot possibly be true.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:09.000
[Amit Varma]: That is stupidity.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's kind of a sign of the times.

