01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:19.000
[Amit Varma]: One, I'm glad we have the constitution.

01:15:19.000 --> 01:15:20.000
[Amit Varma]: We do.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Like you pointed out, it might be a big factor for why we've kind of stayed together as one nation instead of getting balkanized.

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Why we haven't had the army takeover and so on and so forth.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:35.000
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there are deep flaws with it, both at the time of inception and through the years.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:41.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, at inception, if you know, if one just looks at Article 19 and earlier, we referred to free speech.

01:15:41.000 --> 01:15:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's true that you and I are able to have this conversation right now.

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:51.000
[Amit Varma]: But it is also true that throughout the country, the state at least has the tools to clamp down on dissent.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Because the caveats in the constitution to free speech are those vague abstract terms like public order, decency, and so on and so forth.

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Which constitute such limits on free speech that I sometimes think that we are just being lip service to free speech.

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:06.000
[Amit Varma]: It's not there.

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:13.000
[Amit Varma]: Which are also the reason why laws like 295A, 153A, the Sedition Law haven't been struck down.

01:16:13.000 --> 01:16:18.000
[Amit Varma]: The Sedition Law was declared unconstitutional in 1950 and Nehru brought it back with the First Amendment.

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Because he wanted to keep the communists under control at that time.

01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:30.000
[Amit Varma]: So this is my sort of first misgiving about the constitution that it's heavy, bulky document that takes a lot from everywhere.

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Right from its size, you can make out it doesn't have the clarity of, say, the American Constitution, which you can carry in your pocket.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:43.000
[Amit Varma]: And the other misgiving is, I'll hark back to this old cartoon which once came where, you know, a guy goes to a bookshop and he says,

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:46.000
[Amit Varma]: Parliament Bookshop, and he says, can I buy a copy of the constitution?

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:49.000
[Amit Varma]: And the guy says, sorry, sir, we don't sell periodicals.

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:52.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's just been amended so many times.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:16:59.000
[Amit Varma]: One of those amendments famously, you know, turning the right to property from a fundamental right to a legal right or basically not a right at all.

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:07.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's been amended so many times at the whims and mercies of those in charge, that you begin to feel that, you know,

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:15.000
[Amit Varma]: yeh sab dikhawa hai in a sense, you know, I've heard you speak and I completely agree about the centrality of the constitution to our republic.

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But I feel dismayed when I think of all this. What are your thoughts?

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:27.000
[Guest]: Two points, which you said, one is, it's a bulky document, whereas the American one you can carry in your pocket.

01:17:27.000 --> 01:17:34.000
[Guest]: And the second is that it's relatively easy to amend and has been amended over a hundred times.

01:17:34.000 --> 01:17:39.000
[Guest]: On the first, I think there's just a cliche which is incorrect.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:45.000
[Guest]: If I'm living in a state of whatever, Ohio or California or New York or whatever,

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:52.000
[Guest]: I have to look at the constitution of the United States of America plus the constitution of that state, which is fairly large.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:59.000
[Guest]: OK, so we have only one for all 28 states plus the Union.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:05.000
[Guest]: If you add the 28 constitution or 50 constitutions plus one there, it'll be, my guess, I have not read them.

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:12.000
[Guest]: I've seen only the main one, much, much larger. OK, so I actually end in a sense,

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:20.000
[Guest]: if it had been as bare-boned as the American one, my guess is it would not have served its purpose.

01:18:20.000 --> 01:18:24.000
[Guest]: And it needed to put in a lot of details at that time in our history.

01:18:24.000 --> 01:18:32.000
[Guest]: And remember, when you're thinking of a constitution, at the time it was written, what was the background?

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:37.000
[Guest]: The primary thought of the American constitution, the guys who wrote it,

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:44.000
[Guest]: was that they were essentially rich landholders, slave owners, largely.

01:18:44.000 --> 01:18:50.000
[Guest]: And they were threatened by the fact that the mad king George III will come back and take over.

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:57.000
[Guest]: So the entire constitution is to protect their interests. That's the way it is designed.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:19:01.000
[Guest]: And you read the Federalist Papers, which is brilliant. I mean, I recommend that to everyone.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:02.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:09.000
[Guest]: It actually is the first detailed in a language that I know, which is modern English,

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:14.000
[Guest]: exposition of thinking behind separation of powers, etc.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:18.000
[Guest]: I mean, I'm sure others may have written, but this is the one I have read.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:22.000
[Guest]: So this was their thinking and that was the background.

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:27.000
[Guest]: In India, these people were thinking about social reform, economic reform.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:30.000
[Guest]: The Americans weren't. American constitution was conservative.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:36.000
[Guest]: It was keeping the current elite in power, continue to stay in power.

01:19:36.000 --> 01:19:39.000
[Guest]: Our purpose was very, very different.

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:44.000
[Guest]: So it needed, I mean, things like directive principles would never find place in any of those.

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:48.000
[Guest]: Right. So that's one. The second thing that you talked about,

01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:51.000
[Guest]: I would actually call it the strength of the constitution.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:20:00.000
[Guest]: Which is, do you know what's the average life of a constitution in the last maybe 50, 100 years?

01:20:00.000 --> 01:20:01.000
[Amit Varma]: How long do constitutions last?

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Since you've asked me, I'm sure the number is very low.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:07.000
[Guest]: I have read this in a paper.

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:16.000
[Guest]: So it's in that book edited by, it's a handbook on the constitution edited by Madhav Khosla,

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:19.000
[Guest]: Pratap Bhanumetha and Sudeep Bose.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:22.000
[Guest]: It says 15 years, maybe 15, 16.

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:24.000
[Guest]: We have done 70.

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:29.000
[Guest]: And despite all our contradictions, all the pressures, we are the only,

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:36.000
[Guest]: I said we stated democracy, we state that also we are possibly the most diverse nation on earth.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:39.000
[Guest]: We are Europe or we are Africa.

01:20:39.000 --> 01:20:43.000
[Guest]: We are not France or Germany. Right.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:48.000
[Guest]: And we have stayed. And I think this is part of the thing is the flexibility it afforded,

01:20:48.000 --> 01:20:51.000
[Guest]: which helped manage the contradictions.

01:20:51.000 --> 01:20:53.000
[Guest]: I'll just start at the very beginning.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:21:01.000
[Guest]: Nineteen early fifties, there was this movement in Andhra Pradesh that we need a state for the Telugus,

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:06.000
[Guest]: separate from Madras province. And you know Nehru wasn't for it.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:09.000
[Guest]: He was afraid of balkanization.

01:21:09.000 --> 01:21:14.000
[Guest]: If these interests are allowed to go, then everybody will want and the country will split up.

01:21:14.000 --> 01:21:16.000
[Guest]: That was his genuine worry.

01:21:16.000 --> 01:21:21.000
[Guest]: And this was just a few years after the country had split on religious lines.

01:21:21.000 --> 01:21:23.000
[Guest]: They wanted to split on linguistic lines.

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:30.000
[Guest]: But then 1956, which is pretty soon after, there's this major amendment to the constitution,

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:33.000
[Guest]: which created linguistic states.

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:41.000
[Unknown]: And in hindsight of 60 years, 65 years, well, it was it has worked.

01:21:41.000 --> 01:21:44.000
[Guest]: So it allowed that sort of flexibility.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:57.000
[Guest]: We have even, I would say, gone back on sovereign promises like the Privy Purses and the titles.

01:21:57.000 --> 01:22:00.000
[Guest]: Now you can look at it two ways and I'll tell you my bias.

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:09.000
[Guest]: One way is that these were sovereign guarantees given by the sovereign state of India to the princely states to join.

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:14.000
[Guest]: So in a way, it was a treaty between two sovereigns.

01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:24.000
[Guest]: And we are unilaterally backing out of our side of the bargain because we are more powerful now than way, way more powerful.

01:22:24.000 --> 01:22:29.000
[Guest]: And we have the power to kick them now.

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:31.000
[Guest]: So it's not the right thing to do.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:41.000
[Guest]: But my bias on the other side, which is that do you want two classes or multiple classes of citizens in a democratic republic?

01:22:41.000 --> 01:22:45.000
[Guest]: OK, just look at Malaysia, for example.

01:22:45.000 --> 01:22:50.000
[Guest]: They have those 13, I think 12 or 13 of those kings and those they take turns.

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:55.000
[Guest]: And one of the princes runs over somebody in a car and he's immune to prosecution.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:23:03.000
[Guest]: Not that a powerful person in India running over a car is not immune to prosecution, but legally that person is not immune to prosecution.

01:23:03.000 --> 01:23:06.000
[Guest]: Whereas in Malaysia, legally that person has immunity.

01:23:06.000 --> 01:23:08.000
[Guest]: OK, do you want that?

01:23:08.000 --> 01:23:11.000
[Guest]: I would or whatever different class of persons.

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:13.000
[Guest]: My bias is no.

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:18.000
[Guest]: At least on paper, in theory, I want all people to be equal.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:28.000
[Guest]: Of course, power structures will never make that, but power structures also say that there is a theoretical possibility for anyone to climb that ladder.

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:32.000
[Guest]: But there is no theoretical possibility for me.

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:39.000
[Guest]: I mean, there is a theoretical possibility for me becoming the prime minister of India, but I cannot become the prince of XYZ state.

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:41.000
[Guest]: I wasn't born to it.

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:43.000
[Guest]: So we actually did that.

01:23:43.000 --> 01:23:44.000
[Guest]: And that was in 1970s.

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:45.000
[Guest]: We went back.

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:51.000
[Guest]: So the flexibility has allowed us to progress also in many, many ways.

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:53.000
[Guest]: So I would say we needed that.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:24:00.000
[Guest]: And while doing and very interesting thing was the 1973 Kesavananda Bharti judgment.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:09.000
[Guest]: Again, my bias is towards the judgment because one argument can be OK, the literal word of the Constitution and not just literal word.

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:15.000
[Guest]: Ambedkar actually said, et cetera, is that we are making the Constitution for our times.

01:24:15.000 --> 01:24:16.000
[Guest]: Times will change.

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:18.000
[Guest]: People should be able to amend it.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:22.000
[Guest]: That's why the amendment is not a very high bar.

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:25.000
[Guest]: The U.S. has had what, 27 amendments?

01:24:25.000 --> 01:24:29.000
[Guest]: And out of which ignore the first 10 because they were in the first two years.

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:35.000
[Guest]: So they effectively had 17 amendments in 130 years.

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:38.000
[Guest]: We have crossed a century long back.

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:40.000
[Guest]: Of course, they don't have a Sachin Tendulkar.

01:24:40.000 --> 01:24:41.000
[Guest]: We have one.

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:44.000
[Guest]: So we know how to score centuries.

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:51.000
[Guest]: We made it amendable, but this one limited the scope of what to the extent that parliament can amend.

01:24:51.000 --> 01:25:04.000
[Guest]: And let me give you a hypothetical scenario, which is that there is somebody who is a fairly powerful prime minister with both houses of parliament, huge majority.

01:25:04.000 --> 01:25:05.000
[Guest]: Today, we don't have that yet.

01:25:05.000 --> 01:25:10.000
[Guest]: But I would say the last one was Rajiv Gandhi.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:12.000
[Guest]: And before that, Indira had, before that, Nehru had.

01:25:12.000 --> 01:25:27.000
[Guest]: They were the people who had more than two thirds majority in both houses and also had their party had more than 50 percent of the states and they were completely in control to the extent one can be over the party system.

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:35.000
[Guest]: Suppose one of them says, OK, Indira says in 1976 emergency that amend the constitution constitutionally.

01:25:35.000 --> 01:25:39.000
[Guest]: This is a monarchy and Sanjay Gandhi will succeed me.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:47.000
[Guest]: OK, if you did not have the basic structure doctrine, this would be constitutionally valid.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:48.000
[Guest]: Would I want that?

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:49.000
[Guest]: No.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:56.000
[Guest]: So I think limiting the power of parliament to change the constitution was also a good thing.

01:25:56.000 --> 01:26:03.000
[Guest]: So what it has evolved into, not originally, is that it is not too difficult to amend, but there are limits to the amendment.

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:05.000
[Guest]: I think we have reached a reasonable bargain.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:09.000
[Guest]: That can always be some better thing, which I don't know about.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:12.000
[Guest]: But I have no problems with that.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:21.000
[Guest]: And again, to me, finally, it is the outcomes which test theory, which is that we have stayed together.

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:22.000
[Guest]: We are one country.

01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:23.000
[Guest]: We are a democracy.

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:32.000
[Guest]: We haven't done too badly, and even on social reform and economic reform, we have actually done fairly, I would say, very well.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:35.000
[Guest]: You know, a few years ago, and I have that quiz.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:39.000
[Guest]: I can redo it at some time.

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:41.000
[Guest]: Just one burst of enthusiasm.

01:26:41.000 --> 01:26:46.000
[Guest]: Just before Independence Day, I just created about 35 questions, which are multiple choice.

01:26:46.000 --> 01:26:47.000
[Guest]: And I sent it to some friends.

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:48.000
[Guest]: People got excited.

01:26:48.000 --> 01:26:52.000
[Guest]: So I just put it on to a couple of my WhatsApp groups and was surprised.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:26:58.000
[Guest]: It was a quiz on India's economy and India's social, this thing.

01:26:58.000 --> 01:27:02.000
[Guest]: For example, what was the infant mortality rate at that year?

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:03.000
[Guest]: What's it now?

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:04.000
[Guest]: How much it has moved?

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:08.000
[Guest]: Which is a sign of, let's say, the HDI or the economy itself.

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:09.000
[Guest]: How much is it?

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:10.000
[Guest]: How many cars did we make?

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:11.000
[Guest]: Then how many do we make now?

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:13.000
[Guest]: What is the food gain production?

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:14.000
[Guest]: What is it now?

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:15.000
[Guest]: What are the railway lines?

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:16.000
[Guest]: What is it now?

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:24.000
[Guest]: On most parameters, we are second to China.

01:27:24.000 --> 01:27:25.000
[Guest]: But we are second.

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:30.000
[Guest]: China is, of course, the biggest outlier in the history of mankind.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:32.000
[Guest]: And we have stated democracy throughout.

01:27:32.000 --> 01:27:34.000
[Guest]: So we are actually not done badly.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:37.000
[Guest]: So as you can see, I'm quite an optimist.

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:38.000
[Amit Varma]: You're an optimist.

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll give four quick counterpoints to different things you said and move on,

01:27:42.000 --> 01:27:43.000
[Amit Varma]: which is not to say I don't agree with you.

01:27:43.000 --> 01:27:47.000
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you, but just to sort of throw these notes out there also.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:51.000
[Amit Varma]: One, I did an episode with Madhav Khosla about his excellent book,

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:54.000
[Amit Varma]: which came out, where he spoke about how part of the purpose of the

01:27:54.000 --> 01:27:59.000
[Amit Varma]: constitution was pedagogic, that you want these values to kind of spread.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:03.000
[Amit Varma]: So you have to spell it out much more in terms of processes.

01:28:03.000 --> 01:28:05.000
[Amit Varma]: So there are no ambiguities.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So in the actual sort of when theory becomes practice, it's easier for that.

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And I understand a transformative urge.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:17.000
[Amit Varma]: My question is that on this one matter, on many matters,

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:20.000
[Amit Varma]: I disagree with Gandhi strongly, but on this one matter,

01:28:20.000 --> 01:28:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I kind of agree with him that the transformative urge could not really work top down.

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:29.000
[Amit Varma]: It had to happen in a more organic way.

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:31.000
[Amit Varma]: You could not change India from the top down.

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And I believe we haven't.

01:28:32.000 --> 01:28:37.000
[Amit Varma]: I believe, in fact, we've, you know, politics has reached where society is now.

01:28:37.000 --> 01:28:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And another counterpoint is when you speak of outcomes.

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are no counterfactuals.

01:28:43.000 --> 01:28:47.000
[Amit Varma]: So we cannot possibly, you know, we could have been worse, but we could have been better.

01:28:47.000 --> 01:28:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And I would say that many of our social problems have not been solved.

01:28:50.000 --> 01:28:51.000
[Guest]: That's a counterfactual.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:53.000
[Guest]: Look across the Western border.

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:55.000
[Guest]: That's a counterfactual.

01:28:55.000 --> 01:28:57.000
[Guest]: That is one counterfactual.

01:28:57.000 --> 01:28:59.000
[Guest]: There are many possible counterfactuals.

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:00.000
[Guest]: I agree we could have been worse.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:02.000
[Amit Varma]: But I also think we could have been better.

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:10.000
[Amit Varma]: And much of what we tried to reform in society from the top down, to my mind, has failed and might have created further divisions.

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:12.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if that works.

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:14.000
[Amit Varma]: I'd also kind of disagree.

01:29:14.000 --> 01:29:19.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I understand your nuanced point of view on the Privy Purses and all of that.

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:23.000
[Amit Varma]: But my sense is that you spoke about two ways of looking at it.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And I find the first way actually slightly more convincing because it addresses the means.

01:29:29.000 --> 01:29:36.000
[Amit Varma]: While the second one seems to say that, A, that the end justifies the means, which I believe should never drive something that you do.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, it seems to imply that they were treated as a separate class, which I don't think is really true.

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:49.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I read a calculation recently about had they continued the Privy Purses, it would have been such a small percentage that it wouldn't have mattered.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:51.000
[Guest]: It's not the money.

01:29:51.000 --> 01:29:52.000
[Guest]: Money is irrelevant.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:53.000
[Guest]: They carried the title.

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:54.000
[Guest]: You have to call them Maharaj.

01:29:54.000 --> 01:29:57.000
[Guest]: I mean, to me, I don't want to call anybody Maharaj.

01:29:57.000 --> 01:30:00.000
[Guest]: They have a right to be called His Highness.

01:30:00.000 --> 01:30:03.000
[Amit Varma]: See, if I don't call someone His Highness, I can go to jail.

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:06.000
[Guest]: I mean, there is a, people will end up calling.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:11.000
[Guest]: I mean, that creates a, there's a feudal structure, which is maintained within a democracy.

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:14.000
[Guest]: Because as you said, society hasn't moved yet.

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:21.000
[Guest]: So you're actually breaking that societal link to the old feudal structure by taking one power away.

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:29.000
[Amit Varma]: So I read in a recent profile of Jyotir Aditya Sindia that when he travels to his native place, everyone calls him Maharaj.

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:30.000
[Amit Varma]: You haven't changed society.

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:32.000
[Guest]: No, but will they call his son and his grandson?

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:33.000
[Guest]: Probably not.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:34.000
[Guest]: It takes time.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:36.000
[Guest]: So, but if you had this, they would call them also.

01:30:36.000 --> 01:30:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:40.000
[Amit Varma]: But my issue really there is with the means.

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, we made them a promise.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:43.000
[Amit Varma]: We broke the promise.

01:30:43.000 --> 01:30:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And my sense actually, and I know many people will disagree with this, but that what Patel and Menon did so extremely well,

01:30:50.000 --> 01:30:56.000
[Amit Varma]: in the years between 47 and 50, was a kind of fast track colonization.

01:30:56.000 --> 01:31:02.000
[Amit Varma]: Where what the British took hundreds of years to do over a period of time, they did in three years, part of it was through coercion.

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And part of it was through promises that they broke later.

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And I understand that we should celebrate that we are one great United Nation today.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And I love this country and I love that aspect of it.

01:31:12.000 --> 01:31:16.000
[Amit Varma]: But it gives me pause that this is how we got here.

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:18.000
[Guest]: Yes, definitely.

01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:23.000
[Guest]: I mean, I also, in general, and in my professional work, always say means matter.

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:31.000
[Guest]: And I mean, that finally, if you follow the right means, on average, you will reach better outcomes than if you don't.

01:31:31.000 --> 01:31:41.000
[Guest]: Because if you, in fact, I wrote against, publicly wrote against the Aadhaar bill being passed as a money bill.

01:31:41.000 --> 01:31:45.000
[Guest]: And I actually wrote in that, that I'm not talking about whether Aadhaar is good or not.

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:46.000
[Guest]: That's not my point.

01:31:46.000 --> 01:31:48.000
[Guest]: My point is that it's not a money bill.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:56.000
[Guest]: And if you think Aadhaar is an important thing and let it get passed, whatever, tomorrow, something you don't like will be passed as a money bill.

01:31:56.000 --> 01:32:00.000
[Guest]: Because you open the way for it and you created a precedent.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:02.000
[Guest]: OK, so I agree with you on that.

01:32:02.000 --> 01:32:04.000
[Guest]: So I don't like that fact.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:12.000
[Guest]: But on the other side, and, you know, interestingly, we had broken the promises right back in 1956 in a very nice way.

01:32:12.000 --> 01:32:25.000
[Guest]: Part of the thing was that these several of these princely state heads, the kings or princes, whatever they were called, they were promised the governorships of where they were called.

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:28.000
[Guest]: So, in fact, the constitution had two different words.

01:32:28.000 --> 01:32:32.000
[Guest]: The princely states cobbled together became a state of India or whatever.

01:32:32.000 --> 01:32:34.000
[Guest]: They were called Raj Brahmukhs.

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:40.000
[Guest]: And the British India, which became a state of India, like Uttar Pradesh, United Provinces, had a governor.

01:32:40.000 --> 01:32:45.000
[Guest]: Nicely, in the Seventh Amendment, we just kicked out the Raj Brahmukhs.

01:32:45.000 --> 01:32:52.000
[Guest]: Essentially, what we did was we recast the states.

01:32:52.000 --> 01:32:56.000
[Guest]: Now, the new state has to have a new governor.

01:32:56.000 --> 01:33:01.000
[Guest]: Part of the new state is not part of what this chap used to be.

01:33:01.000 --> 01:33:05.000
[Guest]: So we gently, we just, the amendment did, OK, no more Raj Brahmukhs, it's a governor.

01:33:05.000 --> 01:33:07.000
[Guest]: And then the centre appoints the governor.

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:15.000
[Guest]: So we have gone back on some of those promises, which, I mean, in general, I would agree with you.

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:24.000
[Guest]: But there are larger objectives where you may have to occasionally break the law to hold the state together.

01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:25.000
[Guest]: OK.

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:27.000
[Unknown]: I mean, otherwise you lose the state.

01:33:27.000 --> 01:33:37.000
[Guest]: I mean, it is like, let's say, if I go back to Mahabharata, the Pandavas were the biggest cheats, right?

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:39.000
[Guest]: I mean, right from the way they killed Bhishma to Dronacharya.

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:43.000
[Guest]: I mean, every major warrior on the other side was killed through deceit.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And I don't think that's justifiable.

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:46.000
[Guest]: Maybe not.

01:33:46.000 --> 01:33:49.000
[Guest]: No, but if they wanted to win the war, there's no other way.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:51.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm not saying morality.

01:33:51.000 --> 01:33:52.000
[Guest]: You also have to win the war.

01:33:52.000 --> 01:33:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Rationality and instrumentality, I get that.

01:33:54.000 --> 01:33:57.000
[Unknown]: You have to win the war, otherwise you've lost everything.

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:02.000
[Guest]: So to win the war, you put on the cloak of morality, but you occasionally cheat.

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:06.000
[Amit Varma]: The one tiny thing I'd add to that, I agree with you.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:08.000
[Amit Varma]: I get what you're saying exactly.

01:34:08.000 --> 01:34:09.000
[Amit Varma]: I won't argue with any of it.

01:34:09.000 --> 01:34:14.000
[Amit Varma]: But the one tiny thing that when you say we, when you use the word we, that we had to hold together.

01:34:14.000 --> 01:34:15.000
[Guest]: I mean the Indian state.

01:34:15.000 --> 01:34:16.000
[Guest]: Correct.

01:34:16.000 --> 01:34:18.000
[Guest]: Because I wasn't even born then.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:19.000
[Guest]: Yeah, exactly.

01:34:19.000 --> 01:34:23.000
[Amit Varma]: And that's a distinction I want to make that I will not use we for that.

01:34:23.000 --> 01:34:26.000
[Amit Varma]: I will say the Indian state wanted to hold together and it'sâ¦

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:28.000
[Guest]: I'm saying we as in we Indians.

01:34:28.000 --> 01:34:29.000
[Guest]: Yeah, yeah.

01:34:29.000 --> 01:34:32.000
[Guest]: Possibly as in we Indians needed to do that.

01:34:32.000 --> 01:34:36.000
[Guest]: I mean, I'm thinking of us all as one community of people as Indians.

01:34:36.000 --> 01:34:37.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:40.000
[Guest]: And of course, the people we stabbed in the back were also Indians.

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:41.000
[Unknown]: Yes.

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:43.000
[Guest]: But I'm not counting them in we.

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:44.000
[Guest]: So maybe I'm being inconsistent.

01:34:44.000 --> 01:34:46.000
[Amit Varma]: That's a very thorny subject.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:49.000
[Amit Varma]: The fourth thing I wanted to kind of talk about wasâ¦

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:53.000
[Amit Varma]: I totally buy what you're saying again about the founding of the American state

01:34:53.000 --> 01:34:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and the imperatives of the elites kind of keeping the position.

01:34:56.000 --> 01:35:01.000
[Amit Varma]: But what the American Constitution did by the time it gained its first stable form

01:35:01.000 --> 01:35:05.000
[Amit Varma]: after the initial bunch of amendments was that it was a brilliant set of rules

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:09.000
[Amit Varma]: devised from first principles which protected every individual.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Like you have also, you know, in the pastâ¦

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:13.000
[Guest]: Every white man.

01:35:13.000 --> 01:35:14.000
[Guest]: Every white man.

01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, sure enough.

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:16.000
[Amit Varma]: But whatever.

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:19.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that principle later got expanded to whatever.

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:25.000
[Amit Varma]: But as what I'm pointing out is that the Indian state is not animated

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:29.000
[Amit Varma]: by a set of first principles that it has held firm to.

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And even when we talk about like the basic doctrine and the 1973 judgment,

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:39.000
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me is that who determines what the basic doctrine is.

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:41.000
[Amit Varma]: On one hand, if you say that with changing times,

01:35:41.000 --> 01:35:44.000
[Amit Varma]: the Constitution can change and values can change,

01:35:44.000 --> 01:35:47.000
[Amit Varma]: then you could argue why shouldn't that basic structure change.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:50.000
[Amit Varma]: On the other hand, you can argue that if there is a set of values

01:35:50.000 --> 01:35:52.000
[Amit Varma]: that is so important that it should never change,

01:35:52.000 --> 01:35:58.000
[Amit Varma]: then it should drive everything else, which is also not the case.

01:35:58.000 --> 01:36:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Because I have a deep unease with some of these changes.

01:36:00.000 --> 01:36:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, when people last year during the CAA protest,

01:36:04.000 --> 01:36:07.000
[Amit Varma]: one of the most heartening things was common people across the country

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:10.000
[Amit Varma]: waving the preamble, which is so important and beautiful.

01:36:10.000 --> 01:36:14.000
[Amit Varma]: But what gave me a moment of unease there was that it was Indira Gandhi's

01:36:14.000 --> 01:36:17.000
[Amit Varma]: amendment of the preamble and not the original Ambedkar version.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:21.000
[Amit Varma]: And to me, that's a problem because that included the word socialist.

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And Indira introduced this clause in the Constitution

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:28.000
[Amit Varma]: that any political party has to declare that it is socialist.

01:36:28.000 --> 01:36:31.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the Swatantra party fought against this.

01:36:31.000 --> 01:36:34.000
[Amit Varma]: SV Raju and all that fought against this because they said what the hell.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, socialism is toxic and kept our country poor for decades.

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:41.000
[Amit Varma]: And you can argue about that.

01:36:41.000 --> 01:36:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But to insist that everybody must pled allegiance to a particular ideology,

01:36:46.000 --> 01:36:49.000
[Amit Varma]: whatever it is, seems to me to just be so wrong.

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And so I don't know if that's considered part of the basic structure or not.

01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:56.000
[Amit Varma]: But I think that's kind of one of the dangers and one of the misgivings I have

01:36:56.000 --> 01:37:00.000
[Amit Varma]: that those animating principles of the US Constitution,

01:37:00.000 --> 01:37:04.000
[Amit Varma]: like they're so clear on free speech that everything that follows from there is clear.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:06.000
[Amit Varma]: You can't really go wrong.

01:37:06.000 --> 01:37:09.000
[Guest]: Not exactly.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:13.000
[Guest]: A lot of it depends upon the way the courts have interpreted it

01:37:13.000 --> 01:37:16.000
[Guest]: over centuries in the US or decades in our case.

01:37:16.000 --> 01:37:22.000
[Guest]: So there is a societal evolution along with that the courts go with the times.

01:37:22.000 --> 01:37:26.000
[Guest]: And, for example, US, there are certain debates they have,

01:37:26.000 --> 01:37:30.000
[Guest]: which I find quite weird, like the biggest one, abortion rights.

01:37:30.000 --> 01:37:32.000
[Guest]: I don't even understand that.

01:37:32.000 --> 01:37:35.000
[Guest]: Or the gun rights. I don't understand that.

01:37:35.000 --> 01:37:40.000
[Guest]: So it's beyond my ability to actually understand what's going on.

01:37:40.000 --> 01:37:43.000
[Guest]: So every society has its own problems.

01:37:43.000 --> 01:37:46.000
[Guest]: The grass looks greener on the other side.

01:37:46.000 --> 01:37:49.000
[Guest]: So coming back to this thing about, I would say,

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:54.000
[Guest]: the core principles are primarily in the preamble.

01:37:54.000 --> 01:37:59.000
[Guest]: And frankly, socialism, yes, she added it.

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:01.000
[Guest]: Is it such a big deal?

01:38:01.000 --> 01:38:08.000
[Guest]: Well, if you were a very textual idealist, yes, it's a big deal.

01:38:08.000 --> 01:38:11.000
[Guest]: On a practical sense, irrelevant.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:12.000
[Guest]: Irrelevant.

01:38:12.000 --> 01:38:15.000
[Guest]: It is like, I mean, I can be a Hindu and an atheist.

01:38:15.000 --> 01:38:17.000
[Guest]: I can be a Hindu and a Vaishnava.

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:19.000
[Guest]: I can be a Hindu and a Shaivite.

01:38:19.000 --> 01:38:24.000
[Guest]: I can be an Indian, extremely libertarian pro-market and a socialist.

01:38:24.000 --> 01:38:25.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:28.000
[Unknown]: So it means nothing.

01:38:28.000 --> 01:38:34.000
[Guest]: So if it just added some, okay, somebody a pat on the back and move on.

01:38:34.000 --> 01:38:38.000
[Guest]: If words don't mean anything, then the constitution doesn't mean anything.

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:41.000
[Guest]: A word like socialist in the Indian context,

01:38:41.000 --> 01:38:44.000
[Guest]: the Supreme Court has actually interpreted it because there is a case.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:47.000
[Guest]: It said, so that was a nice part, right?

01:38:47.000 --> 01:38:49.000
[Guest]: I mean, I don't know whether you know about the Supreme Court.

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:54.000
[Guest]: So there was a case to the Supreme Court to remove the word socialist from the constitution.

01:38:54.000 --> 01:38:55.000
[Guest]: That is basic.

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:58.000
[Guest]: They also said socialist, you can interpret in any way.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:03.000
[Unknown]: So in a way, legally in India, socialist means nothing

01:39:03.000 --> 01:39:08.000
[Guest]: because the authority which interprets what socialist means has said so.

01:39:10.000 --> 01:39:11.000
[Amit Varma]: I guess that's fair enough.

01:39:11.000 --> 01:39:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know many people who think socialist means working for society,

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:16.000
[Amit Varma]: which is actually...

01:39:16.000 --> 01:39:18.000
[Unknown]: They said working for society.

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:20.000
[Unknown]: In effect, it's the opposite.

01:39:20.000 --> 01:39:25.000
[Guest]: But let's, I mean, nobody really bothers about it, so it's fine.

01:39:25.000 --> 01:39:26.000
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

01:39:26.000 --> 01:39:29.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's now come to PRS.

01:39:29.000 --> 01:39:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's start talking about the Indian Parliament because there's kind of so much to talk about.

01:39:34.000 --> 01:39:38.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's first go back to your biographical journey for a moment

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:41.000
[Amit Varma]: before coming to Parliament and talking about how Parliament functions

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:43.000
[Amit Varma]: and what it is and all of that.

01:39:43.000 --> 01:39:46.000
[Amit Varma]: So when you decided to start PRS,

01:39:46.000 --> 01:39:50.000
[Amit Varma]: one, what were the early misconceptions you had about your venture which got corrected?

01:39:50.000 --> 01:39:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Because whenever we start something, we see the world in a particular way

01:39:54.000 --> 01:39:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and very soon we are mugged by reality as it were

01:39:57.000 --> 01:40:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and we realize things are kind of different and, you know, move along those paths.

01:40:01.000 --> 01:40:03.000
[Amit Varma]: So what were the early days of PRS like?

01:40:03.000 --> 01:40:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Like what was your early vision and how was that modified?

01:40:07.000 --> 01:40:12.000
[Amit Varma]: And were there things which gave you reason to pause and say, is this going to work out?

01:40:12.000 --> 01:40:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And were there reasons in the initial days which gave you hope and said, yes, I'm so glad I did this?

01:40:18.000 --> 01:40:23.000
[Guest]: OK, in a way, it was relatively easy for me because I didn't have too many preconceptions.

01:40:23.000 --> 01:40:25.000
[Guest]: I didn't know much about it.

01:40:25.000 --> 01:40:31.000
[Guest]: OK, so it was, as I said, Madhukar was the original ideator behind.

01:40:31.000 --> 01:40:32.000
[Guest]: He was a good friend.

01:40:32.000 --> 01:40:35.000
[Guest]: I thought it would be fun doing something like this.

01:40:35.000 --> 01:40:41.000
[Guest]: And I told Madhukar when we started that I am willing to put two years.

01:40:41.000 --> 01:40:44.000
[Guest]: We have no idea whether MPs will use our stuff.

01:40:44.000 --> 01:40:46.000
[Guest]: Nobody has done this before.

01:40:46.000 --> 01:40:51.000
[Guest]: Personally, the number of MPs I met before PRS is zero.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:55.000
[Guest]: I'd never met an MP in my life, like most people of our class.

01:40:55.000 --> 01:40:58.000
[Guest]: Why would you meet an MP? I was working in the finance industry in Bombay.

01:40:58.000 --> 01:41:01.000
[Guest]: There's no reason for me to meet a member of parliament.

01:41:01.000 --> 01:41:07.000
[Guest]: The one person whom I had met who happened to be a member of parliament, which was Dr. Bimal Jalan,

01:41:07.000 --> 01:41:11.000
[Guest]: he was a nominated member, he was an RBI governor, and in my interest rate,

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:15.000
[Guest]: when my boss had a meeting with him, he had tagged along to that meeting.

01:41:15.000 --> 01:41:19.000
[Guest]: So I had been in a room with him in a small, us and him meeting.

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:21.000
[Guest]: That's the only MP I'd ever met in my life.

01:41:21.000 --> 01:41:23.000
[Guest]: So I said, you don't know what this is.

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:31.000
[Guest]: Let's say at the end of two years, if nobody uses, I have a reasonable enough CV that somebody will give me a job.

01:41:31.000 --> 01:41:35.000
[Guest]: So I don't have worries and I have no liabilities.

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:37.000
[Guest]: I'd never taken a loan in my life.

01:41:37.000 --> 01:41:40.000
[Guest]: So that gives me the freedom to do things.

01:41:40.000 --> 01:41:43.000
[Guest]: If I'm not using that freedom, then I'm wasting that freedom.

01:41:43.000 --> 01:41:45.000
[Guest]: So let me go on an adventure.

01:41:45.000 --> 01:41:47.000
[Guest]: That was the idea.

01:41:47.000 --> 01:41:55.000
[Guest]: Skillsets, I had been writing research on interest rates, currencies, economy, etc.

01:41:55.000 --> 01:42:02.000
[Guest]: In an extremely competitive market, because you're all writing for some hedge fund guys and there are multiple people.

01:42:02.000 --> 01:42:05.000
[Guest]: So why should somebody read your research?

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:13.000
[Guest]: So that hones you and people train you how to write in a manner which is sharp and focused and which people will read and understand.

01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:15.000
[Guest]: So I had that skill set.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:17.000
[Guest]: Domain knowledge is zero.

01:42:17.000 --> 01:42:22.000
[Guest]: I didn't write a bill or an act in my life before.

01:42:22.000 --> 01:42:25.000
[Guest]: So I said, OK, so I jumped into it.

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:30.000
[Guest]: There's only actually one word which will capture what I did.

01:42:30.000 --> 01:42:32.000
[Guest]: I think it's called foolhardy.

01:42:32.000 --> 01:42:34.000
[Guest]: OK, it was a foolhardy venture.

01:42:34.000 --> 01:42:37.000
[Guest]: OK, but the idea was, let's see what happens.

01:42:37.000 --> 01:42:44.000
[Guest]: So we wrote our first brief, which was so we OK, before that, we know we want to start this.

01:42:44.000 --> 01:42:46.000
[Guest]: Madhukar had done it. He was in the US.

01:42:46.000 --> 01:42:49.000
[Guest]: He had come back on a trip and he had met a bunch of people.

01:42:49.000 --> 01:42:58.000
[Guest]: And one of the very good advice he had got from someone earlier who knew the Indian system was that don't try to set up something independent initially.

01:42:58.000 --> 01:43:04.000
[Guest]: Find a good think tank or any research organization which can host you.

01:43:04.000 --> 01:43:13.000
[Guest]: Because otherwise you will be spending your time trying to get your income tax exemption and ATG and this and that.

01:43:13.000 --> 01:43:15.000
[Guest]: And you might have an initial grant.

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:19.000
[Guest]: But by the time you get these and started, your time is over.

01:43:19.000 --> 01:43:24.000
[Guest]: So find somebody to get the proof of concept out.

01:43:24.000 --> 01:43:28.000
[Guest]: Start working and see whether it works, then figure out.

01:43:28.000 --> 01:43:30.000
[Guest]: So he met a number of people.

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:36.000
[Guest]: One of them happened to be Pratap Bhanu Mehta, who was then at the Center for Policy Research and CPR.

01:43:36.000 --> 01:43:38.000
[Guest]: And something clicked and CPR was up.

01:43:38.000 --> 01:43:41.000
[Guest]: And in hindsight, we were there for seven years.

01:43:41.000 --> 01:43:43.000
[Guest]: That was a very important move.

01:43:43.000 --> 01:43:50.000
[Guest]: So we got we started off as a project of CPR, which meant we had the umbrella to work under.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:44:00.000
[Guest]: Pratap was there, which was great and very important thing about CPR, which still is today, is that unlike many other think tanks, for example, CCS.

01:44:00.000 --> 01:44:03.000
[Guest]: CCS has a very clear house view.

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:10.000
[Guest]: We couldn't have been there because certain parties will not want that particular outlook.

01:44:10.000 --> 01:44:13.000
[Guest]: CPR doesn't have any ideology.

01:44:13.000 --> 01:44:18.000
[Guest]: It's a bunch of different people with possibly opposite ideologies working under the same roof.

01:44:18.000 --> 01:44:20.000
[Guest]: It's like a university in that sense.

01:44:20.000 --> 01:44:23.000
[Guest]: So that we needed that shelter.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:26.000
[Guest]: They were a well-known, well-regarded think tank in Delhi.

01:44:26.000 --> 01:44:32.000
[Guest]: They were located in Chanakya Puri, which always helps because you're like pretty close by to because you're going to meet MPs.

01:44:32.000 --> 01:44:34.000
[Guest]: You're a 10 minute drive away.

01:44:34.000 --> 01:44:37.000
[Guest]: You're not a 50 minute drive away for everything.

01:44:37.000 --> 01:44:39.000
[Guest]: So CPR worked out well.

01:44:39.000 --> 01:44:43.000
[Guest]: It gave us a good intellectual place to work out of.

01:44:43.000 --> 01:44:44.000
[Guest]: There's lots of things happen there.

01:44:44.000 --> 01:44:46.000
[Guest]: So you also meet lots of other people.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:48.000
[Guest]: Other interesting people are working there.

01:44:48.000 --> 01:44:49.000
[Guest]: They're holding events.

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:52.000
[Guest]: Of course, at that time, CPR, I mean, Pratap started building it back.

01:44:52.000 --> 01:44:54.000
[Guest]: It had gone down.

01:44:54.000 --> 01:44:56.000
[Guest]: But it was a great place to work with.

01:44:56.000 --> 01:44:59.000
[Guest]: So we started at CPR.

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:01.000
[Guest]: We wrote our first brief.

01:45:01.000 --> 01:45:04.000
[Guest]: Pratap's suggestion was that do something on it.

01:45:04.000 --> 01:45:07.000
[Guest]: So he said write to education draft bill was out.

01:45:07.000 --> 01:45:09.000
[Guest]: And Madhukar had worked in that field for years.

01:45:09.000 --> 01:45:13.000
[Guest]: So he said, OK, work somewhere where you have some domain knowledge and you know people.

01:45:13.000 --> 01:45:15.000
[Guest]: So he wrote the first brief.

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:17.000
[Guest]: We sent it out to every MP.

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:23.000
[Guest]: We printed it, put it in envelopes, Delhi address on top and just sent it to MPs with a cover letter.

01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:27.000
[Guest]: We wrote the second one, which was on the pension fund bill.

01:45:27.000 --> 01:45:32.000
[Guest]: I had some domain background and new people I could talk to, sent it out.

01:45:32.000 --> 01:45:35.000
[Guest]: Then some people started calling us.

01:45:35.000 --> 01:45:37.000
[Guest]: Because everything had a cover letter that we are doing this.

01:45:37.000 --> 01:45:40.000
[Guest]: And if you want on this or any other issue in Parliament, let us know.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:45.000
[Guest]: So over a period of the next six months, we are also trying to meet MPs etc.

01:45:45.000 --> 01:45:49.000
[Guest]: About 60-70 MPs have started reaching out to us.

01:45:49.000 --> 01:45:52.000
[Guest]: And of two years, the number at was 100.

01:45:52.000 --> 01:45:55.000
[Guest]: So I said, OK, there is a market for this.

01:45:55.000 --> 01:45:58.000
[Guest]: Because you don't even know whether they want it or not.

01:45:58.000 --> 01:46:03.000
[Guest]: People want, people are looking for research content.

01:46:03.000 --> 01:46:08.000
[Guest]: If we can provide them in a format which they can use, which they can understand, which they can appreciate.

01:46:08.000 --> 01:46:10.000
[Guest]: And they are calling us for briefings.

01:46:10.000 --> 01:46:16.000
[Guest]: So on deliberately our briefs, we put an upper page limit of six pages,

01:46:16.000 --> 01:46:20.000
[Guest]: which includes a cover summary page, which has only 10 bullets.

01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:21.000
[Guest]: Outstanding.

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:25.000
[Guest]: We said, if I send a 50-page note, people will say, yes, it is good.

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:28.000
[Guest]: I will read it with the intention of reading it.

01:46:28.000 --> 01:46:29.000
[Guest]: They'll keep it on the desk.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:31.000
[Guest]: Then multiple other things will pile on.

01:46:31.000 --> 01:46:36.000
[Guest]: If it is two pages, if you get something which is two pages, you won't put it on the site.

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:40.000
[Guest]: You'll say, oh, two pages, let me just glance through it before I file it away or keep it.

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:46.000
[Guest]: So six pages included a maximum of two pages of what's in the bill.

01:46:46.000 --> 01:46:53.000
[Guest]: And three pages, including all references and citations of our analysis.

01:46:53.000 --> 01:46:56.000
[Guest]: So typically two, two and a half something and half page or one page for that.

01:46:56.000 --> 01:47:00.000
[Guest]: And everything that's written, if there's any number cited, any argument made,

01:47:00.000 --> 01:47:03.000
[Guest]: this is a citation about the source.

01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:06.000
[Guest]: So you can verify the credibility of what you're saying.

01:47:06.000 --> 01:47:08.000
[Guest]: And we don't take a view.

01:47:08.000 --> 01:47:09.000
[Guest]: So people coming back.

01:47:09.000 --> 01:47:15.000
[Guest]: By the time 2009 election happened, we had over 200 people reaching out to us.

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:16.000
[Guest]: OK.

01:47:16.000 --> 01:47:19.000
[Guest]: 225 or something, if I remember correctly.

01:47:19.000 --> 01:47:21.000
[Guest]: Elections happened.

01:47:21.000 --> 01:47:28.000
[Guest]: So February 2009, we had about 225 people reaching out to us, current MPs.

01:47:28.000 --> 01:47:33.000
[Guest]: May 2005, this had come down to 100 odd because 100 of them vanished.

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:41.000
[Guest]: But then, by then, word of mouth between them and our work had started getting appreciation.

01:47:41.000 --> 01:47:43.000
[Guest]: So we built back.

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:49.000
[Guest]: So every election cycle, we have built back up to 400 plus MPs.

01:47:49.000 --> 01:47:52.000
[Guest]: I'm talking about 700, not 525.

01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:54.000
[Guest]: Lok Sabha plus Rajya Sabha.

01:47:54.000 --> 01:47:59.000
[Guest]: The numbers are, there are 790 or 788 now.

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:02.000
[Guest]: 245 Rajya Sabha and 543 Lok Sabha.

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:04.000
[Guest]: Then there were 545 because there are two Anglo-Indians.

01:48:04.000 --> 01:48:05.000
[Guest]: We're no longer there.

01:48:05.000 --> 01:48:09.000
[Guest]: Out of it, roughly, let's say 90 are ministers, 80-90.

01:48:09.000 --> 01:48:12.000
[Guest]: Ministers go on a different trip because they have their own thing.

01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:18.000
[Guest]: So my potential audience is 700.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:21.000
[Guest]: Out of 700, we are reaching out to more than half.

01:48:21.000 --> 01:48:24.000
[Guest]: When I say reaching out, we sent everybody, how many are calling me?

01:48:24.000 --> 01:48:26.000
[Guest]: What is the pull, not the push?

01:48:26.000 --> 01:48:29.000
[Guest]: Push is 790, pull is 400 type.

01:48:29.000 --> 01:48:30.000
[Guest]: That's been there.

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:32.000
[Guest]: Of course, there's a variation, high and low.

01:48:32.000 --> 01:48:33.000
[Guest]: How many?

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:43.000
[Guest]: So the market feedback, it's worth doing simply because what is the resource they are spending on this?

01:48:43.000 --> 01:48:46.000
[Guest]: They're spending time, which is their most valuable resource.

01:48:46.000 --> 01:48:54.000
[Guest]: If they're spending time doing this and they are reaching out to us, probably we are doing something that they find useful.

01:48:54.000 --> 01:48:56.000
[Guest]: Otherwise, they won't do it.

01:48:56.000 --> 01:49:00.000
[Guest]: That is my market feedback.

01:49:00.000 --> 01:49:02.000
[Guest]: And therefore, it's worth doing.

01:49:02.000 --> 01:49:05.000
[Guest]: So that's how it started.

01:49:05.000 --> 01:49:09.000
[Guest]: So that was the starting part.

01:49:09.000 --> 01:49:15.000
[Guest]: Then as we started, the original idea, in fact, our original node said legislation

01:49:15.000 --> 01:49:24.000
[Guest]: because the idea was that even a minor change in a bill can have a large scale effect.

01:49:24.000 --> 01:49:29.000
[Guest]: I can give you the easiest example for people to understand.

01:49:29.000 --> 01:49:39.000
[Guest]: The many easiest example, simplest example is there was an amendment about a couple of, I mean, during the NDA,

01:49:39.000 --> 01:49:46.000
[Guest]: I don't know what to call it, NDA 1, 2, whatever, essentially 2014 to 19 NDA, not counting the Vajpayee NDA.

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:56.000
[Guest]: During this government, there was an amendment to the Forest Act where they clarify that bamboo is not a tree, but a grass.

01:49:56.000 --> 01:49:58.000
[Unknown]: That's all, simple one.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:05.000
[Guest]: What that meant was you can't cut a tree in India without prior permission.

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:11.000
[Guest]: You can't cut grass, which essentially revitalized the bamboo products industry.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:13.000
[Guest]: Now you can grow bamboo.

01:50:13.000 --> 01:50:15.000
[Guest]: Bamboo has a lot of bamboo products.

01:50:15.000 --> 01:50:17.000
[Guest]: I can do that.

01:50:17.000 --> 01:50:19.000
[Guest]: One line.

01:50:19.000 --> 01:50:25.000
[Guest]: Or let me say, I'm not saying whether it's a good thing or a bad thing because there's an ideology involved,

01:50:25.000 --> 01:50:28.000
[Guest]: but I'll say it's a high impact thing, good or bad.

01:50:28.000 --> 01:50:38.000
[Guest]: The Right to Education Act has that one clause which says all private schools have to reserve 25% of their seats for economically weaker sections.

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:41.000
[Guest]: This is one line.

01:50:41.000 --> 01:50:43.000
[Guest]: Impact is high.

01:50:43.000 --> 01:50:54.000
[Guest]: So laws make, and sometimes just a comma or a, in fact, there's a famous judgment, which in the US interpretation,

01:50:54.000 --> 01:50:59.000
[Guest]: which is if you Google, you should find, I don't remember exactly what it was, it was about something about a trucker,

01:50:59.000 --> 01:51:02.000
[Guest]: but the Oxford comma made the difference.

01:51:02.000 --> 01:51:03.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:51:03.000 --> 01:51:04.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

01:51:04.000 --> 01:51:11.000
[Guest]: So that comma or the lack of a comma made the codes interpreted in a different way and makes an impact.

01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:13.000
[Guest]: So even a comma or a full stop or a semicolon makes a difference.

01:51:13.000 --> 01:51:19.000
[Guest]: So we said, okay, we need to make sure that our laws are well thought out and clearly written.

01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:21.000
[Guest]: That is our purpose because that will have an impact.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:28.000
[Guest]: As we started doing and working, MPs started coming to us and asking us for other things.

01:51:28.000 --> 01:51:34.000
[Guest]: So there is this discussion happening on, let's say, price rise.

01:51:34.000 --> 01:51:37.000
[Guest]: I want to speak on that.

01:51:37.000 --> 01:51:39.000
[Guest]: Do you have any material?

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:42.000
[Guest]: So we write a note and give it to them.

01:51:42.000 --> 01:51:48.000
[Guest]: So we started getting requests on other things being discussed in Parliament.

01:51:48.000 --> 01:51:52.000
[Guest]: We started getting requests on budgets.

01:51:52.000 --> 01:51:53.000
[Guest]: I need to speak on the budget.

01:51:53.000 --> 01:51:55.000
[Guest]: The party has asked me to speak.

01:51:55.000 --> 01:51:58.000
[Guest]: Have you done an analysis?

01:51:58.000 --> 01:52:06.000
[Guest]: So over a period of time, we evolved our work to say that what is driving us?

01:52:06.000 --> 01:52:08.000
[Guest]: Actually, the driver is not Parliament.

01:52:08.000 --> 01:52:10.000
[Guest]: Parliament is an instrument.

01:52:10.000 --> 01:52:18.000
[Guest]: The driver is that if we want lives of citizens of this country to be better, I'm loosely

01:52:18.000 --> 01:52:24.000
[Guest]: defining the word better because it has many other things, but this thing, we need better

01:52:24.000 --> 01:52:31.000
[Guest]: thought out and written laws and government to be held to account, budgets to be done,

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:32.000
[Guest]: which are all Parliament's job.

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:40.000
[Guest]: We need Parliament to work more effectively or if Parliament works more effectively, then

01:52:40.000 --> 01:52:44.000
[Guest]: people will have, I mean, it serves citizens better.

01:52:44.000 --> 01:52:46.000
[Guest]: And the final target is citizens.

01:52:46.000 --> 01:52:50.000
[Guest]: And finally, why do I care about this MP or that MP?

01:52:50.000 --> 01:52:54.000
[Guest]: They are the root to the citizen.

01:52:54.000 --> 01:53:02.000
[Guest]: So we should therefore support MPs with research on all the things that come up in Parliament.

01:53:02.000 --> 01:53:04.000
[Guest]: We started doing that.

01:53:04.000 --> 01:53:11.000
[Guest]: Parallelly, what happened was MPs started pushing us individually at one-on-one meetings.

01:53:11.000 --> 01:53:16.000
[Guest]: Somebody will say Parliament still has reasonable systems.

01:53:16.000 --> 01:53:18.000
[Guest]: There's a good library.

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:20.000
[Guest]: Parliament is an excellent library.

01:53:20.000 --> 01:53:24.000
[Guest]: There are standing committees, which by and large work.

01:53:24.000 --> 01:53:28.000
[Guest]: But my state is in a bad shape.

01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:31.000
[Guest]: Can you do something for my state legislature?

01:53:31.000 --> 01:53:37.000
[Guest]: We were a team, at that time our research team was a grand total of three people, including

01:53:37.000 --> 01:53:38.000
[Guest]: me.

01:53:38.000 --> 01:53:41.000
[Guest]: 28 states, three or four people.

01:53:41.000 --> 01:53:43.000
[Guest]: Sorry, can't do.

01:53:43.000 --> 01:53:50.000
[Guest]: But over a period of time, we realized that if we go back to what is our core purpose,

01:53:50.000 --> 01:53:54.000
[Guest]: citizens, and if you look at the Constitution, back to the Constitution, and you look at

01:53:54.000 --> 01:54:03.000
[Guest]: the seventh schedule, many things that affect people directly are either state list or concurrent

01:54:03.000 --> 01:54:06.000
[Guest]: list, which means implementation by states more or less.

01:54:06.000 --> 01:54:12.000
[Guest]: And if you're not looking at state legislatures, we are fooling ourselves by saying we are

01:54:12.000 --> 01:54:13.000
[Guest]: doing this.

01:54:13.000 --> 01:54:15.000
[Guest]: So we need to do it.

01:54:15.000 --> 01:54:16.000
[Guest]: It's a question of timing.

01:54:16.000 --> 01:54:19.000
[Guest]: Should we do it this year, next year, two years down the line?

01:54:19.000 --> 01:54:22.000
[Guest]: But we should be doing it.

01:54:22.000 --> 01:54:24.000
[Guest]: That was the decision we took.

01:54:24.000 --> 01:54:25.000
[Guest]: We took that in 2000.

01:54:25.000 --> 01:54:30.000
[Guest]: We had started late 2005, 2008, we said, OK, we need to do this.

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:33.000
[Guest]: And by 2011 or something, we started reaching out slowly.

01:54:33.000 --> 01:54:37.000
[Guest]: Now we are working across many, many states.

01:54:37.000 --> 01:54:40.000
[Guest]: Again, most state legislatures are in a bad shape.

01:54:40.000 --> 01:54:43.000
[Guest]: And there's no point as of now having people there.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:50.000
[Guest]: If a state legislature meets for 25 days a year, and if there is a PRS person sitting

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:55.000
[Guest]: in that state capital, what does that person do for the remaining 340 days of the year

01:54:55.000 --> 01:54:57.000
[Guest]: or 330 days of the year?

01:54:57.000 --> 01:55:00.000
[Guest]: So we have only one office in Delhi.

01:55:00.000 --> 01:55:04.000
[Guest]: What we do is when the legislature meets, people travel there.

01:55:04.000 --> 01:55:06.000
[Guest]: I mean, there's a four-day session.

01:55:06.000 --> 01:55:09.000
[Guest]: So you just go and park in a hotel for those four days and come back.

01:55:09.000 --> 01:55:12.000
[Guest]: It is way more efficient than having an office there.

01:55:12.000 --> 01:55:15.000
[Guest]: So we are working across states.

01:55:15.000 --> 01:55:16.000
[Guest]: We are working here.

01:55:16.000 --> 01:55:19.000
[Guest]: So again, similar stuff in states.

01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:24.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, one of the big restrictions, it seems to me here, is the structure of parliament

01:55:24.000 --> 01:55:29.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that the anti-defection law of the 1980s, and I had an episode on this way

01:55:29.000 --> 01:55:35.000
[Amit Varma]: back, essentially means that you can run parliament from the top down with an Excel sheet.

01:55:35.000 --> 01:55:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Because basically what the anti-defection law is, it forces members of parliament to

01:55:40.000 --> 01:55:44.000
[Amit Varma]: vote not according to their individual conscience, but whatever is a party line.

01:55:44.000 --> 01:55:46.000
[Amit Varma]: You're given a whip, you got to vote.

01:55:46.000 --> 01:55:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So let's say that in that game too, where parliamentarians educate themselves about

01:55:50.000 --> 01:55:54.000
[Amit Varma]: everything that is at stake, if they come to a different conclusion from their party,

01:55:54.000 --> 01:56:00.000
[Amit Varma]: they can actually do nothing about it, you know, even if they come to a different conclusion.

01:56:00.000 --> 01:56:03.000
[Amit Varma]: So how frustrating has this been for you?

01:56:03.000 --> 01:56:05.000
[Amit Varma]: And what is the flip side of this?

01:56:05.000 --> 01:56:07.000
[Amit Varma]: Because obviously you're getting a lot done.

01:56:07.000 --> 01:56:10.000
[Amit Varma]: So what are the processes through which that happens?

01:56:10.000 --> 01:56:11.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:56:11.000 --> 01:56:12.000
[Guest]: I completely agree.

01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:16.000
[Guest]: In fact, if there is one thing of which I am an evangelist, it is that the anti-defection

01:56:16.000 --> 01:56:17.000
[Guest]: law should go.

01:56:17.000 --> 01:56:20.000
[Guest]: I've written about it many, many times.

01:56:20.000 --> 01:56:24.000
[Guest]: I mean, give me an opportunity to talk about Indian cricket team.

01:56:24.000 --> 01:56:28.000
[Guest]: I'll bring in the anti-defection somewhere and talk about it for five minutes.

01:56:28.000 --> 01:56:32.000
[Guest]: So when I was talking to you, I was thinking, it was in the back of the mind, how do I bring

01:56:32.000 --> 01:56:34.000
[Guest]: that in if you did not bring that in?

01:56:34.000 --> 01:56:36.000
[Guest]: One has to bring it in, it's central.

01:56:36.000 --> 01:56:38.000
[Guest]: I knew you would, so I waited.

01:56:38.000 --> 01:56:40.000
[Guest]: That's my pet theme in any case.

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:46.000
[Guest]: I think anti-defection is completely, and the Supreme Court erred on that, basic structure,

01:56:46.000 --> 01:56:47.000
[Guest]: incorrect.

01:56:47.000 --> 01:56:50.000
[Guest]: I'll tell you why in multiple ways.

01:56:50.000 --> 01:56:53.000
[Guest]: It's not just in one way.

01:56:53.000 --> 01:56:58.000
[Guest]: First thing, what is the, how do you think of a legislator or an elected representative?

01:56:58.000 --> 01:57:04.000
[Guest]: Broadly, there are two ways in which people have conceived the role of, let's say an MP.

01:57:04.000 --> 01:57:07.000
[Guest]: When I say an MP, I mean an MLA also in this, right?

01:57:07.000 --> 01:57:12.000
[Guest]: One is the Burke thing, where the Burke made that very famous speech, which I would actually

01:57:12.000 --> 01:57:15.000
[Guest]: recommend people to read because it's all of four pages.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:16.000
[Guest]: I'll link it in the show notes.

01:57:16.000 --> 01:57:21.000
[Guest]: It's a five minute read, where he talks to the electors of Bristol after the election,

01:57:21.000 --> 01:57:30.000
[Guest]: which he says that you effectively, he says that my job is to exercise my judgment for

01:57:30.000 --> 01:57:39.000
[Guest]: the betterment of the whole country and not be your agent to do what you want me to do.

01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:45.000
[Guest]: And he also goes on to say that I am betraying you if you don't exercise my judgment because

01:57:45.000 --> 01:57:46.000
[Guest]: that is my job.

01:57:46.000 --> 01:57:53.000
[Guest]: I mean, think of it like, let's say that I am the CEO of a publicly registered company.

01:57:53.000 --> 01:57:58.000
[Guest]: I'm not asking the shareholder to take, tell me what to do every time.

01:57:58.000 --> 01:58:02.000
[Guest]: I am exercising my judgment to do things.

01:58:02.000 --> 01:58:09.000
[Guest]: A good CEO is exercising his or her judgment to do things which will benefit the shareholder

01:58:09.000 --> 01:58:12.000
[Guest]: and not act as the direct agents asking them every time, right?

01:58:12.000 --> 01:58:13.000
[Guest]: Or the board does.

01:58:13.000 --> 01:58:17.000
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's a quote from Burke which says this as well from that letter, where

01:58:17.000 --> 01:58:22.000
[Amit Varma]: he writes, your representative owes you not his industry only, but his judgment.

01:58:22.000 --> 01:58:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:58:23.000 --> 01:58:27.000
[Amit Varma]: And he betrays instead of serving you if he sacrifices it to your opinion.

01:58:27.000 --> 01:58:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:58:28.000 --> 01:58:33.000
[Amit Varma]: Thereby giving that nuance that the job of a citizen in a democracy is not just to elect

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:38.000
[Amit Varma]: someone who will do what you want him to do, but to elect people of good judgment, whose

01:58:38.000 --> 01:58:39.000
[Amit Varma]: judgment you trust.

01:58:39.000 --> 01:58:40.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:58:40.000 --> 01:58:45.000
[Guest]: I mean, this is, this is the quote that I was, I mean, I couldn't remember the exact

01:58:45.000 --> 01:58:47.000
[Guest]: quote, but this is what I tried to paraphrase.

01:58:47.000 --> 01:58:48.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:49.000
[Guest]: That's one notion.

01:58:49.000 --> 01:58:57.000
[Guest]: The second notion, which is that is effectively people are elected and he's supposed to further

01:58:57.000 --> 01:59:02.000
[Guest]: their, he or she is to further their interests, because that is what, because you are the

01:59:02.000 --> 01:59:03.000
[Guest]: representative.

01:59:03.000 --> 01:59:05.000
[Guest]: So you are representing them.

01:59:05.000 --> 01:59:07.000
[Guest]: So I am in a constituency.

01:59:07.000 --> 01:59:08.000
[Guest]: There's something coming up.

01:59:08.000 --> 01:59:10.000
[Guest]: This is good or bad for the constituency.

01:59:10.000 --> 01:59:16.000
[Guest]: I will react or vote in a way which benefits the people I am representing.

01:59:16.000 --> 01:59:20.000
[Guest]: There's a second notion, which is generally the delegate concept.

01:59:20.000 --> 01:59:21.000
[Guest]: Agreed.

01:59:21.000 --> 01:59:26.000
[Guest]: I mean, I'm not, my own bias is towards the first, but let's take the second for what.

01:59:26.000 --> 01:59:33.000
[Guest]: It's also a notion worth considering and people, I mean, I have respect for that position.

01:59:33.000 --> 01:59:40.000
[Guest]: What we have done is we have made the MP a delegate of the party leadership, neither

01:59:40.000 --> 01:59:43.000
[Guest]: of the constituency nor of his or her own judgment.

01:59:43.000 --> 01:59:45.000
[Guest]: We have just converted that.

01:59:45.000 --> 01:59:48.000
[Guest]: So we have completely taken away the concept of a representative.

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:52.000
[Guest]: Now comes the second rank, which is that.

01:59:52.000 --> 01:59:54.000
[Guest]: How does a good democracy work?

01:59:54.000 --> 01:59:55.000
[Guest]: Okay.

01:59:55.000 --> 01:59:59.000
[Guest]: Let's take for, for all its flaws, the US is a reasonably good democracy because it

01:59:59.000 --> 02:00:04.000
[Guest]: is sustained 200 years and we have all, and also because it makes good TV.

02:00:04.000 --> 02:00:05.000
[Guest]: So we have all watched it.

02:00:05.000 --> 02:00:07.000
[Guest]: So we are familiar with it.

02:00:07.000 --> 02:00:11.000
[Guest]: I mean, there may be many other good ones, but we don't have the familiarity.

02:00:11.000 --> 02:00:16.000
[Guest]: So when there is a presidential, there's a debate for the president of the US or the

02:00:16.000 --> 02:00:22.000
[Guest]: primaries and there is some senator there, people ask and very often ask, there was this

02:00:22.000 --> 02:00:23.000
[Guest]: Iraq vote.

02:00:23.000 --> 02:00:24.000
[Guest]: How did you vote?

02:00:24.000 --> 02:00:25.000
[Guest]: Why did you vote on this?

02:00:25.000 --> 02:00:26.000
[Guest]: There's some other vote.

02:00:26.000 --> 02:00:27.000
[Guest]: What is right?

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:37.000
[Guest]: So your actions in parliament, the voter is evaluating and using that to decide whether

02:00:37.000 --> 02:00:39.000
[Guest]: you need another chance.

02:00:39.000 --> 02:00:46.000
[Guest]: And in fact, that is the core of representative democracy, that you are answerable to the

02:00:46.000 --> 02:00:49.000
[Guest]: electorate every five years.

02:00:49.000 --> 02:00:52.000
[Guest]: And if you have not performed, you will be kicked out.

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:58.000
[Guest]: Once you bring in the anti-defection law, how am I answerable to my electorate?

02:00:58.000 --> 02:01:03.000
[Guest]: Because I did not have the freedom to do what I thought was right, or I didn't have the

02:01:03.000 --> 02:01:07.000
[Guest]: freedom to even do what they thought was right.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:10.000
[Guest]: I can only do what the boss says.

02:01:10.000 --> 02:01:12.000
[Guest]: So that it goes.

02:01:12.000 --> 02:01:19.000
[Guest]: I think the anti-defection law also, I'm telling you different angles, completely misjudges

02:01:19.000 --> 02:01:23.000
[Guest]: the concept of a political party.

02:01:23.000 --> 02:01:27.000
[Guest]: Now, I mean, a political party has a few crore people.

02:01:27.000 --> 02:01:32.000
[Guest]: There is no way that everyone has the same opinion on everything.

02:01:32.000 --> 02:01:36.000
[Guest]: And you can't have a crore political parties.

02:01:36.000 --> 02:01:41.000
[Guest]: So the way parties are is, again, I'm not necessarily talking India.

02:01:41.000 --> 02:01:47.000
[Guest]: I'm talking, let's say, more mature democracies where they've evolved over a long period.

02:01:47.000 --> 02:01:48.000
[Guest]: Again, let's take the US.

02:01:48.000 --> 02:01:52.000
[Guest]: You have a broad idea what the Democrat Party stands for.

02:01:52.000 --> 02:01:56.000
[Guest]: You have a broad idea what the Republicans stand for.

02:01:56.000 --> 02:01:58.000
[Guest]: Now, you are a citizen.

02:01:58.000 --> 02:02:00.000
[Guest]: You're not really involved in politics.

02:02:00.000 --> 02:02:04.000
[Guest]: But for whatever reasons, whatever has shaped you and your interest and what you grew up

02:02:04.000 --> 02:02:09.000
[Guest]: with, you have an inclination towards this ideology or that ideology.

02:02:09.000 --> 02:02:12.000
[Guest]: And you go with those guys, whichever you have.

02:02:12.000 --> 02:02:14.000
[Guest]: Maybe instead of two, you may have three, four, five.

02:02:14.000 --> 02:02:16.000
[Guest]: You can't have a hundred.

02:02:16.000 --> 02:02:18.000
[Guest]: But you may be a Democrat.

02:02:18.000 --> 02:02:20.000
[Guest]: There are a hundred things.

02:02:20.000 --> 02:02:25.000
[Guest]: You agree with them on 70, you disagree with them on 30, which is true within the party's

02:02:25.000 --> 02:02:28.000
[Guest]: senators, or they say.

02:02:28.000 --> 02:02:34.000
[Guest]: But what the anti-democrats assumes is that on everything, I agree with everyone else

02:02:34.000 --> 02:02:36.000
[Guest]: in the party, right?

02:02:36.000 --> 02:02:38.000
[Guest]: Because we are all voting.

02:02:38.000 --> 02:02:40.000
[Guest]: I'll just take a favorite example.

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:42.000
[Guest]: I've used this before.

02:02:42.000 --> 02:02:45.000
[Guest]: There is this vote on FDI in retail during the UPA days.

02:02:45.000 --> 02:02:50.000
[Guest]: And I'm deliberately going 10 years back so that we don't get into current politics.

02:02:50.000 --> 02:02:52.000
[Guest]: FDI in retail.

02:02:52.000 --> 02:02:55.000
[Guest]: The UPA proposed, wanted to open it up.

02:02:55.000 --> 02:02:57.000
[Guest]: The BJP opposed it.

02:02:57.000 --> 02:03:00.000
[Guest]: The Congress had, I think, 206 members.

02:03:00.000 --> 02:03:02.000
[Guest]: There's UPA too.

02:03:02.000 --> 02:03:05.000
[Guest]: And BJP had 116 members or something like that.

02:03:05.000 --> 02:03:12.000
[Guest]: I can't believe that all the 206 MPs of the Congress in Lok Sabha thought FDI in retail

02:03:12.000 --> 02:03:15.000
[Guest]: was good and each of the 116 the BJP thought FDI is bad.

02:03:15.000 --> 02:03:17.000
[Guest]: But that's how they voted.

02:03:17.000 --> 02:03:20.000
[Guest]: There was actually a vote, recorded vote on this.

02:03:20.000 --> 02:03:22.000
[Guest]: That's how they voted.

02:03:22.000 --> 02:03:32.000
[Guest]: So, anti-defection law actually makes, enforces MPs to be dishonest about their beliefs.

02:03:32.000 --> 02:03:34.000
[Guest]: And it infantilizes them.

02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:35.000
[Guest]: Infantilizes them.

02:03:35.000 --> 02:03:36.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:03:36.000 --> 02:03:37.000
[Amit Varma]: Since I'm listing out the different ways, let me list you one.

02:03:37.000 --> 02:03:38.000
[Unknown]: Please list out all of them.

02:03:38.000 --> 02:03:39.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:03:39.000 --> 02:03:42.000
[Unknown]: I don't think I'll list all of them because there may be more which I have not thought

02:03:42.000 --> 02:03:43.000
[Guest]: of.

02:03:43.000 --> 02:03:44.000
[Guest]: Let me think of one more.

02:03:44.000 --> 02:03:49.000
[Guest]: Again, I'm going to the basics of what an MP and party stand for.

02:03:49.000 --> 02:03:50.000
[Guest]: Right?

02:03:50.000 --> 02:03:51.000
[Guest]: Conceptual basics.

02:03:51.000 --> 02:03:55.000
[Guest]: What is the primary job of an MP?

02:03:55.000 --> 02:04:02.000
[Guest]: And let's get back to, there's a nice speech by Ambedkar in the Constituent Assembly when

02:04:02.000 --> 02:04:06.000
[Guest]: he introduces the draft constitution.

02:04:06.000 --> 02:04:09.000
[Guest]: I think it is 1948 November or something like that.

02:04:09.000 --> 02:04:10.000
[Guest]: I think.

02:04:10.000 --> 02:04:11.000
[Guest]: I don't know the exact date.

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:13.000
[Guest]: But that's the introduction of the constitution.

02:04:13.000 --> 02:04:18.000
[Guest]: When he's explaining the structure of the constitution as they have introduced.

02:04:18.000 --> 02:04:24.000
[Guest]: And in that, he discusses the presidential versus the parliamentary forms.

02:04:24.000 --> 02:04:26.000
[Guest]: And he says, both are there.

02:04:26.000 --> 02:04:28.000
[Guest]: Both are there around the world.

02:04:28.000 --> 02:04:33.000
[Guest]: The presidential system provides more stability because they were that guy for four years.

02:04:33.000 --> 02:04:37.000
[Guest]: The parliamentary system provides the word uses is greater responsibility.

02:04:37.000 --> 02:04:39.000
[Guest]: We can use the word accountability.

02:04:39.000 --> 02:04:43.000
[Guest]: There's a modern usage of the word accountability, which possibly was.

02:04:43.000 --> 02:04:48.000
[Guest]: And he goes on to explain saying that every day, the government has to be responsible

02:04:48.000 --> 02:04:53.000
[Guest]: to parliament, which is maintained through questions, motions, debates, including the

02:04:53.000 --> 02:04:54.000
[Guest]: no confidence motion.

02:04:54.000 --> 02:04:58.000
[Guest]: The conception is that you are accountable to every MP.

02:04:58.000 --> 02:05:04.000
[Guest]: Now, obviously, the government of the day in India in Lok Sabha is the person who has

02:05:04.000 --> 02:05:07.000
[Guest]: won a majority in Lok Sabha after that.

02:05:07.000 --> 02:05:12.000
[Guest]: So there is a what the anti-deficit law has converted this into is day one.

02:05:12.000 --> 02:05:14.000
[Guest]: There is an election, if there is any.

02:05:14.000 --> 02:05:16.000
[Guest]: And you choose a leader.

02:05:16.000 --> 02:05:22.000
[Guest]: For five years, you can't hold that person accountable at all.

02:05:22.000 --> 02:05:23.000
[Guest]: Right.

02:05:23.000 --> 02:05:30.000
[Guest]: So you have taken away the absolute basis of what a parliamentary democracy is about.

02:05:30.000 --> 02:05:38.000
[Guest]: So I think there are enough reasons for the Supreme Court to have fairly easily struck

02:05:38.000 --> 02:05:48.000
[Guest]: this down on basic structure because it completely changes the nature of parliamentary representative

02:05:48.000 --> 02:05:49.000
[Guest]: democracy.

02:05:49.000 --> 02:05:50.000
[Guest]: It actually changes the nature.

02:05:50.000 --> 02:05:57.000
[Guest]: And if that if a representative democracy is part of the basic structure, which I presume

02:05:57.000 --> 02:06:04.000
[Guest]: it is, and we are not a monarchy, then or we are not an elected five year elected monarchy

02:06:04.000 --> 02:06:06.000
[Guest]: or autocracy, whatever.

02:06:06.000 --> 02:06:10.000
[Guest]: In that case, anti-defection law should have no place.

02:06:10.000 --> 02:06:14.000
[Guest]: And incidentally, this is something that when I was researching about five, six years ago,

02:06:14.000 --> 02:06:18.000
[Guest]: I wrote a book chapter and at that time I was looking and I don't think things should

02:06:18.000 --> 02:06:19.000
[Guest]: have changed much.

02:06:19.000 --> 02:06:24.000
[Guest]: I discovered that there are only five other countries, great democracies, which share

02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:29.000
[Guest]: this feature, where if an MP votes against the party whip, the MP loses his or her seat.

02:06:29.000 --> 02:06:32.000
[Guest]: And the other five, I remember the names.

02:06:32.000 --> 02:06:36.000
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan, Sierra Leone, Bangladesh, Guyana, and I forget the fifth.

02:06:36.000 --> 02:06:39.000
[Guest]: Oh, you read it by something that I wrote?

02:06:39.000 --> 02:06:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, I got it from you.

02:06:41.000 --> 02:06:42.000
[Amit Varma]: Zimbabwe.

02:06:42.000 --> 02:06:43.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:06:43.000 --> 02:06:44.000
[Guest]: This was the Robert Mugabe Zimbabwe.

02:06:44.000 --> 02:06:45.000
[Unknown]: Yeah, yeah.

02:06:45.000 --> 02:06:50.000
[Guest]: Not that I don't know what it is now, but we share, I mean, these are the five countries

02:06:50.000 --> 02:06:53.000
[Guest]: we share this great concept with.

02:06:53.000 --> 02:06:58.000
[Guest]: So, that's, so there is no, we should not have that at all.

02:06:58.000 --> 02:07:06.000
[Guest]: Now to your second part of the question, which was that if this is there, then what's the

02:07:06.000 --> 02:07:08.000
[Guest]: whole point of having a parliament?

02:07:08.000 --> 02:07:10.000
[Guest]: What are, what is PRS doing?

02:07:10.000 --> 02:07:12.000
[Guest]: Why are we bothering to talk to MPs?

02:07:12.000 --> 02:07:17.000
[Guest]: Why are we not just talking to, let us say, the leader of the BJP and the leader of the

02:07:17.000 --> 02:07:21.000
[Guest]: Congress and the leader of the Trinamool and the leader of the DMK or whatever, right?

02:07:21.000 --> 02:07:24.000
[Unknown]: I mean, the rest are irrelevant because of a peace issue.

02:07:24.000 --> 02:07:28.000
[Guest]: Well, parties are not monoliths, despite all this.

02:07:28.000 --> 02:07:30.000
[Guest]: And I can give you examples again.

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:36.000
[Guest]: There is an interesting bill called the Seeds Bill, which was brought in in 2004, introduced

02:07:36.000 --> 02:07:37.000
[Guest]: in Rajya Sabha.

02:07:37.000 --> 02:07:38.000
[Guest]: It was there for a very long time.

02:07:38.000 --> 02:07:39.000
[Guest]: The UPI brought it in.

02:07:39.000 --> 02:07:41.000
[Guest]: They could not pass it.

02:07:41.000 --> 02:07:46.000
[Guest]: They could not pass it because there was a lot of resistance by Congress MPs against

02:07:46.000 --> 02:07:47.000
[Guest]: it.

02:07:47.000 --> 02:07:53.000
[Guest]: So, party leader also has to manage internal party dynamics.

02:07:53.000 --> 02:07:58.000
[Guest]: Then there are things like standing committees, which change things.

02:07:58.000 --> 02:08:02.000
[Guest]: Then speeches in parliament do have a long term impact.

02:08:02.000 --> 02:08:08.000
[Guest]: So, what happens if the government has brought in a bill for a final vote in parliament?

02:08:08.000 --> 02:08:11.000
[Guest]: It will almost certainly pass.

02:08:11.000 --> 02:08:17.000
[Guest]: That's because they bring it only if they have already done the groundwork through back

02:08:17.000 --> 02:08:20.000
[Guest]: channels to ensure there is enough support.

02:08:20.000 --> 02:08:27.000
[Guest]: But that groundwork is in that a lot of work goes in.

02:08:27.000 --> 02:08:34.000
[Guest]: So, I can give you many examples where bills have been amended, suggestions made by standing

02:08:34.000 --> 02:08:39.000
[Guest]: committees, and the government has found them reasonable and taken them on board.

02:08:39.000 --> 02:08:41.000
[Guest]: So, there is a lot.

02:08:41.000 --> 02:08:45.000
[Guest]: And even in many other issues, what MPs say do have a large impact.

02:08:45.000 --> 02:08:51.000
[Guest]: So, these are the sort of direct things where other than improving the quality of discourse,

02:08:51.000 --> 02:08:58.000
[Guest]: which is a much more fuzzy thing, there is even a lot of direct impact, including budgets.

02:08:58.000 --> 02:08:59.000
[Guest]: How do you look at budgets?

02:08:59.000 --> 02:09:00.000
[Guest]: Where should you allocate?

02:09:00.000 --> 02:09:01.000
[Guest]: What is the money?

02:09:01.000 --> 02:09:03.000
[Guest]: People are interested in that.

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:06.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm very curious, what role does say something like question hour play in this?

02:09:06.000 --> 02:09:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the sort of benefits of the whole program that you run and helping parliamentarians

02:09:12.000 --> 02:09:18.000
[Amit Varma]: manage this game too, is that even if they cannot actually vote the way they want to

02:09:18.000 --> 02:09:24.000
[Amit Varma]: necessarily, they can still have an impact in terms of asking questions to ministers,

02:09:24.000 --> 02:09:28.000
[Amit Varma]: some which the ministers have time to prepare for, some which they don't when there are

02:09:28.000 --> 02:09:32.000
[Amit Varma]: supplementary questions, burning questions on the issues of the day.

02:09:32.000 --> 02:09:34.000
[Amit Varma]: How much of an impact does this have?

02:09:34.000 --> 02:09:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Because while this is incredibly useful, what I have realized is that most of the country

02:09:39.000 --> 02:09:42.000
[Amit Varma]: doesn't actually tune in to watch this or follow this at all.

02:09:42.000 --> 02:09:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's not reported.

02:09:44.000 --> 02:09:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And none of that really happens.

02:09:45.000 --> 02:09:49.000
[Amit Varma]: So, if it's like happening effectively in a sealed chamber, I mean, obviously it's not,

02:09:49.000 --> 02:09:50.000
[Amit Varma]: anyone can follow it.

02:09:50.000 --> 02:09:55.000
[Amit Varma]: But if it's effectively in a sealed chamber, then is it just a kind of a charade or does

02:09:55.000 --> 02:09:56.000
[Amit Varma]: it have a real impact?

02:09:56.000 --> 02:10:01.000
[Amit Varma]: And can you give examples of real impact that you have seen coming out from your research?

02:10:01.000 --> 02:10:02.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:10:02.000 --> 02:10:03.000
[Guest]: There are two different things.

02:10:03.000 --> 02:10:11.000
[Guest]: One is, we as a policy do not draft questions for MPs because that takes a position and

02:10:11.000 --> 02:10:12.000
[Guest]: we don't take a position.

02:10:12.000 --> 02:10:18.000
[Guest]: But if an MP asks us, let's say, I want to raise this issue, can you give me background

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:19.000
[Guest]: research?

02:10:19.000 --> 02:10:20.000
[Guest]: We'll do that.

02:10:20.000 --> 02:10:24.000
[Guest]: And what we do with MPs is very clear in the sense it's only research.

02:10:24.000 --> 02:10:31.000
[Guest]: So, if today, even on a bill, if a BJP MP asks or a Congress MP asks or a Trinamool

02:10:31.000 --> 02:10:34.000
[Guest]: MP asks or a Shiv Sena MP asks, they get the same material.

02:10:34.000 --> 02:10:38.000
[Guest]: I'm not customizing for the MPs politics or ideology.

02:10:38.000 --> 02:10:42.000
[Guest]: So, if one MP asks you, you will give that not only to them, but to everybody?

02:10:42.000 --> 02:10:43.000
[Guest]: No, no.

02:10:43.000 --> 02:10:45.000
[Guest]: So, there are some standard products which everybody gets.

02:10:45.000 --> 02:10:48.000
[Guest]: But if one MP asks, that person gets it.

02:10:48.000 --> 02:10:52.000
[Guest]: But let's say four days later or one week later, another MP asks.

02:10:52.000 --> 02:10:55.000
[Guest]: Same thing may be updated for some extra information.

02:10:55.000 --> 02:10:58.000
[Unknown]: I mean, next year, somebody asks.

02:10:58.000 --> 02:11:03.000
[Guest]: You obviously take out the old research note, look at it, see how correct it is.

02:11:03.000 --> 02:11:05.000
[Guest]: If something has happened, update it and give that.

02:11:05.000 --> 02:11:06.000
[Guest]: So, I'm not customizing.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:07.000
[Guest]: I'm not bothered.

02:11:07.000 --> 02:11:12.000
[Guest]: In fact, I'm not bothered what that MP's politics is or ideologies.

02:11:12.000 --> 02:11:15.000
[Guest]: It's the same note everybody gets.

02:11:15.000 --> 02:11:16.000
[Guest]: Questions themselves.

02:11:16.000 --> 02:11:19.000
[Guest]: And this is a very good question that you asked.

02:11:19.000 --> 02:11:21.000
[Guest]: But why does this even matter?

02:11:21.000 --> 02:11:22.000
[Guest]: Forget this.

02:11:22.000 --> 02:11:25.000
[Guest]: Why does a speech in Lok Sabha matter?

02:11:25.000 --> 02:11:31.000
[Guest]: At the end of the speech, if they're on a bill, let's say there is four hours of people speaking.

02:11:31.000 --> 02:11:37.000
[Guest]: End of it, everybody knows that the government has a majority.

02:11:37.000 --> 02:11:38.000
[Guest]: Government has judiciary whip.

02:11:38.000 --> 02:11:41.000
[Unknown]: They're going to win the bill.

02:11:41.000 --> 02:11:47.000
[Guest]: So, is the rest of it just like a four-hour thing where you're just watching Sholay or

02:11:47.000 --> 02:11:51.000
[Guest]: listening to a podcast or, I mean, entertainment or information?

02:11:51.000 --> 02:11:54.000
[Unknown]: I would love parliamentarians to listen to my podcast while they're there.

02:11:54.000 --> 02:12:02.000
[Guest]: So, is it just to the core thing about what the outcome is, which is a bill becoming an act?

02:12:02.000 --> 02:12:03.000
[Guest]: It is completely irrelevant.

02:12:03.000 --> 02:12:08.000
[Guest]: So, why do they even, okay, why do people even bother to prepare for it?

02:12:08.000 --> 02:12:11.000
[Guest]: Why do they waste their time preparing for it?

02:12:11.000 --> 02:12:14.000
[Guest]: And there can be multiple pressures.

02:12:14.000 --> 02:12:18.000
[Guest]: But one of the things I think is always there and it works.

02:12:18.000 --> 02:12:19.000
[Guest]: Yes.

02:12:19.000 --> 02:12:22.000
[Guest]: Peer pressure, peer appreciation, peer criticism.

02:12:22.000 --> 02:12:32.000
[Guest]: Every MP, like all of us, want to look, I mean, to do things, partly to be seen as doing

02:12:32.000 --> 02:12:35.000
[Guest]: things also, also to do things sincerely.

02:12:35.000 --> 02:12:41.000
[Guest]: I mean, why are there so many people who are doing things when nobody's watching, doing

02:12:41.000 --> 02:12:42.000
[Amit Varma]: it diligently?

02:12:42.000 --> 02:12:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Like they say, character is what you do when no one's watching.

02:12:45.000 --> 02:12:46.000
[Guest]: So, many of them do that.

02:12:46.000 --> 02:12:48.000
[Guest]: They also get rewarded.

02:12:48.000 --> 02:12:55.000
[Guest]: So, if you are seen as very diligent, you might become an MOS or something because the

02:12:55.000 --> 02:12:57.000
[Guest]: party boss is watching you.

02:12:57.000 --> 02:13:03.000
[Guest]: So, you might actually get tangible rewards in terms of you'll get a ticket again, you

02:13:03.000 --> 02:13:04.000
[Guest]: will get appreciation from others.

02:13:04.000 --> 02:13:11.000
[Guest]: In fact, I remember this was on one of the bills during UPA time again.

02:13:11.000 --> 02:13:17.000
[Guest]: It was a BJP MP and he had worked very hard on that bill because he was the lead speaker.

02:13:17.000 --> 02:13:24.000
[Guest]: In fact, he wanted to meet us and we had a two hour long meeting going through the entire

02:13:24.000 --> 02:13:25.000
[Guest]: bill.

02:13:25.000 --> 02:13:29.000
[Guest]: And that person's eyes were red because he had not slept the whole, I mean, not because

02:13:29.000 --> 02:13:34.000
[Guest]: the person was drinking, but because the person had not slept the whole night, was preparing

02:13:34.000 --> 02:13:35.000
[Guest]: very hard.

02:13:35.000 --> 02:13:38.000
[Guest]: Next day, he gave a very good speech.

02:13:38.000 --> 02:13:45.000
[Guest]: And then he called us, after the speech, he actually called and said, thanks for helping

02:13:45.000 --> 02:13:48.000
[Guest]: me understand the issues.

02:13:48.000 --> 02:13:54.000
[Guest]: Pranabda said, well spoke, said, and Pranabda was the leader of the house from the Congress.

02:13:54.000 --> 02:14:00.000
[Guest]: And this guy is a BJP MP, but a pat on the back from Pranab Mukherjee, who was a respected

02:14:00.000 --> 02:14:04.000
[Guest]: parliamentarian, means a lot to that person.

02:14:04.000 --> 02:14:09.000
[Guest]: I'm sure in the Indian cricket team, if there is a newbie, at the end of the day, if Kohli

02:14:09.000 --> 02:14:14.000
[Guest]: taps and says, well done boy, I mean, that guy will be out, regardless of what he scored,

02:14:14.000 --> 02:14:15.000
[Guest]: would be up there.

02:14:15.000 --> 02:14:20.000
[Guest]: I mean, you like that, I mean, the person you look up to telling you that you've done

02:14:20.000 --> 02:14:21.000
[Guest]: a good job.

02:14:21.000 --> 02:14:22.000
[Guest]: So, it's like that.

02:14:22.000 --> 02:14:23.000
[Guest]: So, that also drives.

02:14:23.000 --> 02:14:24.000
[Guest]: So, multiple things do.

02:14:24.000 --> 02:14:25.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:14:25.000 --> 02:14:28.000
[Guest]: The questionnaire itself does have a lot of impact.

02:14:28.000 --> 02:14:33.000
[Guest]: Again, the minister doesn't want to be caught, embarrassed, doesn't want to be caught on

02:14:33.000 --> 02:14:34.000
[Guest]: court.

02:14:34.000 --> 02:14:35.000
[Guest]: So, they have to prepare.

02:14:35.000 --> 02:14:41.000
[Guest]: They work very hard to anticipate and the ministry works very hard to anticipate the

02:14:41.000 --> 02:14:48.000
[Guest]: supplementary questions so that they have a good answer, because you don't want public

02:14:48.000 --> 02:14:49.000
[Guest]: embarrassment.

02:14:49.000 --> 02:14:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Just to make it clear to the listener, the difference between the main question and the

02:14:53.000 --> 02:14:57.000
[Amit Varma]: supplementary question is they have 10 days to prepare for the main question as given

02:14:57.000 --> 02:14:58.000
[Amit Varma]: in advance.

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:02.000
[Amit Varma]: But when supplementary questions are asked based on the answer, they have to think on

02:15:02.000 --> 02:15:03.000
[Guest]: their feet.

02:15:03.000 --> 02:15:04.000
[Guest]: It's a surprise quiz.

02:15:04.000 --> 02:15:09.000
[Guest]: Just, just think of it as a home assignment versus a surprise quiz in your class.

02:15:09.000 --> 02:15:10.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:15:10.000 --> 02:15:11.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:15:11.000 --> 02:15:13.920
[Amit Varma]: So, it's a home assignment immediately followed by a surprise quiz.

02:15:13.920 --> 02:15:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And does it matter?

02:15:14.920 --> 02:15:16.600
[Guest]: Does it make a tangible difference?

02:15:16.600 --> 02:15:17.600
[Guest]: It does.

02:15:17.600 --> 02:15:20.800
[Guest]: It does shape government policy very often.

02:15:20.800 --> 02:15:25.000
[Guest]: Even sometimes like, let's say, let me take a simple example.

02:15:25.000 --> 02:15:28.000
[Guest]: There's something that the constituency needs.

02:15:28.000 --> 02:15:35.000
[Guest]: Okay, it could even be something like a railway line has a level crossing and you need a flyover

02:15:35.000 --> 02:15:40.000
[Guest]: there, which makes a big difference to the people of my constituency.

02:15:40.000 --> 02:15:45.680
[Guest]: And I asked the Minister of Railways, because that person controls this in that time, that

02:15:45.680 --> 02:15:51.880
[Guest]: is there a plan to build this, etc, etc, etc, that might trigger off.

02:15:51.880 --> 02:15:55.000
[Guest]: So the person can't say, no, you'll never get it.

02:15:55.000 --> 02:15:57.000
[Guest]: Person will say, yes, we are looking into it.

02:15:57.000 --> 02:15:58.000
[Guest]: We'll do it.

02:15:58.000 --> 02:16:02.000
[Guest]: And that might trigger off some files moving, which creates that.

02:16:02.000 --> 02:16:04.000
[Guest]: I'm just taking a very simple constituency type.

02:16:04.000 --> 02:16:08.000
[Guest]: Of course, policy type questions also come very often.

02:16:08.000 --> 02:16:14.000
[Guest]: And those are way more complex, some very often, but they can even trigger policy.

02:16:14.000 --> 02:16:19.000
[Guest]: People ask me, and I'll, before you ask me, I'll ask the question myself and answer it

02:16:19.000 --> 02:16:24.000
[Guest]: because that's, I mean, I like to set the question paper for myself.

02:16:24.000 --> 02:16:25.000
[Amit Varma]: Excellent.

02:16:25.000 --> 02:16:26.000
[Guest]: Go ahead.

02:16:26.000 --> 02:16:28.000
[Guest]: So there is this concept of private member bill.

02:16:28.000 --> 02:16:32.000
[Guest]: Let me explain that because I'm sure many of our listeners don't know this intricacies.

02:16:32.000 --> 02:16:36.000
[Guest]: I had no clue before 2005 when I started PRS.

02:16:36.000 --> 02:16:42.000
[Guest]: So what most of the acts that you see in force, they originate as a bill.

02:16:42.000 --> 02:16:45.000
[Guest]: They're introduced by a minister.

02:16:45.000 --> 02:16:48.000
[Guest]: And then it goes to the parliamentary process.

02:16:48.000 --> 02:16:52.000
[Guest]: And if it's passed by both houses, presidents assent, it becomes an act.

02:16:52.000 --> 02:16:57.000
[Guest]: Now, any member of parliament can propose a bill.

02:16:57.000 --> 02:17:02.000
[Guest]: And if it's proposed by the government, a minister introduces on behalf of the government

02:17:02.000 --> 02:17:07.000
[Guest]: because it's a collective responsibility of the cabinet.

02:17:07.000 --> 02:17:15.000
[Guest]: But if I'm a non-minister, MP, which means I'm called a private member, and I introduce a bill,

02:17:15.000 --> 02:17:22.000
[Guest]: that also, in theory, has the same importance as any other bill.

02:17:22.000 --> 02:17:30.000
[Guest]: In practice, the last private member bill that became law was 1970.

02:17:30.000 --> 02:17:31.000
[Guest]: There were 14 of them.

02:17:31.000 --> 02:17:35.000
[Guest]: It was the government as well, which is very different from, let's say, the UK,

02:17:35.000 --> 02:17:40.000
[Guest]: because they also, we follow the Westminster model.

02:17:40.000 --> 02:17:44.000
[Guest]: UK, every year, about five or six private member bills become law.

02:17:44.000 --> 02:17:46.000
[Guest]: They take them way more seriously.

02:17:46.000 --> 02:17:49.000
[Guest]: Here, we don't that much, but still, they have an impact.

02:17:49.000 --> 02:17:51.000
[Guest]: I'll give you an example.

02:17:51.000 --> 02:17:57.000
[Guest]: 2015, if I remember correctly, maybe off by a year or so,

02:17:57.000 --> 02:18:06.000
[Guest]: there was a private member bill on rights for transgender persons introduced by Tiruchi Shiva of the DMK.

02:18:06.000 --> 02:18:10.000
[Guest]: That bill, he was a Rajya Sabha member, came to Rajya Sabha.

02:18:10.000 --> 02:18:15.000
[Guest]: Typically, what happens is, these are on alternate Fridays afternoon.

02:18:15.000 --> 02:18:19.000
[Guest]: After the discussion, typically, the minister says that,

02:18:19.000 --> 02:18:22.000
[Guest]: we will take action on this, please withdraw your bill.

02:18:22.000 --> 02:18:28.000
[Guest]: And default position, usually, is the MP was introduced, withdraws the bill,

02:18:28.000 --> 02:18:30.000
[Guest]: and says the government will go forward.

02:18:30.000 --> 02:18:33.000
[Guest]: Tiruchi Shiva said, no, I want a vote.

02:18:33.000 --> 02:18:34.000
[Guest]: Wow.

02:18:34.000 --> 02:18:35.000
[Guest]: He has a right to a vote.

02:18:35.000 --> 02:18:36.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:18:36.000 --> 02:18:38.000
[Guest]: I said, no, no, I want a vote.

02:18:38.000 --> 02:18:44.000
[Guest]: Now, how can any government issue, any party issue a whip,

02:18:44.000 --> 02:18:49.000
[Guest]: which says we don't want to protect the rights of transgender persons politically,

02:18:49.000 --> 02:18:51.000
[Guest]: how can you even do that?

02:18:51.000 --> 02:18:53.000
[Guest]: Regardless of what's there in the bill.

02:18:53.000 --> 02:18:57.000
[Guest]: And the time for moving amendments was over.

02:18:57.000 --> 02:18:59.000
[Unknown]: Because you have to give that earlier.

02:18:59.000 --> 02:19:03.000
[Unknown]: Because nobody expected the eventuality of him insisting on it.

02:19:03.000 --> 02:19:04.000
[Unknown]: Wow.

02:19:04.000 --> 02:19:06.000
[Guest]: So, nobody bothered to do the homework.

02:19:06.000 --> 02:19:11.000
[Guest]: If this were to become law, there are these four provisions, which are problematic.

02:19:11.000 --> 02:19:13.000
[Guest]: Let us make them correct and pass law.

02:19:13.000 --> 02:19:16.000
[Guest]: Because, obviously, there are issues.

02:19:16.000 --> 02:19:18.000
[Guest]: So, now it comes to the vote.

02:19:18.000 --> 02:19:20.000
[Guest]: They scrambled.

02:19:20.000 --> 02:19:22.000
[Guest]: And nobody could vote against.

02:19:22.000 --> 02:19:25.000
[Guest]: So, it passed Rajya Sabha.

02:19:25.000 --> 02:19:27.000
[Guest]: Now, it comes to Lok Sabha.

02:19:27.000 --> 02:19:32.000
[Guest]: Now, the rule is that, which, okay, there are lots of private member bills.

02:19:32.000 --> 02:19:34.000
[Guest]: Which one will be discussed in the house?

02:19:34.000 --> 02:19:36.000
[Guest]: That's usually lottery.

02:19:36.000 --> 02:19:41.000
[Guest]: But, if one house has passed a bill, that jumps the queue in the other house.

02:19:41.000 --> 02:19:45.000
[Guest]: Because it has already been deemed to be important by one of the houses.

02:19:45.000 --> 02:19:50.000
[Guest]: And since a member of parliament cannot enter the chamber of the other house,

02:19:50.000 --> 02:19:52.000
[Guest]: unless the person is a minister.

02:19:52.000 --> 02:19:57.000
[Guest]: So, you find a couple of others to sponsor your bill in that house.

02:19:57.000 --> 02:20:01.000
[Guest]: So, two or three MPs there decided to sponsor this bill.

02:20:01.000 --> 02:20:04.000
[Guest]: This is Trichy Sabha's bill, but they are sponsoring it in Lok Sabha.

02:20:04.000 --> 02:20:06.000
[Guest]: And it was listed.

02:20:06.000 --> 02:20:08.000
[Guest]: The government is in a bind now.

02:20:08.000 --> 02:20:10.000
[Guest]: The government said, we will do something.

02:20:10.000 --> 02:20:15.000
[Guest]: They actually postponed a bit by the earlier bill, which was being discussed in Lok Sabha.

02:20:15.000 --> 02:20:18.000
[Guest]: They continued discussing for a few more weeks.

02:20:18.000 --> 02:20:19.000
[Guest]: So, they postponed it.

02:20:19.000 --> 02:20:21.000
[Guest]: But this had to come.

02:20:21.000 --> 02:20:27.000
[Guest]: The day this was listed, that morning, the government introduced its own bill.

02:20:27.000 --> 02:20:29.000
[Guest]: Right of Transgender Persons Bill.

02:20:29.000 --> 02:20:31.000
[Guest]: And then they said that we have our own bill.

02:20:31.000 --> 02:20:36.000
[Guest]: Let's take both these together and let a committee look into it.

02:20:36.000 --> 02:20:38.000
[Guest]: And finally, what happened?

02:20:38.000 --> 02:20:41.000
[Guest]: The government bill got passed.

02:20:41.000 --> 02:20:49.000
[Guest]: Nevertheless, there is now an act that has the protection for transgender rights, etc.

02:20:49.000 --> 02:20:51.000
[Guest]: There is an act.

02:20:51.000 --> 02:20:59.000
[Guest]: I would give Mr. Shiva the credit for pushing, getting this done because he actually pulled the trigger.

02:20:59.000 --> 02:21:00.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:21:00.000 --> 02:21:03.000
[Guest]: So, when people say, how does it matter?

02:21:03.000 --> 02:21:04.000
[Guest]: It does. It signals.

02:21:04.000 --> 02:21:05.000
[Guest]: It pushes.

02:21:05.000 --> 02:21:07.000
[Guest]: It signals intention.

02:21:07.000 --> 02:21:10.000
[Guest]: And even questions, they signal intentions.

02:21:10.000 --> 02:21:13.000
[Amit Varma]: So, since you like cricket, this reminds me ofâ¦

02:21:13.000 --> 02:21:14.000
[Guest]: Only Test Cricket.

02:21:14.000 --> 02:21:15.000
[Guest]: Only Test Cricket.

02:21:15.000 --> 02:21:17.000
[Guest]: T20, I don't watch.

02:21:17.000 --> 02:21:21.000
[Amit Varma]: I think I managed to convince Ram Guha on my episode with him that they are two different sports.

02:21:21.000 --> 02:21:23.000
[Guest]: So, one should not judge them against each other.

02:21:23.000 --> 02:21:24.000
[Guest]: Fair enough.

02:21:24.000 --> 02:21:29.000
[Amit Varma]: So, in 1996, Lalit Modi had the idea for a league system, though involving one-day matches,

02:21:29.000 --> 02:21:35.000
[Amit Varma]: because in those days T20 was not a popular format, for something that looked very IPL-like.

02:21:35.000 --> 02:21:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And I remember Mr. Bindra in 2003 gave me an interview when I was in Cricket Info where he spoke about this at length.

02:21:42.000 --> 02:21:44.000
[Amit Varma]: But it was on the back burner.

02:21:44.000 --> 02:21:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And then the ICL, Zee came up with the ICL.

02:21:47.000 --> 02:21:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And that spurred the BCCI into acting on Modi's idea.

02:21:51.000 --> 02:21:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And then the IPL happened and the ICL went.

02:21:53.000 --> 02:21:58.000
[Amit Varma]: So, when you spoke of, you know, this bill happening kinda like that, independent member comes in.

02:21:58.000 --> 02:22:01.000
[Amit Varma]: You used the phrase, there are lots of private bills.

02:22:01.000 --> 02:22:05.000
[Amit Varma]: Why are there lots of private bills when the last one that got through was 1970?

02:22:05.000 --> 02:22:09.000
[Guest]: Because like Trichy Shiva's thing, people want to signal intentions.

02:22:09.000 --> 02:22:10.000
[Unknown]: Wow.

02:22:10.000 --> 02:22:11.000
[Guest]: They put in a lot of work.

02:22:11.000 --> 02:22:13.000
[Guest]: Because writing a bill takes effort.

02:22:13.000 --> 02:22:14.000
[Guest]: Do you work with that also?

02:22:14.000 --> 02:22:15.000
[Guest]: We don't.

02:22:15.000 --> 02:22:16.000
[Guest]: In terms of the background?

02:22:16.000 --> 02:22:17.000
[Guest]: We don't.

02:22:17.000 --> 02:22:18.000
[Guest]: We don't.

02:22:18.000 --> 02:22:19.000
[Guest]: We don't.

02:22:19.000 --> 02:22:20.000
[Guest]: Okay, I'll tell you where we do and where we don't.

02:22:20.000 --> 02:22:23.000
[Guest]: We run a different program where we just run the program.

02:22:23.000 --> 02:22:26.000
[Guest]: We don't get into the details called the Lamb Fellowship.

02:22:26.000 --> 02:22:27.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't know whether you've heard of that.

02:22:27.000 --> 02:22:28.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, of course.

02:22:28.000 --> 02:22:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Of course.

02:22:29.000 --> 02:22:31.000
[Guest]: I had one of your alumni, Shivam Shankar Singh on my show recently.

02:22:31.000 --> 02:22:32.000
[Guest]: Oh, yeah, yeah.

02:22:32.000 --> 02:22:33.000
[Guest]: Shivam was there.

02:22:33.000 --> 02:22:34.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:22:34.000 --> 02:22:37.000
[Guest]: So, the Lamb Fellows, they work with the MP and they take positions.

02:22:37.000 --> 02:22:38.000
[Guest]: They draft questions.

02:22:38.000 --> 02:22:39.000
[Guest]: They do that.

02:22:39.000 --> 02:22:43.000
[Guest]: But there's a very clear wall that I don't know what bill they are working on or what

02:22:43.000 --> 02:22:44.000
[Guest]: questions they are.

02:22:44.000 --> 02:22:48.000
[Guest]: So, the reporting to us, we do, obviously, we need to monitor the program we run.

02:22:48.000 --> 02:22:51.000
[Guest]: It is like, how many questions did you do in the lesson?

02:22:51.000 --> 02:22:53.000
[Guest]: Not what questions.

02:22:53.000 --> 02:22:57.000
[Guest]: And of course, when something happens and it's introduced, the guy comes and says, array,

02:22:57.000 --> 02:22:58.000
[Guest]: I did this, shows.

02:22:58.000 --> 02:22:59.000
[Guest]: And we say, okay, good, shows.

02:22:59.000 --> 02:23:00.000
[Guest]: That sort of a thing.

02:23:00.000 --> 02:23:06.000
[Guest]: But we are not involved in any way in drafting these because that means we are taking a position.

02:23:06.000 --> 02:23:08.000
[Guest]: Drafting, you're taking a position.

02:23:08.000 --> 02:23:09.000
[Amit Varma]: We can't.

02:23:09.000 --> 02:23:13.000
[Amit Varma]: My next question, and this is something you referred to in the break, and you referred

02:23:13.000 --> 02:23:17.000
[Amit Varma]: to during the conversation as well, when you said that we make sure it's six pages, the

02:23:17.000 --> 02:23:21.000
[Amit Varma]: first page is a cover page, two pages of what the bill actually is, two and a half, three

02:23:21.000 --> 02:23:23.000
[Amit Varma]: pages of whatever, including the footnotes.

02:23:23.000 --> 02:23:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And I found it really impressive because one of the problems people have is that even if

02:23:28.000 --> 02:23:33.000
[Amit Varma]: you have the sincere intent that you want to absorb knowledge, either you put it off

02:23:33.000 --> 02:23:39.000
[Amit Varma]: or you skim, which is exactly why you said that you didn't want more pages or less pages.

02:23:39.000 --> 02:23:44.000
[Amit Varma]: And you want them to take it seriously, but also actually read the full thing.

02:23:44.000 --> 02:23:46.000
[Amit Varma]: In the break, we were talking about writing values.

02:23:46.000 --> 02:23:51.000
[Amit Varma]: And I kind of realized that independently and most probably before me, you have started

02:23:51.000 --> 02:23:55.000
[Amit Varma]: teaching a lot of the values that I talk about in my writing course, like what I call the

02:23:55.000 --> 02:23:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Naniji test in my writing course is the mum test for you.

02:23:59.000 --> 02:24:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And language is really important because one of the problems with people writing policy

02:24:04.000 --> 02:24:11.000
[Amit Varma]: is this dull, academic, jargony language full of abstract terms that just make the eyes

02:24:11.000 --> 02:24:13.000
[Amit Varma]: glaze over and you can't possibly read it.

02:24:13.000 --> 02:24:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And your writing needs to be functional because you're talking to people who are really busy.

02:24:17.000 --> 02:24:22.000
[Amit Varma]: And even if they want it, you've got to make sure it's as clear as possible.

02:24:22.000 --> 02:24:27.000
[Amit Varma]: So how did you, like when you started PRS, when you started writing these briefs, did

02:24:27.000 --> 02:24:31.000
[Amit Varma]: you already come with a set of values that you evolved over time?

02:24:31.000 --> 02:24:36.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, what was that process like where you arrive at your sort of handbook for writing

02:24:36.000 --> 02:24:37.000
[Amit Varma]: these?

02:24:37.000 --> 02:24:39.000
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a little bit more about that as well.

02:24:39.000 --> 02:24:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Because I think many, many people have a problem with being able to communicate complex subjects

02:24:45.000 --> 02:24:46.000
[Amit Varma]: in simple language.

02:24:46.000 --> 02:24:52.000
[Guest]: My background helped in the sense I was working for Bank of America before that for ISEC.

02:24:52.000 --> 02:24:55.000
[Guest]: And actually learned the writing in ICICI securities.

02:24:55.000 --> 02:24:57.000
[Guest]: OK, this is the first job.

02:24:57.000 --> 02:24:59.000
[Guest]: First job is where you got taught.

02:24:59.000 --> 02:25:02.000
[Guest]: So I am writing, let's say, a report.

02:25:02.000 --> 02:25:06.000
[Guest]: I was for some time a banking sector analyst.

02:25:06.000 --> 02:25:09.000
[Guest]: So I'm writing a report on State Bank of India stock.

02:25:09.000 --> 02:25:11.000
[Guest]: That's my job.

02:25:11.000 --> 02:25:13.000
[Guest]: I'm sitting in ISEC and writing.

02:25:13.000 --> 02:25:15.000
[Guest]: There's a guy sitting in Deutsche Bank and writing.

02:25:15.000 --> 02:25:20.000
[Guest]: There's a guy sitting in some other brokerage, Anand Rati and writing.

02:25:20.000 --> 02:25:23.000
[Guest]: There's someone else writing in CSSA and writing.

02:25:23.000 --> 02:25:25.000
[Guest]: Some 30 of us are writing.

02:25:25.000 --> 02:25:27.000
[Guest]: Who's our target audience?

02:25:27.000 --> 02:25:30.000
[Guest]: The fund manager or the, right?

02:25:30.000 --> 02:25:32.000
[Guest]: And that person has 30 reports.

02:25:32.000 --> 02:25:35.000
[Guest]: Why would that person read my report?

02:25:35.000 --> 02:25:41.000
[Guest]: And if that person doesn't read my report, OK, and many people don't read my reports,

02:25:41.000 --> 02:25:42.000
[Guest]: I lose my job.

02:25:42.000 --> 02:25:45.000
[Guest]: Why should my boss pay me a salary if nobody's reading my report?

02:25:45.000 --> 02:25:47.000
[Guest]: That feedback comes back.

02:25:47.000 --> 02:25:49.000
[Guest]: So it's a matter of survival, right?

02:25:49.000 --> 02:25:58.000
[Guest]: So we are taught to write in a way that a busy person will still read what you write.

02:25:58.000 --> 02:26:00.000
[Guest]: So I had that background.

02:26:00.000 --> 02:26:01.000
[Guest]: That's why I write short.

02:26:01.000 --> 02:26:07.000
[Guest]: So in fact, one of the lessons that there's a person called Andrew McCormack.

02:26:07.000 --> 02:26:08.000
[Guest]: He was a JP Morgan guy.

02:26:08.000 --> 02:26:09.000
[Guest]: He was my first.

02:26:09.000 --> 02:26:14.000
[Guest]: He was the head of sales training and research when I joined ICSS securities,

02:26:14.000 --> 02:26:16.000
[Guest]: an Englishman, because JP Morgan.

02:26:16.000 --> 02:26:20.000
[Guest]: So he used to say, and that is something that I internalized,

02:26:20.000 --> 02:26:24.000
[Guest]: is that there are two ways of making an argument.

02:26:24.000 --> 02:26:28.000
[Guest]: A, B, C, D, therefore E.

02:26:28.000 --> 02:26:31.000
[Guest]: E because A, B, C, D.

02:26:31.000 --> 02:26:33.000
[Guest]: He says write E because A, B, C, D.

02:26:33.000 --> 02:26:34.000
[Guest]: Get their attention.

02:26:34.000 --> 02:26:40.000
[Guest]: Because otherwise, by the time you reach your conclusion, people have stopped reading you.

02:26:40.000 --> 02:26:45.000
[Guest]: And he used to say, you have to write boom, boom, boom, boom, five bullets.

02:26:45.000 --> 02:26:46.000
[Guest]: So it's short.

02:26:46.000 --> 02:26:47.000
[Guest]: People notice all five.

02:26:47.000 --> 02:26:49.000
[Guest]: If you write large ones, nobody reads.

02:26:49.000 --> 02:26:55.000
[Guest]: So I said, OK, busy audience, hedge fund manager, busy audience, member of parliament.

02:26:55.000 --> 02:26:57.000
[Guest]: Same thing, different subject.

02:26:57.000 --> 02:27:00.000
[Guest]: But same, in a way, there's some commonality.

02:27:00.000 --> 02:27:02.000
[Guest]: So one should write for this.

02:27:02.000 --> 02:27:04.000
[Guest]: That was the idea when we started.

02:27:04.000 --> 02:27:08.000
[Guest]: So how do you actually have a larger team when people also internalize that?

02:27:08.000 --> 02:27:13.000
[Guest]: Some of that is that as we got a team, I was editing other people's.

02:27:13.000 --> 02:27:17.000
[Guest]: I found that the Indian education system is particularly bad and not just Indian.

02:27:17.000 --> 02:27:25.000
[Guest]: Even the American education system in some of these areas, they write convoluted long sentences.

02:27:25.000 --> 02:27:33.000
[Guest]: And how do you make people, how do you actually industrialize, if I may use the word, simple writing?

02:27:33.000 --> 02:27:35.000
[Guest]: Because there are, let's say, six analysts, seven analysts.

02:27:35.000 --> 02:27:38.000
[Guest]: I want to make, I'm lazy, basically.

02:27:38.000 --> 02:27:40.000
[Guest]: I want to make my job easy.

02:27:40.000 --> 02:27:44.000
[Guest]: So how do I make my editing job easier when they give it to me?

02:27:44.000 --> 02:27:46.000
[Guest]: Put in rules.

02:27:46.000 --> 02:27:48.000
[Guest]: So there's a second rule that we put in.

02:27:48.000 --> 02:27:50.000
[Guest]: 15 word.

02:27:50.000 --> 02:27:55.000
[Guest]: So any sentence, I said, if there's a sentence greater than 15 words, I'm not going to read it.

02:27:55.000 --> 02:27:57.000
[Guest]: So I won't edit the document.

02:27:57.000 --> 02:28:00.000
[Guest]: You better break it up into two sentences and bring it back to me.

02:28:00.000 --> 02:28:05.000
[Guest]: Because you can't write a complex sentence with 15 words.

02:28:05.000 --> 02:28:09.000
[Guest]: So we brought in some of these ideas of writing.

02:28:09.000 --> 02:28:15.000
[Guest]: And by the way, all our research works are freely available to everybody on the website.

02:28:15.000 --> 02:28:17.000
[Guest]: And the reason is simple.

02:28:17.000 --> 02:28:23.000
[Guest]: Part of our role, as we see it, is also that people of India should know what's happening in Parliament,

02:28:23.000 --> 02:28:26.000
[Guest]: should know what bills are coming up, should be able to understand the nuances,

02:28:26.000 --> 02:28:29.000
[Guest]: because that's how there's a greater public awareness and public debate.

02:28:29.000 --> 02:28:35.000
[Guest]: So if you want to look at a complex subject and you want to see what you have done,

02:28:35.000 --> 02:28:39.000
[Guest]: look at the first report on the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code.

02:28:39.000 --> 02:28:40.000
[Guest]: It's a complex one.

02:28:40.000 --> 02:28:44.000
[Guest]: Or look at the similar one which was not passed.

02:28:44.000 --> 02:28:50.000
[Guest]: FRDI bill, which is the insolvency bill for the financial guys.

02:28:50.000 --> 02:28:54.000
[Guest]: It was financial, I don't remember the full name, something.

02:28:54.000 --> 02:28:55.000
[Guest]: FRDI bill.

02:28:55.000 --> 02:28:56.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:28:56.000 --> 02:29:02.000
[Guest]: How do you regulate banks, the risk of a bank going under?

02:29:02.000 --> 02:29:03.000
[Guest]: How do you regulate that?

02:29:03.000 --> 02:29:04.000
[Guest]: How do you manage that?

02:29:04.000 --> 02:29:06.000
[Guest]: That is what that bill is doing.

02:29:06.000 --> 02:29:10.000
[Guest]: And we have written, summarized the bill in two pages.

02:29:10.000 --> 02:29:19.000
[Guest]: Or even we had, because it's more current, we have a brief on the website on the draft cryptocurrency bill.

02:29:19.000 --> 02:29:20.000
[Guest]: Wow.

02:29:20.000 --> 02:29:22.000
[Guest]: First question is, what is cryptocurrency?

02:29:22.000 --> 02:29:23.000
[Guest]: What is a Bitcoin?

02:29:23.000 --> 02:29:25.000
[Guest]: So we are trying to explain that.

02:29:25.000 --> 02:29:29.000
[Guest]: And all in one and a half pages or two pages, because that's the space we have.

02:29:29.000 --> 02:29:35.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, I feel like I've met such a kindred soul because all of this is stuff that I tell my students as well.

02:29:35.000 --> 02:29:39.000
[Amit Varma]: For example, that whole structural thing of ABCDE would start with E instead.

02:29:39.000 --> 02:29:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of my pet peeves about op-eds or opinion pieces is that initially you don't know what the stance of the person is.

02:29:45.000 --> 02:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: You are taken for granted as if that person is entitled to you reading the full thing to figure it out, which really irritates me.

02:29:51.000 --> 02:29:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And another thing I tell participants of my course is that the full stop is your best friend.

02:29:56.000 --> 02:30:02.000
[Amit Varma]: And for a lot of writing, like opinion writing, op-ed writing, writing for large audiences, it really is.

02:30:02.000 --> 02:30:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Though obviously the caveat there is if you're writing fiction or personal essays or whatever, sometimes your sentences need to be long.

02:30:09.000 --> 02:30:13.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a good thing you're building that slow rhythm, but not in this kind of writing.

02:30:13.000 --> 02:30:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I completely agree with all of that.

02:30:15.000 --> 02:30:19.000
[Amit Varma]: And I was going to ask if all of this is accessible to the public and you've just answered that question.

02:30:19.000 --> 02:30:22.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll give the link from the show notes.

02:30:22.000 --> 02:30:31.000
[Amit Varma]: The other element of what you pointed out is that what I have found and what I keep telling my students is that if you force yourself to write in a clear way,

02:30:31.000 --> 02:30:34.000
[Amit Varma]: you are forcing yourself to think in a clear way.

02:30:34.000 --> 02:30:43.000
[Amit Varma]: It helps your thinking because, you know, if you haven't thought through a subject properly, you can still get by by using jargon and vague abstract terms and all of that.

02:30:43.000 --> 02:30:54.000
[Amit Varma]: But if you're going to explain it to your naniji or to your mum in your case, I mean, we have these different tests, then you are forced to use clear, simple language.

02:30:54.000 --> 02:30:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And you're forced to really understand the subject well enough.

02:30:57.000 --> 02:30:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And I also don't understand cryptocurrency.

02:30:59.000 --> 02:31:02.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to read this and see if that kind of helps me.

02:31:02.000 --> 02:31:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's, you know, go back to the subject of Parliament, which is so incredibly important.

02:31:08.000 --> 02:31:16.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, of course, you've spoken all about the anti-defection bill, but do you feel that one inherent limitation and what you can achieve through Parliament,

02:31:16.000 --> 02:31:23.000
[Amit Varma]: even if the anti-defection law was to go, it's just a structure of our republic where so much power is so centralized.

02:31:23.000 --> 02:31:29.000
[Amit Varma]: And as you correctly pointed out earlier, a lot of what affects people's life is really local.

02:31:29.000 --> 02:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Right. And the MP doesn't have much to do with that.

02:31:32.000 --> 02:31:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's really local.

02:31:33.000 --> 02:31:40.000
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you know, and I mean, obviously, you affect what you can and things scale better when they're happening in that.

02:31:40.000 --> 02:31:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the system is what it is and you have to work within that.

02:31:43.000 --> 02:31:48.000
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, does that also, you know, become a limitation?

02:31:48.000 --> 02:31:50.000
[Guest]: Yes, to some extent.

02:31:50.000 --> 02:31:53.000
[Guest]: So this is the dilemma.

02:31:53.000 --> 02:31:55.000
[Guest]: There are multiple problems here.

02:31:55.000 --> 02:32:03.000
[Guest]: One is we are a very large country in the sense we have one, whatever, 1.4 billion, 140 crore people.

02:32:03.000 --> 02:32:12.000
[Guest]: So the size of a central assembly like Parliament, like Lok Sabha, you can't have 3,000 people.

02:32:12.000 --> 02:32:16.000
[Guest]: Because an assembly of 3,000 people is meaningless.

02:32:16.000 --> 02:32:20.000
[Guest]: Then you'll be like the Chinese guy who will be once in five days a year or something rubber stamping.

02:32:20.000 --> 02:32:21.000
[Guest]: You can't have that.

02:32:21.000 --> 02:32:25.000
[Guest]: So you'll have a limit, maybe 500 become 600, 700.

02:32:25.000 --> 02:32:27.000
[Guest]: But it can't be much more than that.

02:32:27.000 --> 02:32:29.000
[Guest]: And divide that by this number.

02:32:29.000 --> 02:32:34.000
[Guest]: You have a constituency size of 20 lakh.

02:32:34.000 --> 02:32:37.000
[Guest]: So that we have to live with that.

02:32:37.000 --> 02:32:42.000
[Guest]: The answer to that is to actually have Parliament just certain things.

02:32:42.000 --> 02:32:44.000
[Guest]: And states are much smaller.

02:32:44.000 --> 02:32:46.000
[Guest]: The largest state is still very large, which is UP.

02:32:46.000 --> 02:32:56.000
[Guest]: But the second largest state is Maharashtra, which is about 10 crore, still very large, still larger than the United Kingdom or France or Germany.

02:32:56.000 --> 02:32:58.000
[Guest]: It is actually even Maharashtra is large.

02:32:58.000 --> 02:33:02.000
[Amit Varma]: The suburb where I live, Warsaw is larger than Iceland in population.

02:33:02.000 --> 02:33:03.000
[Guest]: Yeah, would be.

02:33:03.000 --> 02:33:14.000
[Guest]: Yesterday I was checking out because the Netherlands has imposed a lockdown because they had, I think, 13,000 or 15,000 cases of COVID.

02:33:14.000 --> 02:33:23.000
[Guest]: So they just put, so when I said I just Googled, I mean, so to the word, the first search result for credibility that has population of Netherlands.

02:33:23.000 --> 02:33:26.000
[Guest]: And it is less than Delhi.

02:33:26.000 --> 02:33:27.000
[Unknown]: It is half of Delhi.

02:33:27.000 --> 02:33:31.000
[Guest]: So the Netherlands is half of Delhi, roughly, or slightly more than half of Delhi, 60 percent.

02:33:31.000 --> 02:33:33.000
[Guest]: So I was just checking out or something like that.

02:33:33.000 --> 02:33:36.000
[Guest]: So we are a very populous country.

02:33:36.000 --> 02:33:43.000
[Guest]: So the thing is to move that and even move further down to the extent we can to the municipalities and panchayats and all that.

02:33:43.000 --> 02:33:46.000
[Guest]: Of course, the other problem is nobody willingly gives out power.

02:33:46.000 --> 02:33:48.000
[Guest]: Will Parliament give to the states?

02:33:48.000 --> 02:33:49.000
[Guest]: Will states further give down?

02:33:49.000 --> 02:33:50.000
[Guest]: Yes.

02:33:50.000 --> 02:33:52.000
[Guest]: But that can happen.

02:33:52.000 --> 02:33:58.000
[Guest]: I mean, there are strange things that have happened in this country, which I don't understand why they happened.

02:33:58.000 --> 02:34:06.000
[Guest]: Because again, if you go back to incentives and people work Western interests, these things should not have happened by that logic.

02:34:06.000 --> 02:34:10.000
[Guest]: My favorite example is the Right to Information Act.

02:34:10.000 --> 02:34:12.000
[Unknown]: Why did that get passed?

02:34:12.000 --> 02:34:14.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't know.

02:34:14.000 --> 02:34:16.000
[Amit Varma]: The people in power had the opposite incentives.

02:34:16.000 --> 02:34:18.000
[Guest]: Everyone had the opposite incentive.

02:34:18.000 --> 02:34:19.000
[Guest]: They don't want to be accountable.

02:34:19.000 --> 02:34:20.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:34:20.000 --> 02:34:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Until it passed.

02:34:21.000 --> 02:34:22.000
[Guest]: But it passed.

02:34:22.000 --> 02:34:25.000
[Guest]: So that's what keeps me, that's why I said I'm an optimist.

02:34:25.000 --> 02:34:26.000
[Guest]: Things happen.

02:34:26.000 --> 02:34:27.000
[Guest]: Why did it pass?

02:34:27.000 --> 02:34:28.000
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:34:28.000 --> 02:34:30.000
[Guest]: I don't understand things, but they have happened.

02:34:30.000 --> 02:34:38.000
[Guest]: So just because I don't understand the rational doesn't mean that there is not something else going on.

02:34:38.000 --> 02:34:40.000
[Guest]: It's just that I don't understand it.

02:34:40.000 --> 02:34:42.000
[Guest]: Maybe something is going on.

02:34:42.000 --> 02:34:48.000
[Guest]: Maybe my whatever framework is not good enough to capture that.

02:34:48.000 --> 02:34:50.000
[Guest]: But the fact is it happened.

02:34:50.000 --> 02:34:51.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:34:51.000 --> 02:34:52.000
[Guest]: You can't deny that.

02:34:52.000 --> 02:34:59.000
[Guest]: So things happen, which seem to go against all the rational that my framework gives me.

02:34:59.000 --> 02:35:04.000
[Guest]: One way to actually rethink the way we work as a country.

02:35:04.000 --> 02:35:05.000
[Guest]: Again, I don't know.

02:35:05.000 --> 02:35:07.000
[Guest]: Like I said, I don't understand why things happen.

02:35:07.000 --> 02:35:12.000
[Guest]: I'm an optimist that sometimes this might happen, though, again, incentives wise, it should not happen.

02:35:12.000 --> 02:35:16.000
[Guest]: If you think of concurrent list subjects, and if I go back to the original conception,

02:35:16.000 --> 02:35:19.000
[Guest]: there are three lists, right, in the constitution.

02:35:19.000 --> 02:35:25.000
[Guest]: The union list, which is primarily things where you need uniformity across the country.

02:35:25.000 --> 02:35:35.000
[Guest]: Like banking is uniform because, again, I want, whether I have a bank account in Delhi or in Bombay or in Calcutta or in Hyderabad,

02:35:35.000 --> 02:35:37.000
[Guest]: I should be able to comfortably interact.

02:35:37.000 --> 02:35:41.000
[Guest]: It should be a common law and I should have one RBI and non-multiple RBIs.

02:35:41.000 --> 02:35:43.000
[Guest]: There will be chaos.

02:35:43.000 --> 02:35:44.000
[Guest]: So banking should be.

02:35:44.000 --> 02:35:46.000
[Guest]: I should need to have the same currency.

02:35:46.000 --> 02:35:48.000
[Guest]: Not everybody is showing.

02:35:48.000 --> 02:35:49.000
[Guest]: Defense.

02:35:49.000 --> 02:35:50.000
[Guest]: And there are many of them.

02:35:50.000 --> 02:35:54.000
[Guest]: In fact, the list is much larger, but there are some obvious ones.

02:35:54.000 --> 02:35:59.000
[Guest]: There are some things which are definitely local, which is state list.

02:35:59.000 --> 02:36:02.000
[Guest]: And what is a concurrent list?

02:36:02.000 --> 02:36:10.000
[Guest]: I would think of it as you need a certain level of uniformity, but you need a lot of tailoring.

02:36:10.000 --> 02:36:19.000
[Guest]: So in a concurrent list subject, when parliament makes law, it should make law which is reasonably skeletal.

02:36:19.000 --> 02:36:20.000
[Guest]: It should be a law.

02:36:20.000 --> 02:36:24.000
[Guest]: So you can't move outside this, but within this, you play around.

02:36:24.000 --> 02:36:33.000
[Guest]: So in fact, I had made this argument when we were invited by the standing committee in the first,

02:36:33.000 --> 02:36:37.000
[Guest]: when the land acquisition bill was done in 2013.

02:36:37.000 --> 02:36:41.000
[Guest]: I think we went in 2011 or 12 at that time.

02:36:41.000 --> 02:36:46.000
[Guest]: In the committee, I made the argument that this is a concurrent list subject.

02:36:46.000 --> 02:36:49.000
[Guest]: I don't know what it is, but I can easily say that.

02:36:49.000 --> 02:36:54.000
[Guest]: What works in Kerala is unlikely to work in Uttar Pradesh and vice versa,

02:36:54.000 --> 02:36:59.000
[Guest]: because they are very different local scenarios or in Mizoram or in Punjab.

02:36:59.000 --> 02:37:05.000
[Guest]: If you have one law up to the final detail, which is same for Punjab and Mizoram and Uttar Pradesh and Kerala,

02:37:05.000 --> 02:37:07.000
[Guest]: something is going to fail.

02:37:07.000 --> 02:37:08.000
[Guest]: It won't work.

02:37:08.000 --> 02:37:16.000
[Guest]: So you make the skeletal and let the state assemblies on that put on the more details.

02:37:16.000 --> 02:37:19.000
[Guest]: That is one way to think of it.

02:37:19.000 --> 02:37:27.000
[Guest]: We don't do it because again, which government at the center doesn't want to dot all the i's and cross all the t's and say,

02:37:27.000 --> 02:37:30.000
[Guest]: okay, I have done the perfect law.

02:37:30.000 --> 02:37:31.000
[Guest]: Every government will do that.

02:37:31.000 --> 02:37:33.000
[Guest]: That's the problem.

02:37:33.000 --> 02:37:38.000
[Guest]: Which civil servant is going to say that I don't know everything.

02:37:38.000 --> 02:37:42.000
[Amit Varma]: So four final questions for you, unless digressions occur.

02:37:42.000 --> 02:37:45.000
[Amit Varma]: And digressions sometimes occur, but I've taken a lot of your time.

02:37:45.000 --> 02:37:50.000
[Amit Varma]: So my fourth last question, I don't know if there'll even be a word for it.

02:37:50.000 --> 02:37:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Like penultimate is second last.

02:37:51.000 --> 02:37:53.000
[Amit Varma]: What would fourth last be?

02:37:53.000 --> 02:37:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Quadruple ultimate.

02:37:54.000 --> 02:37:55.000
[Guest]: I don't know.

02:37:55.000 --> 02:37:57.000
[Guest]: I mean, in India, we anyway you say second last.

02:37:57.000 --> 02:38:02.000
[Guest]: So penultimate is like, I don't think most people understand.

02:38:02.000 --> 02:38:03.000
[Unknown]: Fourth last.

02:38:03.000 --> 02:38:07.000
[Guest]: Like get down at the second last bus stop is an instruction I have got.

02:38:07.000 --> 02:38:11.000
[Guest]: And I've not figured out how do I find out which is the second last until I go to the last.

02:38:11.000 --> 02:38:12.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:38:12.000 --> 02:38:17.000
[Amit Varma]: Also, you mentioned earlier the importance of a comma here, the importance of a hyphen comes into play.

02:38:17.000 --> 02:38:22.000
[Amit Varma]: Because when I say this is my fourth last question, there has to be a hyphen between the fourth and the last.

02:38:22.000 --> 02:38:26.000
[Amit Varma]: If that hyphen was not there, it would mean that I am deceiving you.

02:38:26.000 --> 02:38:28.000
[Amit Varma]: That I have told you I'm asking a last question.

02:38:28.000 --> 02:38:33.000
[Amit Varma]: And after doing it three times before, I am asking you a fourth last question.

02:38:33.000 --> 02:38:34.000
[Amit Varma]: But I'm not doing that.

02:38:34.000 --> 02:38:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm asking you a fourth last question.

02:38:35.000 --> 02:38:37.000
[Amit Varma]: What a silly digression.

02:38:37.000 --> 02:38:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you've spoken like a link to this talk of yours you gave, which is very, I think you might consider it common knowledge.

02:38:43.000 --> 02:38:49.000
[Amit Varma]: But I think it's a lot of people don't really understand the nuts and bolts of how parliament works and should work.

02:38:49.000 --> 02:38:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And you've spoken about the three key roles of parliament, which is making laws, oversight of government, financial sanction and oversight.

02:38:56.000 --> 02:39:00.000
[Amit Varma]: All of which, obviously, your work really kind of helps with.

02:39:00.000 --> 02:39:10.000
[Amit Varma]: But what is also happening, what you also pointed to is one, the increased number of disruptions and two, that parliament sits less and less.

02:39:10.000 --> 02:39:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I'm sure the anti-defection law in the sense that all this doesn't really matter may play a part in that.

02:39:16.000 --> 02:39:20.000
[Amit Varma]: But parliament is just sitting much less than it used to, much less days of the year.

02:39:20.000 --> 02:39:30.000
[Amit Varma]: And within those days, there are constant disruptions happening by opposition members or whatever, which every party has done when it is in opposition.

02:39:30.000 --> 02:39:35.000
[Amit Varma]: And Arun Jaitley, in fact, you've pointed out famously defended it in this piece he wrote in 2012.

02:39:35.000 --> 02:39:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And then he was on the, the shoe was on the other side very soon.

02:39:38.000 --> 02:39:43.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, just looking at that, I mean, in theory, yeah, these are the things parliament should do.

02:39:43.000 --> 02:39:46.000
[Amit Varma]: And these are, this is how our democracy runs.

02:39:46.000 --> 02:39:47.000
[Amit Varma]: This is our machine.

02:39:47.000 --> 02:39:55.000
[Amit Varma]: So, I see the design of the machine and it's intricate and beautiful and whatever flaws there are, are minor and it's a magnificent conception.

02:39:55.000 --> 02:40:03.000
[Amit Varma]: But then I look at the working of the machine, aur yaha pe lever toota hua hai, screws are missing, rat is cracks, scurrying around inside.

02:40:03.000 --> 02:40:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, and I guess at a meta level, it can be made better because parliament itself and politicians themselves can reform the system.

02:40:09.000 --> 02:40:13.000
[Amit Varma]: And you're giving them the knowledge and the information that can help them arrive at that.

02:40:13.000 --> 02:40:19.000
[Amit Varma]: But what is your sense? Does it sometimes sort of fill you with despair at why am I even doing this?

02:40:19.000 --> 02:40:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Or are your kind of successes good enough to say that no, no, it's worth it?

02:40:24.000 --> 02:40:28.000
[Guest]: There are, of course, times of extreme frustration.

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:35.000
[Guest]: I mean, you, let's say we have worked hard on a bill, put in two months of research, gone and briefed MPs.

02:40:35.000 --> 02:40:39.000
[Guest]: They are interested, they have called us, they have spent their time on it.

02:40:39.000 --> 02:40:44.000
[Guest]: And then there's disruption. And in 30 seconds, the bill is invalid in parliament without any debate.

02:40:44.000 --> 02:40:46.000
[Guest]: Happens. It's frustrating.

02:40:46.000 --> 02:40:54.000
[Guest]: But there are also times when you can see that all this work has actually come to fruition.

02:40:54.000 --> 02:40:56.000
[Guest]: And there is something happening with that.

02:40:56.000 --> 02:41:02.000
[Guest]: So that keeps us on. And the very fact that there are enough MPs.

02:41:02.000 --> 02:41:08.000
[Guest]: And again, when I say MPs, I'm actually, we are increasingly doing work with MLAs also.

02:41:08.000 --> 02:41:13.000
[Guest]: Enough of them who are actually keen makes it worthwhile.

02:41:13.000 --> 02:41:18.000
[Guest]: I mean, I'll just give you an example of MLAs, for example, we did a workshop.

02:41:18.000 --> 02:41:24.000
[Guest]: This was actually our first physical workshop since.

02:41:24.000 --> 02:41:29.000
[Guest]: I mean, the last one was in February, January or February, February 2020.

02:41:29.000 --> 02:41:34.000
[Guest]: We did one or Gannett, I think. And then obviously everything shut down.

02:41:34.000 --> 02:41:38.000
[Guest]: We did a workshop in September this year when things had opened up in Delhi.

02:41:38.000 --> 02:41:45.000
[Guest]: For MLAs from the northeastern states focusing on issues that they are interested in, etc.

02:41:45.000 --> 02:41:50.000
[Guest]: We had to actually close, we had to say, OK, enough.

02:41:50.000 --> 02:41:56.000
[Guest]: Because in a workshop, in a room when you're doing, and especially we wanted, given now,

02:41:56.000 --> 02:42:00.000
[Guest]: we also wanted to make sure that we are not crowding people.

02:42:00.000 --> 02:42:04.000
[Guest]: And this was in the early September. So some distancing, etc.

02:42:04.000 --> 02:42:08.000
[Guest]: So we said we want about 30, 35 people. I mean, that's a large enough group.

02:42:08.000 --> 02:42:12.000
[Guest]: We don't want 70 people in. And we had 35.

02:42:12.000 --> 02:42:16.000
[Guest]: We actually had to turn away people saying that, yes, we understand.

02:42:16.000 --> 02:42:20.000
[Guest]: We'll do a second one. We'll definitely, we don't want to not serve you.

02:42:20.000 --> 02:42:24.000
[Guest]: But we can't do it today because there are people,

02:42:24.000 --> 02:42:27.000
[Guest]: we just first come first serve and others come before you.

02:42:27.000 --> 02:42:32.000
[Guest]: So there is and they are sitting for two full days listening to issues, understanding things,

02:42:32.000 --> 02:42:37.000
[Guest]: understanding how budgets are done, understanding what is the look is policy and things like that.

02:42:37.000 --> 02:42:40.000
[Guest]: Why are they spending two days away from the constituency,

02:42:40.000 --> 02:42:45.000
[Guest]: sitting in a conference room in Delhi, coming all the way?

02:42:45.000 --> 02:42:49.000
[Guest]: And coming at both their time and their cost, right?

02:42:49.000 --> 02:42:52.000
[Guest]: I mean, they are paying for their travel and stay and all that.

02:42:52.000 --> 02:42:55.000
[Guest]: Why are they doing that? There's something going on.

02:42:55.000 --> 02:42:59.000
[Guest]: Therefore, if what we do helps.

02:42:59.000 --> 02:43:04.000
[Guest]: Like in any group and that goes for any organization, any type of organization,

02:43:04.000 --> 02:43:11.000
[Guest]: there is also always a distribution of sincere people, average people and slackers.

02:43:11.000 --> 02:43:16.000
[Guest]: And the system moves forward when you move people from the right, whatever,

02:43:16.000 --> 02:43:18.000
[Guest]: one extreme towards the better extreme, right?

02:43:18.000 --> 02:43:24.000
[Guest]: And the guys at the sincere and hardworking actually become more efficient.

02:43:24.000 --> 02:43:28.000
[Guest]: So our thing is, OK, there are certain set of people that we can't do much about.

02:43:28.000 --> 02:43:30.000
[Guest]: I mean, they are not interested.

02:43:30.000 --> 02:43:34.000
[Guest]: But if there are people who are keen and interested and they don't have the tools,

02:43:34.000 --> 02:43:37.000
[Guest]: to give you a cricket example, because we seem to love it.

02:43:37.000 --> 02:43:45.000
[Guest]: If you send Virat Kohli into bat with a hockey stick, will he score the century?

02:43:45.000 --> 02:43:48.000
[Guest]: So you need to give him the bat.

02:43:48.000 --> 02:43:51.000
[Guest]: But if Virat Kohli is not interested in scoring that century,

02:43:51.000 --> 02:43:54.000
[Guest]: give him the best bat, he can't do anything.

02:43:54.000 --> 02:43:57.000
[Guest]: If he doesn't have the skill set or the intent, he can't.

02:43:57.000 --> 02:44:01.000
[Guest]: Assuming that he has that, he needs the equipment.

02:44:01.000 --> 02:44:04.000
[Guest]: What we are doing is trying to improve the equipment.

02:44:04.000 --> 02:44:06.000
[Guest]: We can't do more than that.

02:44:06.000 --> 02:44:11.000
[Guest]: But I can see that that helps and that's what keeps us going.

02:44:11.000 --> 02:44:14.000
[Amit Varma]: So a digressive question before I get to my last three questions.

02:44:14.000 --> 02:44:18.000
[Amit Varma]: One thing that researchers have interestingly found and Adam Grant writes about it

02:44:18.000 --> 02:44:24.000
[Amit Varma]: in his recent book, Think Again, is how a common quality to leaders everywhere

02:44:24.000 --> 02:44:27.000
[Amit Varma]: across industry and whatever the surveys have shown,

02:44:27.000 --> 02:44:30.000
[Amit Varma]: is not things like intelligence or education or all of those,

02:44:30.000 --> 02:44:33.000
[Amit Varma]: but their humility and eagerness to learn.

02:44:33.000 --> 02:44:39.000
[Amit Varma]: So do you find that this correlates well with those sort of legislators

02:44:39.000 --> 02:44:41.000
[Amit Varma]: that you work with who are at the sincere end,

02:44:41.000 --> 02:44:46.000
[Amit Varma]: that what may matter is not necessarily your native intelligence or any of those things,

02:44:46.000 --> 02:44:50.000
[Amit Varma]: but your intentionality that you can come there without any education,

02:44:50.000 --> 02:44:53.000
[Amit Varma]: but you want to do it and you're open to ideas.

02:44:53.000 --> 02:44:55.000
[Amit Varma]: You're not stuck in an ideology.

02:44:55.000 --> 02:44:58.000
[Guest]: Most of them are open because most of them are humble enough

02:44:58.000 --> 02:45:01.000
[Guest]: to say that they don't know, especially the technical.

02:45:01.000 --> 02:45:05.000
[Guest]: So we are not going and telling them how to win an election because they're experts in that.

02:45:05.000 --> 02:45:10.000
[Guest]: They know that they are not experts in, let us say, electricity regulation.

02:45:10.000 --> 02:45:14.000
[Guest]: So they don't have any ego in understanding that or even things.

02:45:14.000 --> 02:45:18.000
[Guest]: And the interesting thing is that they know a lot

02:45:18.000 --> 02:45:21.000
[Guest]: because they have a lot of on-ground experience.

02:45:21.000 --> 02:45:26.000
[Guest]: I'll just give you an example. Land acquisition.

02:45:26.000 --> 02:45:30.000
[Guest]: We had been working on that for over 10 years.

02:45:30.000 --> 02:45:34.000
[Guest]: I started actually looking at it first time when the first bill came in in 2007.

02:45:34.000 --> 02:45:36.000
[Guest]: Finally, it was passed in 2013.

02:45:36.000 --> 02:45:42.000
[Guest]: Then the NDA1 brought in an amendment in 2014, which didn't get passed,

02:45:42.000 --> 02:45:45.000
[Guest]: but we wrote a brief on that, we went to the committee,

02:45:45.000 --> 02:45:47.000
[Guest]: and there were MPs who were interested in it.

02:45:47.000 --> 02:45:51.000
[Guest]: So one of those MPs came to our office and wanted to understand it in detail.

02:45:51.000 --> 02:45:54.000
[Guest]: Then while we were explaining, this MP says that,

02:45:54.000 --> 02:45:59.000
[Guest]: you know, if you want to acquire land for a road highway,

02:45:59.000 --> 02:46:03.000
[Guest]: it's not too difficult to get it as long as you pay a reasonable price.

02:46:03.000 --> 02:46:06.000
[Guest]: But railway line is very difficult to acquire land.

02:46:06.000 --> 02:46:08.000
[Guest]: So I said, why?

02:46:08.000 --> 02:46:12.000
[Guest]: And then once he says it, you kick yourself as in, why didn't you think of it?

02:46:12.000 --> 02:46:17.000
[Guest]: Which is that, if it's a road, it connects to the nearest town.

02:46:17.000 --> 02:46:19.000
[Guest]: So I'm not giving all my land, right?

02:46:19.000 --> 02:46:22.000
[Guest]: I'm giving a portion of my land because it's a linear project.

02:46:22.000 --> 02:46:25.000
[Guest]: The remaining land value goes up. I have better connectivity. I gain.

02:46:25.000 --> 02:46:28.000
[Guest]: If it's a railway line cutting through my farm,

02:46:28.000 --> 02:46:32.000
[Guest]: I can't go take my tractor from this side to that side of the farm.

02:46:32.000 --> 02:46:34.000
[Guest]: I have to drive five kilometers to reach that level crossing

02:46:34.000 --> 02:46:36.000
[Unknown]: or a flyover and cut across.

02:46:36.000 --> 02:46:37.000
[Unknown]: Wow.

02:46:37.000 --> 02:46:40.000
[Unknown]: And that line doesn't give me any advantage.

02:46:40.000 --> 02:46:44.000
[Guest]: Some train passing through, it doesn't even stop anywhere nearby.

02:46:44.000 --> 02:46:45.000
[Guest]: Wow.

02:46:45.000 --> 02:46:47.000
[Guest]: So I have no benefits. I get hurt.

02:46:47.000 --> 02:46:52.000
[Guest]: So regardless, even if you pay me good market value, it hurts me.

02:46:52.000 --> 02:46:55.000
[Unknown]: Now this, the MP knows, because of the constituency,

02:46:55.000 --> 02:46:58.000
[Unknown]: they will protest on certain things.

02:46:58.000 --> 02:47:01.000
[Unknown]: Sitting here and talking to people, I don't know.

02:47:01.000 --> 02:47:04.000
[Amit Varma]: I would not have been able to guess this had you just told me.

02:47:04.000 --> 02:47:08.000
[Unknown]: But once I tell you, you say, why didn't I think of it?

02:47:08.000 --> 02:47:10.000
[Unknown]: It's obvious, right?

02:47:10.000 --> 02:47:16.000
[Guest]: So they have a huge amount of practical on-ground knowledge

02:47:16.000 --> 02:47:18.000
[Guest]: and they're generally humble.

02:47:18.000 --> 02:47:21.000
[Guest]: And see, that is the one set of people

02:47:21.000 --> 02:47:26.000
[Unknown]: who have to get validation once every five years.

02:47:26.000 --> 02:47:28.000
[Unknown]: They go get kicked by the constituents every five years.

02:47:28.000 --> 02:47:31.000
[Unknown]: That keeps the humility on.

02:47:31.000 --> 02:47:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Third last question, finally, I won't digress further.

02:47:34.000 --> 02:47:36.000
[Amit Varma]: It strikes me that one of the things you do,

02:47:36.000 --> 02:47:39.000
[Amit Varma]: and this could be as important a public service

02:47:39.000 --> 02:47:41.000
[Amit Varma]: as what you set out to do,

02:47:41.000 --> 02:47:44.000
[Amit Varma]: is that you're not just building policies and spreading ideas,

02:47:44.000 --> 02:47:48.000
[Amit Varma]: you're also building people and enabling this ecosystem

02:47:48.000 --> 02:47:51.000
[Amit Varma]: of people who think deeply about these things.

02:47:51.000 --> 02:47:53.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, it's been more than 16 years,

02:47:53.000 --> 02:47:57.000
[Amit Varma]: 16 years and two months, I guess, since BRS was formed.

02:47:57.000 --> 02:47:59.000
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about this,

02:47:59.000 --> 02:48:01.000
[Amit Varma]: because throughout this time, you must have worked

02:48:01.000 --> 02:48:03.000
[Amit Varma]: with many, many young people who've gone off

02:48:03.000 --> 02:48:05.000
[Amit Varma]: into different directions and done things.

02:48:05.000 --> 02:48:07.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, even through the LAM fellowship,

02:48:07.000 --> 02:48:10.000
[Amit Varma]: you've given that invaluable experience

02:48:10.000 --> 02:48:13.000
[Amit Varma]: to people who understand the system better.

02:48:13.000 --> 02:48:15.000
[Amit Varma]: What is your feeling about this?

02:48:15.000 --> 02:48:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Because if I was in your place, damn, I would be so proud.

02:48:19.000 --> 02:48:21.000
[Amit Varma]: So what do you see happening here?

02:48:21.000 --> 02:48:23.000
[Amit Varma]: Like people will often bemoan young people,

02:48:23.000 --> 02:48:25.000
[Amit Varma]: perhaps because they've only experienced

02:48:25.000 --> 02:48:27.000
[Amit Varma]: vocal young people on Twitter,

02:48:27.000 --> 02:48:30.000
[Amit Varma]: and say, nahi yaar, yeh generation aisa hai, waisa hai.

02:48:30.000 --> 02:48:33.000
[Amit Varma]: But it strikes me that many of the people

02:48:33.000 --> 02:48:35.000
[Amit Varma]: I interact with today are just incredible,

02:48:35.000 --> 02:48:38.000
[Amit Varma]: great work ethic, work hard, humility, all of that.

02:48:38.000 --> 02:48:41.000
[Amit Varma]: What's your experience building your,

02:48:41.000 --> 02:48:43.000
[Amit Varma]: the troops of Madhavan, as it were, if I canâ¦

02:48:43.000 --> 02:48:45.000
[Guest]: Oh, not at all.

02:48:45.000 --> 02:48:49.000
[Guest]: No, actually, young people keep me very, again,

02:48:49.000 --> 02:48:51.000
[Guest]: keep me young, let me put it that way.

02:48:51.000 --> 02:48:55.000
[Guest]: So like the median age in my office today

02:48:55.000 --> 02:48:58.000
[Guest]: is I think 25 or 20, they're less than half my age.

02:48:58.000 --> 02:49:02.000
[Guest]: And there are people who have joined now

02:49:02.000 --> 02:49:04.000
[Guest]: whose parents are younger than me.

02:49:04.000 --> 02:49:05.000
[Guest]: Wow.

02:49:05.000 --> 02:49:07.000
[Guest]: Because I'm 53, it just means that I am old.

02:49:07.000 --> 02:49:11.000
[Guest]: So, and they keep me going, actually.

02:49:11.000 --> 02:49:14.000
[Guest]: Other than that, again, I would say

02:49:14.000 --> 02:49:17.000
[Guest]: when people say generalized things,

02:49:17.000 --> 02:49:20.000
[Guest]: that's always a distribution.

02:49:20.000 --> 02:49:24.000
[Guest]: And of course, when I'm hiring for either PRS or LAM,

02:49:24.000 --> 02:49:27.000
[Guest]: it's my attempt to take the right end of the distribution

02:49:27.000 --> 02:49:30.000
[Guest]: because that's what I want to hire.

02:49:30.000 --> 02:49:34.000
[Guest]: So maybe I am not talking about a typical young person.

02:49:34.000 --> 02:49:37.000
[Unknown]: I have a selection bias.

02:49:37.000 --> 02:49:43.000
[Guest]: But both in terms of sincerity and in terms of idealism,

02:49:43.000 --> 02:49:45.000
[Guest]: they are way more idealistic

02:49:45.000 --> 02:49:47.000
[Guest]: than I could think I was at that age.

02:49:47.000 --> 02:49:51.000
[Guest]: And I think a bunch of it is also that

02:49:51.000 --> 02:49:54.000
[Guest]: the country has moved both economically too,

02:49:54.000 --> 02:49:57.000
[Guest]: where you can effort to do that.

02:49:57.000 --> 02:50:00.000
[Guest]: I mean, you're reasonably well off.

02:50:00.000 --> 02:50:02.000
[Guest]: There are also opportunities.

02:50:02.000 --> 02:50:04.000
[Guest]: When I was 21, maybe there was no chance.

02:50:04.000 --> 02:50:06.000
[Guest]: I mean, I needed to get a job

02:50:06.000 --> 02:50:08.000
[Guest]: which was paying me fairly decently.

02:50:08.000 --> 02:50:11.000
[Guest]: Not that we pay very badly at that time.

02:50:11.000 --> 02:50:14.000
[Guest]: But I mean, you can live on it comfortably.

02:50:14.000 --> 02:50:17.000
[Guest]: But you need to want to build a career here.

02:50:17.000 --> 02:50:20.000
[Guest]: And in those days, if anybody had said

02:50:20.000 --> 02:50:25.000
[Guest]: like I said, I followed the usual path of engineer and MBA.

02:50:25.000 --> 02:50:27.000
[Guest]: Why? Because you get a job.

02:50:27.000 --> 02:50:29.000
[Guest]: I didn't know anything about engineering

02:50:29.000 --> 02:50:31.000
[Guest]: when I went in for engineering, right?

02:50:31.000 --> 02:50:34.000
[Guest]: But I knew that if I finish an engineering degree,

02:50:34.000 --> 02:50:35.000
[Guest]: a job is assured.

02:50:35.000 --> 02:50:36.000
[Guest]: Whereas if I do something else,

02:50:36.000 --> 02:50:38.000
[Guest]: I don't know whether I'll get a job or not.

02:50:38.000 --> 02:50:42.000
[Guest]: So that was a predominant concern of those days.

02:50:42.000 --> 02:50:46.000
[Guest]: Today, what you are doing

02:50:46.000 --> 02:50:50.000
[Amit Varma]: would have been fairly inconceivable in 1990.

02:50:50.000 --> 02:50:52.000
[Unknown]: You would not even have thought of this.

02:50:52.000 --> 02:50:54.000
[Guest]: So the country has moved.

02:50:54.000 --> 02:50:55.000
[Guest]: Country has evolved.

02:50:55.000 --> 02:50:57.000
[Guest]: And that has opened up opportunities.

02:50:57.000 --> 02:51:00.000
[Guest]: That I think has given the courage

02:51:00.000 --> 02:51:04.000
[Guest]: for lots of younger people to experiment and come.

02:51:04.000 --> 02:51:05.000
[Guest]: So they do.

02:51:05.000 --> 02:51:08.000
[Guest]: The good thing, and you're right about that.

02:51:08.000 --> 02:51:10.000
[Guest]: I am very proud of them.

02:51:10.000 --> 02:51:12.000
[Guest]: There are people,

02:51:12.000 --> 02:51:14.000
[Guest]: so there are two types of young people,

02:51:14.000 --> 02:51:16.000
[Guest]: which we have had.

02:51:16.000 --> 02:51:17.000
[Guest]: So we get a lot of undergrads,

02:51:17.000 --> 02:51:18.000
[Guest]: even we hire them.

02:51:18.000 --> 02:51:19.000
[Guest]: And we know that.

02:51:19.000 --> 02:51:20.000
[Guest]: And in fact,

02:51:20.000 --> 02:51:22.000
[Guest]: I kick them out at a particular point of time

02:51:22.000 --> 02:51:23.000
[Guest]: and say, okay,

02:51:23.000 --> 02:51:28.000
[Guest]: now it's time you go and do something else.

02:51:28.000 --> 02:51:30.000
[Guest]: Because you need to grow.

02:51:30.000 --> 02:51:33.000
[Guest]: But many of them have done interesting things later.

02:51:33.000 --> 02:51:34.000
[Guest]: And of course,

02:51:34.000 --> 02:51:37.000
[Guest]: I think it's 400 Lampfellows every year.

02:51:37.000 --> 02:51:39.000
[Guest]: It's about 50 of them.

02:51:39.000 --> 02:51:40.000
[Guest]: We have done 10 batches,

02:51:40.000 --> 02:51:41.000
[Guest]: first batch was small.

02:51:41.000 --> 02:51:43.000
[Guest]: So it's more than 450 Lampfellows still now.

02:51:43.000 --> 02:51:46.000
[Guest]: And we did a count about a year,

02:51:46.000 --> 02:51:50.000
[Guest]: year and a half back about what are they doing now.

02:51:50.000 --> 02:51:56.000
[Guest]: About 60% of them were in the politics slash policy space.

02:51:56.000 --> 02:51:57.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:51:57.000 --> 02:52:00.000
[Guest]: I'll just explain to you what I mean by this.

02:52:00.000 --> 02:52:01.000
[Guest]: Politics,

02:52:01.000 --> 02:52:02.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:52:02.000 --> 02:52:05.000
[Guest]: they are working directly with an MP,

02:52:05.000 --> 02:52:06.000
[Guest]: a minister,

02:52:06.000 --> 02:52:07.000
[Guest]: an MLA,

02:52:07.000 --> 02:52:08.000
[Guest]: a party,

02:52:08.000 --> 02:52:13.000
[Guest]: or even with something like Prashant Kishore's outfit,

02:52:13.000 --> 02:52:16.000
[Guest]: or ABM of the BJP side.

02:52:16.000 --> 02:52:17.000
[Guest]: And one of these,

02:52:17.000 --> 02:52:19.000
[Guest]: which is direct politics.

02:52:19.000 --> 02:52:20.000
[Guest]: Policy,

02:52:20.000 --> 02:52:23.000
[Guest]: when I say it means a think tank,

02:52:23.000 --> 02:52:26.000
[Guest]: or even in a corporate policy group,

02:52:26.000 --> 02:52:31.000
[Guest]: or in an activist group in the policy,

02:52:31.000 --> 02:52:33.000
[Guest]: parsing the policy side.

02:52:33.000 --> 02:52:34.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:52:33.000 --> 02:52:35.000
[Guest]: that's what I'm calling policy.

02:52:35.000 --> 02:52:37.000
[Guest]: So 60% are about that.

02:52:37.000 --> 02:52:40.000
[Guest]: 20% are studying because they came after an undergrad,

02:52:40.000 --> 02:52:42.000
[Guest]: they've gone for a master's,

02:52:42.000 --> 02:52:45.000
[Guest]: and many of them are in the top schools around the world.

02:52:45.000 --> 02:52:46.000
[Guest]: So we have had,

02:52:46.000 --> 02:52:47.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:52:46.000 --> 02:52:48.000
[Guest]: if you think of the US,

02:52:48.000 --> 02:52:49.000
[Guest]: these Lampfellows are there in,

02:52:49.000 --> 02:52:50.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:52:50.000 --> 02:52:51.000
[Guest]: name it,

02:52:50.000 --> 02:52:51.000
[Guest]: Harvard,

02:52:51.000 --> 02:52:52.000
[Guest]: Yale,

02:52:51.000 --> 02:52:52.000
[Guest]: Stanford,

02:52:52.000 --> 02:52:53.000
[Guest]: NYU.

02:52:53.000 --> 02:52:54.000
[Guest]: If you look East,

02:52:54.000 --> 02:52:55.000
[Guest]: in US,

02:52:55.000 --> 02:52:56.000
[Guest]: in India,

02:52:56.000 --> 02:52:57.000
[Guest]: they've gone for management.

02:52:57.000 --> 02:52:58.000
[Guest]: They've gone to the IIMs,

02:52:58.000 --> 02:52:59.000
[Guest]: ISB,

02:52:59.000 --> 02:53:01.000
[Guest]: places like the top places.

02:53:01.000 --> 02:53:05.000
[Guest]: So they're actually getting a top rung second digit,

02:53:05.000 --> 02:53:08.000
[Guest]: whatever second degree before they decide what they want to do.

02:53:08.000 --> 02:53:09.000
[Guest]: So,

02:53:09.000 --> 02:53:11.000
[Guest]: and many of them are also,

02:53:11.000 --> 02:53:17.000
[Guest]: I think we are changing the way they look at politics and politicians.

02:53:17.000 --> 02:53:21.000
[Guest]: Because there is this inherent cynicism,

02:53:21.000 --> 02:53:23.000
[Guest]: and not just India,

02:53:23.000 --> 02:53:25.000
[Guest]: about politicians.

02:53:25.000 --> 02:53:28.000
[Guest]: And I'm not saying they are the best people in the world.

02:53:28.000 --> 02:53:30.000
[Guest]: There is a lot of corruption.

02:53:30.000 --> 02:53:32.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:53:32.000 --> 02:53:34.000
[Guest]: there will be enough moral bankruptcy.

02:53:34.000 --> 02:53:35.000
[Guest]: Anyway.

02:53:35.000 --> 02:53:36.000
[Guest]: But,

02:53:36.000 --> 02:53:38.000
[Guest]: what people don't appreciate,

02:53:38.000 --> 02:53:43.000
[Guest]: is the complexity that politicians live with.

02:53:43.000 --> 02:53:46.000
[Guest]: And the pressure that push them towards some of this.

02:53:46.000 --> 02:53:48.000
[Guest]: They are not necessarily bad people.

02:53:48.000 --> 02:53:51.000
[Guest]: But they live in an extremely complex environment.

02:53:51.000 --> 02:53:52.000
[Guest]: And they need to,

02:53:52.000 --> 02:53:55.000
[Guest]: and if you don't behave in a particular way in that environment,

02:53:55.000 --> 02:53:56.000
[Guest]: you die.

02:53:56.000 --> 02:53:59.000
[Guest]: Die in the sense your career is finished.

02:53:59.000 --> 02:54:01.000
[Guest]: So you need to manage that,

02:54:01.000 --> 02:54:02.000
[Guest]: like anyone else.

02:54:02.000 --> 02:54:04.000
[Guest]: People don't understand that.

02:54:04.000 --> 02:54:08.000
[Guest]: And people don't understand that many of them are trying to do,

02:54:08.000 --> 02:54:11.000
[Guest]: what they think is good for society.

02:54:11.000 --> 02:54:12.000
[Guest]: Now we may,

02:54:12.000 --> 02:54:13.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:54:13.000 --> 02:54:14.000
[Guest]: for example,

02:54:14.000 --> 02:54:15.000
[Guest]: the present government,

02:54:15.000 --> 02:54:17.000
[Guest]: I'm reasonably sure that,

02:54:17.000 --> 02:54:18.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:54:18.000 --> 02:54:21.000
[Guest]: you may differ with thinking what they,

02:54:21.000 --> 02:54:23.000
[Guest]: you may think that what they're doing is not good.

02:54:23.000 --> 02:54:24.000
[Guest]: But,

02:54:24.000 --> 02:54:26.000
[Guest]: I'm sure they think,

02:54:26.000 --> 02:54:27.000
[Guest]: what they are doing,

02:54:27.000 --> 02:54:29.000
[Guest]: is good for the country.

02:54:29.000 --> 02:54:33.000
[Guest]: So that is a difference of opinion on the ideology.

02:54:33.000 --> 02:54:36.000
[Guest]: But there's no intent issue.

02:54:36.000 --> 02:54:38.000
[Guest]: They want to do good.

02:54:38.000 --> 02:54:39.000
[Guest]: What they believe is good,

02:54:39.000 --> 02:54:41.000
[Guest]: may be different from what you believe is good.

02:54:41.000 --> 02:54:44.000
[Amit Varma]: This is a classic example of the seen and the unseen,

02:54:44.000 --> 02:54:45.000
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that,

02:54:45.000 --> 02:54:46.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:54:46.000 --> 02:54:47.000
[Amit Varma]: all of these kids who are,

02:54:47.000 --> 02:54:48.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:54:48.000 --> 02:54:50.000
[Amit Varma]: working with you and going on to all these different things,

02:54:50.000 --> 02:54:51.000
[Amit Varma]: will one day run the country,

02:54:51.000 --> 02:54:52.000
[Amit Varma]: hopefully.

02:54:52.000 --> 02:54:55.000
[Amit Varma]: And that'll have a massive social impact.

02:54:55.000 --> 02:54:57.000
[Amit Varma]: But I'll move from the social to the personal for a moment.

02:54:57.000 --> 02:54:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I find it fascinating how,

02:54:59.000 --> 02:55:01.000
[Amit Varma]: what people choose to do,

02:55:01.000 --> 02:55:03.000
[Amit Varma]: can shape who they are,

02:55:03.000 --> 02:55:04.000
[Amit Varma]: can change them.

02:55:04.000 --> 02:55:06.000
[Amit Varma]: And I see a lot of this in my own life,

02:55:06.000 --> 02:55:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and I've written about this as well.

02:55:08.000 --> 02:55:09.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting to me how,

02:55:09.000 --> 02:55:11.000
[Amit Varma]: you shift from,

02:55:11.000 --> 02:55:12.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:55:12.000 --> 02:55:14.000
[Amit Varma]: your corporate career to doing PRS.

02:55:14.000 --> 02:55:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And when you do something like this,

02:55:16.000 --> 02:55:18.000
[Amit Varma]: you're always playing the long game.

02:55:18.000 --> 02:55:19.000
[Unknown]: You know,

02:55:19.000 --> 02:55:20.000
[Amit Varma]: you're always,

02:55:20.000 --> 02:55:22.000
[Amit Varma]: you're just focused on the process.

02:55:22.000 --> 02:55:24.000
[Amit Varma]: You can't look at immediate results of things.

02:55:24.000 --> 02:55:26.000
[Amit Varma]: There might be periods of time where nothing is happening,

02:55:26.000 --> 02:55:27.000
[Amit Varma]: where you wonder,

02:55:27.000 --> 02:55:28.000
[Amit Varma]: is it worth it?

02:55:28.000 --> 02:55:30.000
[Amit Varma]: But I guess you train yourself to be process oriented,

02:55:30.000 --> 02:55:32.000
[Amit Varma]: and say that I'm just going to keep on doing this,

02:55:32.000 --> 02:55:34.000
[Amit Varma]: and have faith in the long run,

02:55:34.000 --> 02:55:35.000
[Amit Varma]: in the long game.

02:55:35.000 --> 02:55:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And I would imagine that,

02:55:36.000 --> 02:55:38.000
[Amit Varma]: this would have to change you as a person,

02:55:38.000 --> 02:55:41.000
[Amit Varma]: in terms of getting more tear off,

02:55:41.000 --> 02:55:42.000
[Amit Varma]: having more patience,

02:55:42.000 --> 02:55:44.000
[Amit Varma]: being less impatient,

02:55:44.000 --> 02:55:46.000
[Amit Varma]: even being less material,

02:55:46.000 --> 02:55:47.000
[Amit Varma]: all of these things.

02:55:47.000 --> 02:55:48.000
[Amit Varma]: So when you sort of,

02:55:48.000 --> 02:55:50.000
[Amit Varma]: if I might ask you to reflect,

02:55:50.000 --> 02:55:51.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:55:51.000 --> 02:55:53.000
[Amit Varma]: do you think you're a different person now,

02:55:53.000 --> 02:55:54.000
[Amit Varma]: than you would have been,

02:55:54.000 --> 02:55:56.000
[Amit Varma]: had you continued in banking,

02:55:56.000 --> 02:55:58.000
[Amit Varma]: or continued in your corporate career?

02:55:58.000 --> 02:55:59.000
[Amit Varma]: And if so,

02:55:59.000 --> 02:56:01.000
[Amit Varma]: what are those differences?

02:56:01.000 --> 02:56:03.000
[Guest]: I actually don't know,

02:56:03.000 --> 02:56:04.000
[Guest]: to be frank.

02:56:04.000 --> 02:56:05.000
[Guest]: Because,

02:56:05.000 --> 02:56:07.000
[Guest]: perhaps I'm more patient,

02:56:07.000 --> 02:56:08.000
[Guest]: I don't know,

02:56:08.000 --> 02:56:09.000
[Guest]: but people who work with me,

02:56:09.000 --> 02:56:11.000
[Guest]: probably will disagree with me.

02:56:11.000 --> 02:56:12.000
[Guest]: Because,

02:56:12.000 --> 02:56:13.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:56:13.000 --> 02:56:15.000
[Guest]: one's own evaluation of oneself,

02:56:15.000 --> 02:56:17.000
[Guest]: will be very different from what others think of you.

02:56:17.000 --> 02:56:19.000
[Guest]: I don't think I have had a significant,

02:56:19.000 --> 02:56:20.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:56:20.000 --> 02:56:21.000
[Guest]: obviously,

02:56:21.000 --> 02:56:22.000
[Guest]: my income in banking,

02:56:22.000 --> 02:56:24.000
[Guest]: would have been a multiple of what I get now.

02:56:24.000 --> 02:56:25.000
[Guest]: But,

02:56:25.000 --> 02:56:26.000
[Guest]: all that would have,

02:56:26.000 --> 02:56:27.000
[Guest]: I have not changed my lifestyle.

02:56:27.000 --> 02:56:30.000
[Guest]: It was never very expensive,

02:56:30.000 --> 02:56:32.000
[Guest]: even when I was earning a lot of money.

02:56:32.000 --> 02:56:34.000
[Guest]: I'm comfortable with a particular set of lifestyle.

02:56:34.000 --> 02:56:35.000
[Guest]: I have not changed it.

02:56:35.000 --> 02:56:36.000
[Guest]: All it would have mattered is,

02:56:36.000 --> 02:56:38.000
[Guest]: my bank balance would have been different.

02:56:38.000 --> 02:56:39.000
[Guest]: How does that,

02:56:39.000 --> 02:56:40.000
[Guest]: but,

02:56:40.000 --> 02:56:41.000
[Guest]: my,

02:56:41.000 --> 02:56:42.000
[Guest]: the way I look at it is,

02:56:42.000 --> 02:56:44.000
[Guest]: the only value of a bank balance,

02:56:44.000 --> 02:56:46.000
[Guest]: is the amount it goes down by,

02:56:46.000 --> 02:56:47.000
[Guest]: which means you're spending.

02:56:47.000 --> 02:56:49.000
[Guest]: If you're not spending it,

02:56:49.000 --> 02:56:51.000
[Guest]: what's the point of having that number,

02:56:51.000 --> 02:56:52.000
[Guest]: in an account somewhere?

02:56:52.000 --> 02:56:53.000
[Unknown]: Yeah.

02:56:53.000 --> 02:56:54.000
[Guest]: Value of money is,

02:56:54.000 --> 02:56:56.000
[Guest]: when you spend it.

02:56:56.000 --> 02:56:57.000
[Guest]: And,

02:56:57.000 --> 02:56:58.000
[Guest]: if I have more than what I need to spend,

02:56:58.000 --> 02:57:00.000
[Guest]: then the remaining is irrelevant.

02:57:00.000 --> 02:57:01.000
[Guest]: So,

02:57:01.000 --> 02:57:02.000
[Guest]: I don't think,

02:57:02.000 --> 02:57:03.000
[Guest]: it has changed me materially,

02:57:03.000 --> 02:57:05.000
[Guest]: in any particular way.

02:57:05.000 --> 02:57:06.000
[Guest]: Oh,

02:57:06.000 --> 02:57:08.000
[Guest]: because I continue doing that.

02:57:08.000 --> 02:57:09.000
[Unknown]: So,

02:57:09.000 --> 02:57:10.000
[Guest]: I actually don't know.

02:57:10.000 --> 02:57:11.000
[Unknown]: Fair enough.

02:57:11.000 --> 02:57:12.000
[Guest]: So,

02:57:12.000 --> 02:57:14.000
[Guest]: it has definitely helped me appreciate,

02:57:14.000 --> 02:57:15.000
[Guest]: the,

02:57:15.000 --> 02:57:16.000
[Guest]: that the world is way,

02:57:16.000 --> 02:57:19.000
[Guest]: way more complex than what I would have thought.

02:57:19.000 --> 02:57:20.000
[Guest]: Because,

02:57:20.000 --> 02:57:22.000
[Guest]: and it has also helped me,

02:57:22.000 --> 02:57:23.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:57:23.000 --> 02:57:24.000
[Guest]: or rather I would say,

02:57:24.000 --> 02:57:25.000
[Guest]: enabled me,

02:57:25.000 --> 02:57:27.000
[Guest]: meet a much larger,

02:57:27.000 --> 02:57:28.000
[Guest]: cross section of people.

02:57:28.000 --> 02:57:29.000
[Guest]: For example,

02:57:29.000 --> 02:57:31.000
[Guest]: I guess what you do,

02:57:31.000 --> 02:57:32.000
[Guest]: one of the pleasures,

02:57:32.000 --> 02:57:33.000
[Guest]: and I share that pleasure,

02:57:33.000 --> 02:57:34.000
[Guest]: is the fact that,

02:57:34.000 --> 02:57:36.000
[Guest]: I get to meet interesting people.

02:57:36.000 --> 02:57:37.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

02:57:37.000 --> 02:57:38.000
[Guest]: I get to meet a lot of interesting people,

02:57:38.000 --> 02:57:40.000
[Guest]: which I would not have done.

02:57:40.000 --> 02:57:41.000
[Guest]: So,

02:57:41.000 --> 02:57:43.000
[Guest]: my old banking circle,

02:57:43.000 --> 02:57:46.000
[Guest]: there are a lot of interesting people,

02:57:46.000 --> 02:57:47.000
[Guest]: but I can continue to meet them,

02:57:47.000 --> 02:57:49.000
[Guest]: and I can continue to meet others,

02:57:49.000 --> 02:57:50.000
[Guest]: I would not have met them there.

02:57:50.000 --> 02:57:51.000
[Guest]: So,

02:57:51.000 --> 02:57:53.000
[Guest]: it's a larger and wider circle.

02:57:53.000 --> 02:57:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah,

02:57:54.000 --> 02:57:55.000
[Amit Varma]: that's wonderful,

02:57:55.000 --> 02:57:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and you're spot on about,

02:57:56.000 --> 02:57:57.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:57:57.000 --> 02:57:59.000
[Amit Varma]: that being one of the perks of what I do as well.

02:57:59.000 --> 02:58:00.000
[Amit Varma]: My final question,

02:58:00.000 --> 02:58:01.000
[Amit Varma]: and this won't,

02:58:01.000 --> 02:58:03.000
[Amit Varma]: this doesn't need reflection,

02:58:03.000 --> 02:58:04.000
[Amit Varma]: it's not a difficult question,

02:58:04.000 --> 02:58:06.000
[Amit Varma]: but it's a question I ask my guests at the end of every show,

02:58:06.000 --> 02:58:07.000
[Amit Varma]: because my listeners love to read.

02:58:07.000 --> 02:58:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Contrary to,

02:58:08.000 --> 02:58:09.000
[Amit Varma]: you know,

02:58:09.000 --> 02:58:10.000
[Amit Varma]: the impression people have,

02:58:10.000 --> 02:58:11.000
[Amit Varma]: that people don't read today,

02:58:11.000 --> 02:58:13.000
[Amit Varma]: people have short attention spans.

02:58:13.000 --> 02:58:14.000
[Amit Varma]: I've realized doing this show,

02:58:14.000 --> 02:58:15.000
[Amit Varma]: that's really not true.

02:58:15.000 --> 02:58:16.000
[Amit Varma]: There's in fact,

02:58:16.000 --> 02:58:17.000
[Amit Varma]: even a meme where,

02:58:17.000 --> 02:58:18.000
[Amit Varma]: people will post books,

02:58:18.000 --> 02:58:19.000
[Amit Varma]: they discovered on the show,

02:58:19.000 --> 02:58:20.000
[Amit Varma]: as seen unseen bookshelves,

02:58:20.000 --> 02:58:22.000
[Amit Varma]: and all that on Twitter.

02:58:22.000 --> 02:58:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So,

02:58:23.000 --> 02:58:25.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to ask you to recommend books,

02:58:25.000 --> 02:58:27.000
[Amit Varma]: which either mean a lot to you,

02:58:27.000 --> 02:58:28.000
[Amit Varma]: or you read recently,

02:58:28.000 --> 02:58:29.000
[Amit Varma]: and were impressed by,

02:58:29.000 --> 02:58:30.000
[Amit Varma]: or that you love so much,

02:58:30.000 --> 02:58:32.000
[Amit Varma]: that you just want to stand on a stool,

02:58:32.000 --> 02:58:33.000
[Amit Varma]: and tell people,

02:58:33.000 --> 02:58:34.000
[Amit Varma]: you have to read this,

02:58:34.000 --> 02:58:35.000
[Amit Varma]: please read this.

02:58:35.000 --> 02:58:38.000
[Guest]: I do read a lot of pulp fiction,

02:58:38.000 --> 02:58:39.000
[Guest]: or whatever,

02:58:39.000 --> 02:58:40.000
[Guest]: junk.

02:58:40.000 --> 02:58:43.000
[Amit Varma]: I would not call any writing junk.

02:58:43.000 --> 02:58:44.000
[Guest]: I won't call it that,

02:58:44.000 --> 02:58:45.000
[Amit Varma]: people call it that,

02:58:45.000 --> 02:58:46.000
[Amit Varma]: because I read that.

02:58:46.000 --> 02:58:49.000
[Guest]: So, I did a binge reading,

02:58:49.000 --> 02:58:50.000
[Guest]: last month,

02:58:50.000 --> 02:58:52.000
[Guest]: I think I spent a lot of time on it,

02:58:52.000 --> 02:58:53.000
[Guest]: on,

02:58:53.000 --> 02:58:55.000
[Guest]: I don't know whether you have read,

02:58:55.000 --> 02:58:56.000
[Guest]: Lee Child,

02:58:56.000 --> 02:58:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and Jack Reacher.

02:58:57.000 --> 02:58:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, of course.

02:58:58.000 --> 02:58:59.000
[Amit Varma]: I think the new book is out.

02:58:59.000 --> 02:59:00.000
[Amit Varma]: No, I haven't read the new one,

02:59:00.000 --> 02:59:01.000
[Guest]: but there is a,

02:59:01.000 --> 02:59:03.000
[Guest]: another guy I discovered last month,

02:59:03.000 --> 02:59:05.000
[Guest]: but he's been writing for a few years,

02:59:05.000 --> 02:59:06.000
[Guest]: Mark Greeney.

02:59:06.000 --> 02:59:08.000
[Guest]: The character is Cotland Gentry,

02:59:08.000 --> 02:59:10.000
[Guest]: the gray man is the first book.

02:59:10.000 --> 02:59:12.000
[Guest]: So, he is about five foot seven,

02:59:12.000 --> 02:59:13.000
[Guest]: or something,

02:59:13.000 --> 02:59:15.000
[Guest]: and he has incredible ability,

02:59:15.000 --> 02:59:17.000
[Guest]: to just merge into the background,

02:59:17.000 --> 02:59:19.000
[Guest]: and when people are following him,

02:59:19.000 --> 02:59:20.000
[Guest]: it's like CIA type.

02:59:20.000 --> 02:59:22.000
[Guest]: But he makes Jack Reacher,

02:59:22.000 --> 02:59:24.000
[Guest]: look like a nobody.

02:59:24.000 --> 02:59:26.000
[Guest]: So, he's like a super, super hero.

02:59:26.000 --> 02:59:27.000
[Guest]: He's like Rajinikanth,

02:59:27.000 --> 02:59:28.000
[Guest]: plus Mithun Chakraborty.

02:59:28.000 --> 02:59:29.000
[Guest]: Okay.

02:59:29.000 --> 02:59:30.000
[Guest]: So, I write,

02:59:30.000 --> 02:59:31.000
[Guest]: so, good fun.

02:59:31.000 --> 02:59:32.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:59:32.000 --> 02:59:33.000
[Guest]: I like reading this.

02:59:33.000 --> 02:59:34.000
[Guest]: I, of course,

02:59:34.000 --> 02:59:36.000
[Guest]: my comfort reading,

02:59:36.000 --> 02:59:37.000
[Guest]: when I'm,

02:59:37.000 --> 02:59:38.000
[Guest]: generally,

02:59:38.000 --> 02:59:39.000
[Guest]: a bit down,

02:59:39.000 --> 02:59:40.000
[Guest]: and I want,

02:59:40.000 --> 02:59:41.000
[Guest]: before going to sleep,

02:59:41.000 --> 02:59:42.000
[Guest]: something which will,

02:59:42.000 --> 02:59:43.000
[Guest]: get me a smile,

02:59:43.000 --> 02:59:44.000
[Guest]: and I go back to sleep,

02:59:44.000 --> 02:59:46.000
[Guest]: is re-read a PJ Wodehouse.

02:59:46.000 --> 02:59:47.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

02:59:47.000 --> 02:59:48.000
[Unknown]: PJ Wodehouse.

02:59:48.000 --> 02:59:49.000
[Guest]: Anytime,

02:59:49.000 --> 02:59:50.000
[Guest]: go back,

02:59:50.000 --> 02:59:51.000
[Guest]: PJ Wodehouse is the all-time,

02:59:51.000 --> 02:59:52.000
[Guest]: repeat favorite.

02:59:52.000 --> 02:59:54.000
[Amit Varma]: It's comfort food for our generation,

02:59:54.000 --> 02:59:55.000
[Guest]: I think.

02:59:55.000 --> 02:59:56.000
[Guest]: Yeah,

02:59:56.000 --> 02:59:57.000
[Guest]: and you just keep laughing,

02:59:57.000 --> 02:59:58.000
[Guest]: and then,

02:59:58.000 --> 02:59:59.000
[Guest]: I mean,

02:59:59.000 --> 03:00:00.000
[Guest]: and even if I re-read,

03:00:00.000 --> 03:00:01.000
[Guest]: I spot things,

03:00:01.000 --> 03:00:02.000
[Guest]: which I missed the last time,

03:00:02.000 --> 03:00:03.000
[Unknown]: in his wordplay.

03:00:03.000 --> 03:00:04.000
[Guest]: Sometimes,

03:00:04.000 --> 03:00:05.000
[Guest]: I mean,

03:00:05.000 --> 03:00:06.000
[Guest]: I forget.

03:00:06.000 --> 03:00:07.000
[Guest]: So,

03:00:07.000 --> 03:00:08.000
[Guest]: he's remarkable.

03:00:08.000 --> 03:00:09.000
[Guest]: So,

03:00:09.000 --> 03:00:10.000
[Guest]: PJ Wodehouse,

03:00:10.000 --> 03:00:11.000
[Guest]: of course,

03:00:11.000 --> 03:00:12.000
[Guest]: and then,

03:00:12.000 --> 03:00:13.000
[Guest]: a lot of,

03:00:13.000 --> 03:00:14.000
[Guest]: last year,

03:00:14.000 --> 03:00:15.000
[Guest]: a couple of years back,

03:00:15.000 --> 03:00:16.000
[Guest]: one of the better,

03:00:16.000 --> 03:00:17.000
[Guest]: science fiction books,

03:00:17.000 --> 03:00:18.000
[Guest]: that I enjoyed reading.

03:00:18.000 --> 03:00:19.000
[Guest]: I actually,

03:00:19.000 --> 03:00:20.000
[Guest]: used to read science fiction,

03:00:20.000 --> 03:00:21.000
[Guest]: a lot,

03:00:21.000 --> 03:00:22.000
[Guest]: then I,

03:00:22.000 --> 03:00:23.000
[Guest]: I don't like the,

03:00:23.000 --> 03:00:24.000
[Unknown]: science fantasy.

03:00:24.000 --> 03:00:25.000
[Guest]: Yeah.

03:00:25.000 --> 03:00:26.000
[Unknown]: I like the more,

03:00:26.000 --> 03:00:27.000
[Guest]: fiction types.

03:00:27.000 --> 03:00:28.000
[Guest]: So,

03:00:28.000 --> 03:00:29.000
[Guest]: I mean,

03:00:29.000 --> 03:00:30.000
[Guest]: the Asimov,

03:00:30.000 --> 03:00:31.000
[Unknown]: Clarke genre,

03:00:31.000 --> 03:00:32.000
[Guest]: rather than the more,

03:00:32.000 --> 03:00:33.000
[Guest]: fantasy genre.

03:00:33.000 --> 03:00:34.000
[Guest]: This,

03:00:34.000 --> 03:00:35.000
[Guest]: the three-body problem,

